(16, 'inline_html', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp; Combustion is a process in which heat is released when organic molecules are burnt :</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\star $ &nbsp;Take some amount of sugar on a tin foil and heat it. Sugar burns, carbondioxide and water are produced and energy is released as heat. This process is clled Combustion.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp; Combustion and Respiration have a few things in common</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\star $ &nbsp;Both these process require oxygen and energy is produced.</p>\n\n<p><span style="line-height:1.6em">&nbsp;</span><span style="line-height:1.6em">$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span style="line-height:1.6em">In combustion, sugar first chars and later burns producing flame which is not seen in respiration.</span></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp; In respiration, several intermediates are produced and in combustion there are no such intermediates.</p>\n', 'Comparision of Respiration with Chemicaal combustion.', 'Both combustion and respiration require oxygen and release energy', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp; Combustion is a process in which heat is released when organic molecules are burnt :</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\star $ &nbsp;Take some amount of sugar on a tin foil and heat it. Sugar burns, carbondioxide and water are produced and energy is released as heat. This process is clled Combustion.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp; Combustion and Respiration have a few things in common</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\star $ &nbsp;Both these process require oxygen and energy is produced.</p>\n\n<p><span style="line-height:1.6em">&nbsp;</span><span style="line-height:1.6em">$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span style="line-height:1.6em">In combustion, sugar first chars and later burns producing flame which is not seen in respiration.</span></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp; In respiration, several intermediates are produced and in combustion there are no such intermediates.</p>\n', 0, 0),
(17, 'inline_html', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Glycolysis is the first step in respiration, which is common in all types of respiration.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\star $ &nbsp;Glucose is the most commonly used sugar for deriving energy in plants, animals and in micro-organisms</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\star $ &nbsp;Glucose is oxidized in two stages. Glucose has six carbon atoms and glucose is converted into two molecules of pyruvic acid.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\star $ &nbsp;This process ocurrs even in absence of&nbsp;oxygen and carbon dioxide is not produced. This process is common in aerobic and anaerobic respiration and is commonly called as Glycolysis.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Oxidation of pyruvic acid to carbon dioxide depends on oxygen availability.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;In the absence of oxygen, yeast cells convert the pyruvic acid into ethanol and this process is called Fermentation.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\overset{ Oxygen &nbsp;present}{\\rightarrow} $ &nbsp; $ CO_{2} $ + $ H_{2} O$ &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Starch&nbsp;$ &nbsp;\\to &nbsp;$ Sugars&nbsp;$ \\overset{Glycolysis}{\\rightarrow} $ Pyruvic acid&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\overset{Oxygen &nbsp;absent}{\\rightarrow} $ &nbsp;$ C_{2} $$ H_{5} $OH &nbsp;+&nbsp;$ CO_{2} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&