(18, 'inline_html', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Oxidation of glucose release energy and heat&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\star $ &nbsp;Some amount of energy produced during glucose oxidation is in the form of heat and keeps thebody warm.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\star $ &nbsp;Rest of energy is stored in a compund called ATP.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;ATP &nbsp;$ &nbsp;\\to $ &nbsp;ADP + Inorganic phosphate + energy</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;The process of addition of high energy phosphate to ADP to form ATP is called Phosphorylation.</p>\n', 'Formation of ATP and its utilization for different purposes', 'ATP provides energy for various reactions and functions in the organism.', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Oxidation of glucose release energy and heat&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\star $ &nbsp;Some amount of energy produced during glucose oxidation is in the form of heat and keeps thebody warm.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\star $ &nbsp;Rest of energy is stored in a compund called ATP.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;ATP &nbsp;$ &nbsp;\\to $ &nbsp;ADP + Inorganic phosphate + energy</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;The process of addition of high energy phosphate to ADP to form ATP is called Phosphorylation.</p>\n', 0, 0),
(19, 'inline_html', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Substances which are oxidised in the body during respiration to produce energy are called Respiratory substrates</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Complex molecules need to be converted to simple molecules for oxidation.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\star $ &nbsp;Carbohydrates like starch and cellulose are complex molecules, these molecules are not oxidised directly to produce energy. First they are converted to simple sugars like glucose ocurrs during digestion of foof materials in digestive system.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $ \\star $ In these process, energy is not released.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Energy is produced when glucose or fatty acids are oxidised in the cells in a process called as cellular respiration.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Energy is released from glucose or fatyy acids in several stages</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;During respiration , energy is produced when glucose or fattyacids oxidised in cells, this process ocurrs in cells so this is called Cellular respiration.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Several products are formed before glucose or fatty acids are oxidised and they are called Metabolic intermediates.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Energy is not produced in each and every reaction during the oxidation of glucose or fatty acids.</p>\n', 'Basic pathways to release the energy are same in all organisms', 'Energy is released from glucose and fatty acids in several stages', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Substances which are oxidised in the body during respiration to produce energy are called Respiratory substrates</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Complex molecules need to be converted to simple molecules for oxidation.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\star $ &nbsp;Carbohydrates like starch and cellulose are complex molecules, these molecules are not oxidised directly to produce energy. First they are converted to simple sugars like glucose ocurrs during digestion of foof materials in digestive system.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $ \\star $ In these process, energy is not released.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Energy is produced when glucose or fatty acids are oxidised in the cells in a process called as cellular respiration.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Energy is released from glucose or fatyy acids in several stages</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;During respiration , energy is produced when glucose or fattyacids oxidised in cells, this process ocurrs in cells so this is called Cellular respiration.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Several products are formed before glucose or fatty acids are oxidised and they are called Metabolic intermediates.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Energy is not produced in each and every reaction during the oxidation of glucose or fatty acids.</p>\n', 0, 0),
(20, 'inline_html', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Mitochondria are absent in prokaryotes.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Mitochondria are known as the power house of the cell.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Mitochondria can be seen in only under microscope.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Mitochondria have two compartments : inner compartment and outer compartment.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Inner membrane of mitochondria has several inward projections called cristae.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;On the inner membrane large number of elementary particles are present.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Outer membrane has no projections.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp; Inner membrane, matrix and elementary particlesin the mitochondria have large number of engymes required for the respiration and energy production.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Mitochondria are the sites of cellular respiration', 'Mitochondria is known as the power house of the cell.', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Mitochondria are absent in prokaryotes.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Mitochondria are known as the power house of the cell.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Mitochondria can be seen in only under microscope.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Mitochondria have two compartments : inner compartment and outer compartment.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Inner membrane of mitochondria has several inward projections called cristae.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;On the inner membrane large number of elementary particles are present.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Outer membrane has no projections.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp; Inner membrane, matrix and elementary particlesin the mitochondria have large number of engymes required for the respiration and energy production.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 0, 0),
(21, 'inline_html', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Glucose is oxidised in two stages. The&nbsp;first stage &nbsp;is<strong> Glycolysis</strong> ( Glyco = sugar, Lysis = breaking down) in which glucose molecule is converted into two pyruvic acid molecules</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;In glycolysis, two ATPs are utilised and 4 ATPs are produced , with a net gainof 2 ATPs.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Two molecules of NADH are also formed in glycolysis.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ When oxygen is available, the pyruvic acid molecules are converted into acetyl coenzyme A with the release of one molecule of carbon dioxide.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ The two carbons of acetyl coenzyme A are oxidised in Krebs Cycle to two molecules carbon dioxide</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;In <strong>Krebs cycle</strong>, the hydrogens along with electrons are transferred from acetyl coenzyme A to&nbsp;$ NAD^{+} $ and&nbsp;$ FAD^{+} $ resulting in the formation of NADH and&nbsp;$ FADH_{2} $</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Oxidation of <strong>NADH</strong> and&nbsp;$ FADH_{2} $ &nbsp;produces large amounts of enrgy</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;For each molecule of acetyl coengyme A ( pyruvic acid ) oxidised, four molecules of NADH and one molecule of&nbsp;$ FADH_{2} $ are formed.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ <strong>NADH&nbsp;</strong>and&nbsp;$ FADH_{2} $ &nbsp;are oxidised in the elementary particles of mitochondria, through a process known as Electron Transport Energy released during this process is used for the production of ATP.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Protons and electrons are finally transferred to Oxygen to form water.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;The transfer of phosphate group in the presence of oxygen is referred to as oxidative phosphorylation.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;A net gain of 38 ATP molecules are formed from the total oxidation of one glucose molecule through glycolysis, krebs cycle and electron transport.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Each ATP molecule gives 7,600 calories of energy.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ 40 % of the total energy present in &nbsp;the glucose molecule is converted into ATP energy.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Glycolysis, Krebs cycle and Electron transport', 'Glucose is oxidised to carbon dioxide and water snd energy is produced.', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Glucose is oxidised in two stages. The&nbsp;first stage &nbsp;is<strong> Glycolysis</strong> ( Glyco = sugar, Lysis = breaking down) in which glucose molecule is converted into two pyruvic acid molecules</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;In glycolysis, two ATPs are utilised and 4 ATPs are produced , with a net gainof 2 ATPs.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Two molecules of NADH are also formed in glycolysis.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ When oxygen is available, the pyruvic acid molecules are converted into acetyl coenzyme A with the release of one molecule of carbon dioxide.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ The two carbons of acetyl coenzyme A are oxidised in Krebs Cycle to two molecules carbon dioxide</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;In <strong>Krebs cycle</strong>, the hydrogens along with electrons are transferred from acetyl coenzyme A to&nbsp;$ NAD^{+} $ and&nbsp;$ FAD^{+} $ resulting in the formation of NADH and&nbsp;$ FADH_{2} $</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Oxidation of <strong>NADH</strong> and&nbsp;$ FADH_{2} $ &nbsp;produces large amounts of enrgy</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;For each molecule of acetyl coengyme A ( pyruvic acid ) oxidised, four molecules of NADH and one molecule of&nbsp;$ FADH_{2} $ are formed.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ <strong>NADH&nbsp;</strong>and&nbsp;$ FADH_{2} $ &nbsp;are oxidised in the elementary particles of mitochondria, through a process known as Electron Transport Energy released during this process is used for the production of ATP.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Protons and electrons are finally transferred to Oxygen to form water.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;The transfer of phosphate group in the presence of oxygen is referred to as oxidative phosphorylation.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;A net gain of 38 ATP molecules are formed from the total oxidation of one glucose molecule through glycolysis, krebs cycle and electron transport.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Each ATP molecule gives 7,600 calories of energy.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ 40 % of the total energy present in &nbsp;the glucose molecule is converted into ATP energy.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 0, 0),
(22, 'inline_html', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Factors controlling respiration are important as they help us to presevrve fruits, vegetables and other food items.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Designing proper drugs to control respiration which may be used for the treatment of several diseases and also control pest and pasrasite infections.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Oxygen in an important factor in the control of respiration.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;In the absence of oxygen, NADH and&nbsp;$ FADH_{2} $ &nbsp;are not oxidised and ATP is not produced. Several bacteria produce lactic acid in the absence of oxygen.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Respiration ocurrs both under aerobic and anerobic conditions</p>\n', 'Factors controlling respiration', 'The factors controlling the respiration are important to preserve fruits, vegetables and food items.', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Factors controlling respiration are important as they help us to presevrve fruits, vegetables and other food items.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Designing proper drugs to control respiration which may be used for the treatment of several diseases and also control pest and pasrasite infections.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Oxygen in an important factor in the control of respiration.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;In the absence of oxygen, NADH and&nbsp;$ FADH_{2} $ &nbsp;are not oxidised and ATP is not produced. Several bacteria produce lactic acid in the absence of oxygen.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Respiration ocurrs both under aerobic and anerobic conditions</p>\n', 0, 0),
(23, 'inline_html', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Temperature is an important factor in the control of respiration rate.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;The temperature at which the rate of repiration is maximum is called <strong>Optimum temperature.</strong></p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ At temperature above and below the optimal temperature, the rate of respiration decreases.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ At low temperatures, enzymes are not active therefore respiration rate will be very low and is used to preserve food materials in refrigerators .</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Heat energy is liberated during respiration.</p>\n', 'Temperature is critical for respiaration', '', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Temperature is an important factor in the control of respiration rate.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;The temperature at which the rate of repiration is maximum is called <strong>Optimum temperature.</strong></p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ At temperature above and below the optimal temperature, the rate of respiration decreases.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ At low temperatures, enzymes are not active therefore respiration rate will be very low and is used to preserve food materials in refrigerators .</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Heat energy is liberated during respiration.</p>\n', 0, 0);
