(28, 'inline_html', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Insects have a thick, hard impervious covering called cuticle which serves as a skeleton and it is called as Exoskeleton.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Insects have adopted a different type of respiratory system called Tracheal system</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Tracheal system has a tube like trachea which open out through spiracles. Spiracles are pores on the sides of the body of cockroach.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Each spiracle open into a small chamber called Atrium</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Trachea branch into tracheoles which enter the tissues.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Air moves in and out of the trachea due to contraction and relaxation of abdominal muscles.</p>\n', 'Tracheal respiration', 'Tracheal respiration is seen in cockroach.', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Insects have a thick, hard impervious covering called cuticle which serves as a skeleton and it is called as Exoskeleton.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Insects have adopted a different type of respiratory system called Tracheal system</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Tracheal system has a tube like trachea which open out through spiracles. Spiracles are pores on the sides of the body of cockroach.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Each spiracle open into a small chamber called Atrium</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Trachea branch into tracheoles which enter the tissues.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Air moves in and out of the trachea due to contraction and relaxation of abdominal muscles.</p>\n', 0, 0),
(29, 'inline_html', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Some aqutic animals have developed special organs for respiration which are known as gills.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;In all the fishes the incoming stream of water enters through its mouth and flows over through the gills.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;There is very little resemblance in the structure of gills in different animal phyla.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Respiratory system of fishes consists of internal branchial, external branchial and branchial pouches.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Mechanism of respiration in fish :&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Flow of water from outside&nbsp;$ \\overset{}{\\rightarrow} $ mouth $ \\overset{}{\\rightarrow} $ oral activity $ \\overset{}{\\rightarrow} $ &nbsp;pharynx $ \\overset{}{\\rightarrow} $ &nbsp;internal branchial aperture $ \\overset{}{\\rightarrow} $ &nbsp;gill pouch $ \\overset{}{\\rightarrow} $ external branchial aperture $ \\overset{}{\\rightarrow} $ &nbsp;outside.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Continuous opening and closing of mouth by a fish is to draw water in to the oral activity.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Gills pouches are connected to pharynx, through internal branchial apertures and open out through external branchial apertures.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Branchial ( Gill ) Respiration - Fishes', '', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Some aqutic animals have developed special organs for respiration which are known as gills.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;In all the fishes the incoming stream of water enters through its mouth and flows over through the gills.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;There is very little resemblance in the structure of gills in different animal phyla.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Respiratory system of fishes consists of internal branchial, external branchial and branchial pouches.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Mechanism of respiration in fish :&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Flow of water from outside&nbsp;$ \\overset{}{\\rightarrow} $ mouth $ \\overset{}{\\rightarrow} $ oral activity $ \\overset{}{\\rightarrow} $ &nbsp;pharynx $ \\overset{}{\\rightarrow} $ &nbsp;internal branchial aperture $ \\overset{}{\\rightarrow} $ &nbsp;gill pouch $ \\overset{}{\\rightarrow} $ external branchial aperture $ \\overset{}{\\rightarrow} $ &nbsp;outside.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Continuous opening and closing of mouth by a fish is to draw water in to the oral activity.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Gills pouches are connected to pharynx, through internal branchial apertures and open out through external branchial apertures.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n', 0, 0),
(30, 'inline_html', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Respiration through lungs is called pulmonary respiration.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Lungs are elastic bag like structures and are supplied with large number of blood vessels. This process is same in teresstrial vertibrates.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;During inspiration, volume of lungs is increased and during exhalation, volume of lungs is reduced.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Lungs in the vertebrates are made up of several thousands of small chambers called alveoli</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Animals add water vapour to the air before the air enters the lungs.</p>\n', 'Pulmonary respiration', 'Pulmonary respiration is same in all terrestrial vertebrates.', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Respiration through lungs is called pulmonary respiration.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Lungs are elastic bag like structures and are supplied with large number of blood vessels. This process is same in teresstrial vertibrates.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;During inspiration, volume of lungs is increased and during exhalation, volume of lungs is reduced.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Lungs in the vertebrates are made up of several thousands of small chambers called alveoli</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Animals add water vapour to the air before the air enters the lungs.</p>\n', 0, 0),
(31, 'inline_html', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Respiration systemin human beings consists of Nostrills, Nasal cavity, Internal nares, Pharynx, Larynx, Trachea, Bronchi and Bronchioles and Lungs.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Air is humidifies and its temperature is adjusted to that of body temperature, as it passes over the mucous layer of nasal cavities.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Two nostrills which open into the nasal cavity and there is a tube like structure behind each nostrill and these are seperated from one another by septum and a bony plate called palate.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><span style="line-height:1.6em">$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;From pharynx air enters the larynx, while food enters into oesophagus</span></p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Larynx is called the voice box</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Lungs are spongy, elastic structures enclosed by two membranes called pleura</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;During inspiration the volume of thorasic cavity increases. So the volume of lungs changes and as such air from out side enters the lungs.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Gas exchange occurs in the alveoli</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;During expiration the volume of thorasic cavity decreases. So the volume of lungs decreases and as such air from lungs goes out.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;In man, diaphragm plays a major role in the respiratory movements while in woman the ribs play a major role.</p>\n', 'Human respiration', 'Respiation in man occurs in two stages - inspiration and expiration.', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Respiration systemin human beings consists of Nostrills, Nasal cavity, Internal nares, Pharynx, Larynx, Trachea, Bronchi and Bronchioles and Lungs.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Air is humidifies and its temperature is adjusted to that of body temperature, as it passes over the mucous layer of nasal cavities.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Two nostrills which open into the nasal cavity and there is a tube like structure behind each nostrill and these are seperated from one another by septum and a bony plate called palate.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><span style="line-height:1.6em">$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;From pharynx air enters the larynx, while food enters into oesophagus</span></p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Larynx is called the voice box</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Lungs are spongy, elastic structures enclosed by two membranes called pleura</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;During inspiration the volume of thorasic cavity increases. So the volume of lungs changes and as such air from out side enters the lungs.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Gas exchange occurs in the alveoli</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;During expiration the volume of thorasic cavity decreases. So the volume of lungs decreases and as such air from lungs goes out.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;In man, diaphragm plays a major role in the respiratory movements while in woman the ribs play a major role.</p>\n', 0, 0),
(32, 'inline_html', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Photosynthesis occurs only in plants and respiration occurs in all living organisms.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Photosynthesis takes in place of light and respiration takes place through out the day and night.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Plants can survive without performing photosynthesis for a few days and no organism can survive without respiration for few minutes.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp; In photosynthesis, light energy is fixed for the synthesis of carbohydrates and in respiration food substances are broken down to release energy for cellular functions.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Photophosophorylation occurs in photosynthesis while oxidative phosphorylation occurs in respiration</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Chloroplast is the site of photosynthesis while respiration occurs in cytoplasm and mitochondria.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Oxygen is consumed in respiration and it is released during photosynthesis</p>\n', 'Comparision of photosynthesis and respiration', 'Photosynthesis is a anabolic process and respiration is a catabolic process', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Photosynthesis occurs only in plants and respiration occurs in all living organisms.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Photosynthesis takes in place of light and respiration takes place through out the day and night.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Plants can survive without performing photosynthesis for a few days and no organism can survive without respiration for few minutes.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp; In photosynthesis, light energy is fixed for the synthesis of carbohydrates and in respiration food substances are broken down to release energy for cellular functions.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Photophosophorylation occurs in photosynthesis while oxidative phosphorylation occurs in respiration</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Chloroplast is the site of photosynthesis while respiration occurs in cytoplasm and mitochondria.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Oxygen is consumed in respiration and it is released during photosynthesis</p>\n', 0, 0),
(33, 'inline_html', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Transport of goods is an important part of our living.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Transport systems are present in the bodies of all the organisms and they are essential to keep the cells alive and healthy.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Substances like oxygen and carbondioxide are to be transpoted with in the body.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Hormones need to be transported because they work at places other than where they are produced.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\star $ Harmones are the chemicals which control and co ordinate the functions.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $ \\star $ Pituatory galnd is located in the brain but the harmones it secretes work on ther galnds like adrenal glands.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Transport system has undergone evolutionary change in animals.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $ \\star $ &nbsp;In unicellular organismslike amoeba, transport of substance occurs within the cytoplasm either by diffusion or by movements of cytoplasm.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $ \\star $ &nbsp;Special fluids like blood and lymph were evolved for the transport of substances with in the body of multicellular organisms.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\star $ &nbsp;Animals developed circulatory systems with blood vessels to transport the fluids . Arteries carry substances to the cells and veins collect substances from cells.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Need for transport', '', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Transport of goods is an important part of our living.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Transport systems are present in the bodies of all the organisms and they are essential to keep the cells alive and healthy.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Substances like oxygen and carbondioxide are to be transpoted with in the body.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Hormones need to be transported because they work at places other than where they