(36, 'inline_html', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ Administering blood of one person to another person through the vein is called blood transfusion</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Mixing of blood samples of different blood groups results in clumping or agglutination</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ There are four blood groups recognized in human beings</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Blood group antigens are present on the membranes of RBC and blood group antibodies are present in the plasma.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ The people with blood group &#39;&#39;O&#39;&#39; do not have antigens on their red blood cells, there will not ba any clumping of red blood cells in &nbsp;the recipient. Therefore, people with &#39;&#39;O&#39;&#39; blood group are called Universal donors.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ People with blood group &#39;&#39;AB&#39;&#39; can recieve blood belonging to bllod groups &#39;&#39;A&#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;B&#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;AB&#39; and &#39;&#39;O&#39;&#39;.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ People with &#39;&#39;AB&#39;&#39; blood group are called Universal recipients.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Before blood transfusion, the patients blood is to be tested in laboratory. Recipients blood should match with donars blood.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Healthy people between 18 - 60 years of age can donate blood. The donor should not be suffering from any diseases at the time of donating the blood</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Blood collected from the donors can be stored in blood banks</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Blood groups and importance of blood doantion', '''''O'''' blood group is called Universal donors\n''''AB'''' blood group is called Universal recipients', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ Administering blood of one person to another person through the vein is called blood transfusion</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Mixing of blood samples of different blood groups results in clumping or agglutination</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ There are four blood groups recognized in human beings</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Blood group antigens are present on the membranes of RBC and blood group antibodies are present in the plasma.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ The people with blood group &#39;&#39;O&#39;&#39; do not have antigens on their red blood cells, there will not ba any clumping of red blood cells in &nbsp;the recipient. Therefore, people with &#39;&#39;O&#39;&#39; blood group are called Universal donors.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ People with blood group &#39;&#39;AB&#39;&#39; can recieve blood belonging to bllod groups &#39;&#39;A&#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;B&#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;AB&#39; and &#39;&#39;O&#39;&#39;.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ People with &#39;&#39;AB&#39;&#39; blood group are called Universal recipients.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Before blood transfusion, the patients blood is to be tested in laboratory. Recipients blood should match with donars blood.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Healthy people between 18 - 60 years of age can donate blood. The donor should not be suffering from any diseases at the time of donating the blood</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Blood collected from the donors can be stored in blood banks</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 0, 0),
(37, 'inline_html', '<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Blood is fluid connective tissue of the body</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;The study of blood is called Haemotology</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;The fluid present between the blood cells is called Plasma. In average adult, there is about 5 litres of blood.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Composition of blood can be studied by simple methods</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;The&nbsp;fluid that is remaining after blood clotting ( when we collect the blood without adding sodium oxalate ) is called serum.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Several inorganic ions like chloride, phosphate, sulphate, bicarbonate, sodium, potassium, calicium, and magnesium are present in the blood plasma.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;The organic components of the plasma are sugars, amino acids , fattyacids, urea, lipids, proteins etc.,</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Blood contins heparin, which prevents clotting of blood in the blood vessels.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Differenet types of proteins like albumin, globulin fibrinogen and prothrombin</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;Red blood cells or erthrocytes are most abundant in the blood</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ Organelles like nucleus, mitochondria, lysosomes, golgi complex, endoplasmic reticulum, ribosomes etc., are not present in mature RBC</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;The production of RBC is called erthropoiesis and RBC have special pigment in their cytoplasm called Heamoglobin.</p>\n\n<p><span style="line-height:1.6em">$ \\bigstar $ </span><span style="line-height:1.6em">Leukocytes are called as white blood cells and life span of WBC &nbsp;is 12 or 13 days.</span></p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ &nbsp;WBC are also called a phagocytes because they feed on the foreighn germs that enter the body .</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigstar $ In blood we find granulocytes like acidophils, basophils and neutrophils and agranulocytes like lymphocytes and monocytes.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $ \\star $ &nbsp;In acido phils the 