(56, 'inline_html', '<p><strong>Square Root of a Positive Rational Number</strong></p>\n\n<p>Let &#39;a&#39; be any positive rational number and we express&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ = b if and only if b&gt;0 and&nbsp;$ b^{2} $ = a&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>The value of &#39;b&#39; is called the &quot;positive square root&quot; of positive rational number &#39;a&#39; .</p>\n\n<p><strong>Density Property :</strong></p>\n\n<p>There are infinitely many irrational numbers between any two rational numbers,&nbsp;this property is known as density property.</p>\n\n<p>If &#39;a&#39; and &#39;b&#39; are two positive rational numbers such that ab is not a perfect square of a rational number , then&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{ab} $ is an irrational number lying between a and b.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; N$ \\subset $W$ \\subset $Z$ \\subset $Q$ \\subset $R &nbsp;,$ Q^{|} $$ \\subset $R</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Let a and b be positive real numbers , then</p>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp;1) $ \\sqrt{ab} $ =&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $$ \\sqrt{b} $</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp;2) $ \\sqrt{&nbsp;\\frac{a}{b}&nbsp;} $ =&nbsp;$ \\frac{&nbsp;\\sqrt{a} }{&nbsp;\\sqrt{b} } $ ; if b&nbsp;$ \\neq $0</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp;3) ($ \\sqrt{a} $+$ \\sqrt{b} $)($ \\sqrt{a} $-$ \\sqrt{b} $) = a - b</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp;4) (a+$ \\sqrt{b} $)(a-$ \\sqrt{b} $) =&nbsp;$ a^{2} $- b</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp;5) ($ \\sqrt{a} $+$ \\sqrt{b} $)($ \\sqrt{c} $+$ \\sqrt{d} $) =&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{ac} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{ad} $ &nbsp;+&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{bc} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{bd} $</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp;6)&nbsp;$ (&nbsp;\\sqrt{a} $+$ \\sqrt{b} )^{2} $ = a+b+2$ \\sqrt{ab} $.</div>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Properties of Square Roots Of Real Numbers', '', '<p><strong>Square Root of a Positive Rational Number</strong></p>\n\n<p>Let &#39;a&#39; be any positive rational number and we express&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ = b if and only if b&gt;0 and&nbsp;$ b^{2} $ = a&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>The value of &#39;b&#39; is called the &quot;positive square root&quot; of positive rational number &#39;a&#39; .</p>\n\n<p><strong>Density Property :</strong></p>\n\n<p>There are infinitely many irrational numbers between any two rational numbers,&nbsp;this property is known as density property.</p>\n\n<p>If &#39;a&#39; and &#39;b&#39; are two positive rational numbers such that ab is not a perfect square of a rational number , then&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{ab} $ is an irrational number lying between a and b.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; N$ \\subset $W$ \\subset $Z$ \\subset $Q$ \\subset $R &nbsp;,$ Q^{|} $$ \\subset $R</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Let a and b be positive real numbers , then</p>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp;1) $ \\sqrt{ab} $ =&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $$ \\sqrt{b} $</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp;2) $ \\sqrt{&nbsp;\\frac{a}{b}&nbsp;} $ =&nbsp;$ \\frac{&nbsp;\\sqrt{a} }{&nbsp;\\sqrt{b} } $ ; if b&nbsp;$ \\neq $0</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp;3) ($ \\sqrt{a} $+$ \\sqrt{b} $)($ \\sqrt{a} $-$ \\sqrt{b} $) = a - b</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp;4) (a+$ \\sqrt{b} $)(a-$ \\sqrt{b} $) =&nbsp;$ a^{2} $- b</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp;5) ($ \\sqrt{a} $+$ \\sqrt{b} $)($ \\sqrt{c} $+$ \\sqrt{d} $) =&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{ac} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{ad} $ &nbsp;+&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{bc} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{bd} $</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp;6)&nbsp;$ (&nbsp;\\sqrt{a} $+$ \\sqrt{b} )^{2} $ = a+b+2$ \\sqrt{ab} $.</div>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 0, 0),
(57, 'inline_html', '<p><strong>Surd:</strong></p>\n\n<p>If n is a positive integer and a rational number &nbsp;a(&gt;0) is not the $ n^{th} $ &nbsp;power of any other rational number , then&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ or&nbsp;$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n} &nbsp;} $ is called a &#39;surd&#39; or &#39;radical&#39; of order n.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Here &#39;a&#39; is called radicand&nbsp;.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{} $ is called radical sign</p>\n\n<p>n is called the degree of radical .</p>\n\n<p>$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $ is called an exponential form</p>\n\n<p>$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ is called radical form of surd.</p>\n\n<p>Ex :&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{2} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{3} $ ,&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{9} $ ,..... etc.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\sqrt{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\pi &nbsp; } $ is not a surd , since&nbsp;$ \\pi $ &nbsp;is an irrational number.</p>\n\n<p>If $ \\sqrt[n]{&nbsp;a^{n} &nbsp;} $ = a</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;If two surds a +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $ = c&nbsp;+&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{d} $ then&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; a = c and b = d</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ X&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{b} $ =&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{axb} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\sqrt[n]{a} }{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\sqrt[n]{b} } $ =&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{&nbsp;\\frac{a}{b} &nbsp;} $ where b$ \\neq $0</p>\n\n<p><strong>N th root of Real &nbsp;Number:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Let a&gt;0 be a real number and &#39;n&#39; be a positive integer. If&nbsp;$ b^{n} $ = a, for some positive real number &#39;b&#39; ,then bis called n th root of &#39;a&#39; and we write&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ = b</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; i.e.&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ = b &nbsp;; b =&nbsp;$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n} &nbsp;} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 'N th roots and Surds', '', '<p><strong>Surd:</strong></p>\n\n<p>If n is a positive integer and a rational number &nbsp;a(&gt;0) is not the $ n^{th} $ &nbsp;power of any other rational number , then&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ or&nbsp;$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n} &nbsp;} $ is called a &#39;surd&#39; or &#39;radical&#39; of order n.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Here &#39;a&#39; is called radicand&nbsp;.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{} $ is called radical sign</p>\n\n<p>n is called the degree of radical .</p>\n\n<p>$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $ is called an exponential form</p>\n\n<p>$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ is called radical form of surd.</p>\n\n<p>Ex :&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{2} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{3} $ ,&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{9} $ ,..... etc.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\sqrt{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\pi &nbsp; } $ is not a surd , since&nbsp;$ \\pi $ &nbsp;is an irrational number.</p>\n\n<p>If $ \\sqrt[n]{&nbsp;a^{n} &nbsp;} $ = a</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;If two surds a +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $ = c&nbsp;+&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{d} $ then&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; a = c and b = d</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ X&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{b} $ =&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{axb} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\sqrt[n]{a} }{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\sqrt[n]{b} } $ =&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{&nbsp;\\frac{a}{b} &nbsp;} $ where b$ \\neq $0</p>\n\n<p><strong>N th root of Real &nbsp;Number:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Let a&gt;0 be a real number and &#39;n&#39; be a positive integer. If&nbsp;$ b^{n} $ = a, for some positive real number &#39;b&#39; ,then bis called n th root of &#39;a&#39; and we write&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ = b</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; i.e.&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ = b &nbsp;; b =&nbsp;$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n} &nbsp;} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 0, 0),
(58, 'inline_html', '<h3>Vulgar Fraction:</h3>\n\n<p>A fraction whose denominator is a natural number , other than 10, 100, 1000 etc., is called Vulgar fraction.</p>\n', 'Vulgar fraction', '', '<h3>Vulgar Fraction:</h3>\n\n<p>A fraction whose denominator is a natural number , other than 10, 100, 1000 etc., is called Vulgar fraction.</p>\n', 0, 0),
(59, 'inline_html', '<h3>Proper&nbsp;Fraction:</h3>\n\n<p>A fraction in which numerator is less than the denominator is called a proper fraction.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp; Ex:&nbsp;$ \\frac{3}{7} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{4}{15} $ etc..</div>\n', 'Proper fraction', '', '<h3>Proper&nbsp;Fraction:</h3>\n\n<p>A fraction in which numerator is less than the denominator is called a proper fraction.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp; Ex:&nbsp;$ \\frac{3}{7} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{4}{15} $ etc..</div>\n', 0, 0),
(60, 'inline_html', '<h3>Improper Fraction:</h3>\n\n<p>A fraction in which numerator is greater than the denominator is called an improper function.</p>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Ex :&nbsp;$ \\frac{7}{3} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{8}{5} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{11}{7} $ etc .</div>\n', 'Improper fraction', '', '<h3>Improper Fraction:</h3>\n\n<p>A fraction in which numerator is greater than the denominator is called an improper function.</p>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Ex :&nbsp;$ \\frac{7}{3} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{8}{5} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{11}{7} $ etc .</div>\n', 0, 0),
(61, 'inline_html', '<h3><span style="line-height:1.2em">Mixed Fraction:</span></h3>\n\n<p>An improper fraction can be written as a combination of a whole and a past such fractions are called mixed fractions.</p>\n\n<div class="content-formula"><span style="line-height:1.6em">&nbsp;</span><span style="line-height:1.6em"> Ex : 2$ \\frac{1}{5} $ , 2$ \\frac{1}{3} $ etc..</span></div>\n', 'Mixed fraction', '', '<h3><span style="line-height:1.2em">Mixed Fraction:</span></h3>\n\n<p>An improper fraction can be written as a combination of a whole and a past such fractions are called mixed fractions.</p>\n\n<div class="content-formula"><span style="line-height:1.6em">&nbsp;</span><span style="line-height:1.6em"> Ex : 2$ \\frac{1}{5} $ , 2$ \\frac{1}{3} $ etc..</span></div>\n', 0, 0),
(62, 'inline_html', '<h3>Equivalent Fraction:</h3>\n\n<p>Fractions that represent the same part are called equivalent fraction.</p>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp;Ex :&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $ and&nbsp;$ \\frac{2}{4} $ ;&nbsp;$ \\frac{2}{7} $ and&nbsp;$ \\frac{6}{21} $ etc.</div>\n', 'Equivalent Fraction', '', '<h3>Equivalent Fraction:</h3>\n\n<p>Fractions that represent the same part are called equivalent fraction.</p>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp;Ex :&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $ and&nbsp;$ \\frac{2}{4} $ ;&nbsp;$ \\frac{2}{7} $ and&nbsp;$ \\frac{6}{21} $ etc.</div>\n', 0, 0),
(63, 'inline_html', '<h3>Like Fractions:</h3>\n\n<p>The fractional number`s that have the same denominators are called like fractions.</p>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; Ex :&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{9} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{2}{9} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{4}{9} $ etc,.</div>\n', 'Like  Fractions', '', '<h3>Like Fractions:</h3>\n\n<p>The fractional number`s that have the same denominators are called like fractions.</p>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; Ex :&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{9} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{2}{9} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{4}{9} $ etc,.</div>\n', 0, 0),
(64, 'inline_html', '<h3>Unlike Fractions:</h3>\n\n<p>Fractions that have different denominators are called unlike fractions.</p>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp; Ex :&nbsp;$ \\frac{4}{7} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{3}{4} $ etc .</div>\n', 'Unlike Fractions', '', '<h3>Unlike Fractions:</h3>\n\n<p>Fractions that have different denominators are called unlike fractions.</p>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp; Ex :&nbsp;$ \\frac{4}{7} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{3}{4} $ etc .</div>\n', 0, 0),
(65, 'inline_html', '<p>Any fraction&nbsp;$ \\frac{p}{q} $ can be expressed as a decimal. If the decimal expression of&nbsp;<span style="line-height:1.6em">$ \\frac{p}{q} $ terminates ., i.e. comes to an end , then the decimal to obtained is called a terminating decimal.&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="line-height:1.6em">&nbsp;&nbsp;Ex : 1)&nbsp;</span>$ \\frac{3}{2} $ = 1.5&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2)$ \\frac{3}{4} $ = 0.75</p>\n\n<p>Note : A fraction&nbsp;$ \\frac{p}{q} $ is a terminating decimal only, when prime factors of q are 2 and 5 only.</p>\n', 'Terminating Decimal', '', '<p>Any fraction&nbsp;$ \\frac{p}{q} $ can be expressed as a decimal. If the decimal expression of&nbsp;<span style="line-height:1.6em">$ \\frac{p}{q} $ terminates ., i.e. comes to an end , then the decimal to obtained is called a terminating decimal.&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="line-height:1.6em">&nbsp;&nbsp;Ex : 1)&nbsp;</span>$ \\frac{3}{2} $ = 1.5&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2)$ \\frac{3}{4} $ = 0.75</p>\n\n<p>Note : A fraction&nbsp;$ \\frac{p}{q} $ is a terminating decimal only, when prime factors of q are 2 and 5 only.</p>\n', 0, 0),
(66, 'inline_html', '<p>If in a decimal , a digit or a set of digits in the decimal part of is repeated continuously , then such a number is called a recurring or repeating decimal.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Ex : &nbsp;1)&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{3} $ = 0.33333............ &nbsp; &nbsp;= 0.$ \\bar{3} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2)$ \\frac{3}{11} $ = 0.272727......... &nbsp; &nbsp; =&nbsp;0.$ \\bar{27} $</p>\n', 'Recurring Decimals', '', '<p>If in a decimal , a digit or a set of digits in the decimal part of is repeated continuously , then such a number is called a recurring or repeating decimal.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Ex : &nbsp;1)&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{3} $ = 0.33333............ &nbsp; &nbsp;= 0.$ \\bar{3} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2)$ \\frac{3}{11} $ = 0.272727......... &nbsp; &nbsp; =&nbsp;0.$ \\bar{27} $</p>\n', 0, 0),
(67, 'inline_html', '<p>If a rational number in its lowest terms has prime factors other than 2 and 5 , the division does not end.During the process of division &nbsp;we get a digit or a group of digits repeated in some order.such decimal fractions are called non-terminating but recurring decimals.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Ex : &nbsp;1)$ \\frac{4}{9} $ = 0.444444........... = 0.$ \\bar{4} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2)$ \\frac{7}{15} $ = 0.4666666........ =&nbsp;0.4$ \\bar{6} $</p>\n\n<p>types of non-terminating repeating decimals:</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 1)pure recurring decimals : A decimal number in which all the digits after the decimal &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; point are repeated .</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Ex : 1)$ \\frac{3}{11} $ = 0.$ \\bar{27} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2)$ \\frac{1}{11} $ =&nbsp;0.$ \\bar{09} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;2)Mixed recurring decimals : A decimal number in which at least one digit after the decimal point is not repeated and others are repeated.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Ex :&nbsp;0.4$ \\bar{6} $ ,&nbsp;0.6$ \\bar{45} $ ,&nbsp;0.1$ \\bar{6} $</p>\n', 'Non-terminating decimal ', '', '<p>If a rational number in its lowest terms has prime factors other than 2 and 5 , the division does not end.During the process of division &nbsp;we get a digit or a group of digits repeated in some order.such decimal fractions are called non-terminating but recurring decimals.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Ex : &nbsp;1)$ \\frac{4}{9} $ = 0.444444........... = 0.$ \\bar{4} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2)$ \\frac{7}{15} $ = 0.4666666........ =&nbsp;0.4$ \\bar{6} $</p>\n\n<p>types of non-terminating repeating decimals:</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 1)pure recurring decimals : A decimal number in which all the digits after the decimal &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; point are repeated .</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Ex : 1)$ \\frac{3}{11} $ = 0.$ \\bar{27} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2)$ \\frac{1}{11} $ =&nbsp;0.$ \\bar{09} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;2)Mixed recurring decimals : A decimal number in which at least one digit after the decimal point is not repeated and others are repeated.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Ex :&nbsp;0.4$ \\bar{6} $ ,&nbsp;0.6$ \\bar{45} $ ,&nbsp;0.1$ \\bar{6} $</p>\n', 0, 0);
