(79, 'inline_html', '<p>Let a&gt;0 be a real number and &#39;n&#39; be a positive integer. If&nbsp;$ b^{n} $ = a, for some positive real number &#39;b&#39; ,then bis called n th root of &#39;a&#39; and we write&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ = b</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; i.e.&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ = b &nbsp;; b =&nbsp;$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n} &nbsp;} $</p>\n', 'N th root of Ral number', '', '<p>Let a&gt;0 be a real number and &#39;n&#39; be a positive integer. If&nbsp;$ b^{n} $ = a, for some positive real number &#39;b&#39; ,then bis called n th root of &#39;a&#39; and we write&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ = b</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; i.e.&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ = b &nbsp;; b =&nbsp;$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n} &nbsp;} $</p>\n', 0, 0),
(80, 'inline_html', '<p>If n is a positive integer and a rational number &nbsp;a(&gt;0) is not the n th power of any other rational number , then&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ or&nbsp;$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n} &nbsp;} $ is called a &#39;surd&#39; or &#39;radical&#39; of order n.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Here &#39;a&#39; is called radicand .</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{} $ is called radical sign</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;n is called the degree of radical .</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $ is called an exponential form</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ is called radical form of surd.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Ex :&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{2} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{3} $ ,&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{9} $ ,..... etc.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{&nbsp;\\prod &nbsp;} $ is not a surd , since&nbsp;$ \\prod $ is an irrational number.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{&nbsp;a^{n} &nbsp;} $ = a</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;If two surds a +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $ = c&nbsp;+&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{d} $ then&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; a = c and b = d</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ X&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{b} $ =&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{axb} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\sqrt[n]{a} }{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\sqrt[n]{b} } $ =&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{&nbsp;\\frac{a}{b} &nbsp;} $ where b$ \\neq $0</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Surd', '', '<p>If n is a positive integer and a rational number &nbsp;a(&gt;0) is not the n th power of any other rational number , then&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ or&nbsp;$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n} &nbsp;} $ is called a &#39;surd&#39; or &#39;radical&#39; of order n.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Here &#39;a&#39; is called radicand .</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{} $ is called radical sign</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;n is called the degree of radical .</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $ is called an exponential form</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ is called radical form of surd.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Ex :&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{2} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{3} $ ,&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{9} $ ,..... etc.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{&nbsp;\\prod &nbsp;} $ is not a surd , since&nbsp;$ \\prod $ is an irrational number.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{&nbsp;a^{n} &nbsp;} $ = a</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;If two surds a +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $ = c&nbsp;+&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{d} $ then&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; a = c and b = d</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ X&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{b} $ =&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{axb} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\sqrt[n]{a} }{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\sqrt[n]{b} } $ =&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{&nbsp;\\frac{a}{b} &nbsp;} $ where b$ \\neq $0</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 0, 0),
(81, 'inline_html', '<p>If the product of two surds is a rational number then each of the two is the rationalising factor(R.F)of the other.</p>\n\n<p>Note : R.F. of a given surd is not a unique.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; R.F of&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ +$ \\sqrt{b} $ is&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ -&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;R.F of&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ -&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $ is&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;R.F of &nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{a} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{b} $ is&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{&nbsp;a^{2} &nbsp;} $ -&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{ab} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{ b^{2}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;R.F of &nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{a} $ -&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{b} $ is&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{&nbsp;a^{2}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{ab} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{ b^{2}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $</p>\n', 'Rationalising Factor (R.F)', '', '<p>If the product of two surds is a rational number then each of the two is the rationalising factor(R.F)of the other.</p>\n\n<p>Note : R.F. of a given surd is not a unique.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; R.F of&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ +$ \\sqrt{b} $ is&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ -&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;R.F of&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ -&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $ is&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;R.F of &nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{a} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{b} $ is&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{&nbsp;a^{2} &nbsp;} $ -&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{ab} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{ b^{2}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;R.F of &nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{a} $ -&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{b} $ is&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{&nbsp;a^{2}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{ab} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{ b^{2}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $</p>\n', 0, 0),
(82, 'inline_html', '<p><strong>Polynomial:</strong></p>\n\n<p>An algebraic expression in which the variables involved have only non-negative integral powers is called a polynomial.</p>\n\n<p>Ex : 3$ x^{2} $+ 4x+ 7</p>\n\n<p><strong>Algebraic Expression:</strong></p>\n\n<p>A constant alone or a variable alone or their combination with the four fundamental operations &#39;+&#39; , &#39;-&#39; ,&#39;X&#39; &nbsp;and &nbsp;&#39;$ \\div $ &#39; &nbsp;is known as an algebraic expression.</p>\n\n<p>Ex: &nbsp;2x+y , 3$ x^{2} $+$ \\frac{1}{x} $+5 etc.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Standard form of a polynomial in one variable:</strong></p>\n\n<p>A polynomial p(x) in one variable x is an algebraic expression in x of the form</p>\n\n<p>p(x) =&nbsp;$ a_{n} $$ x^{n} $+&nbsp;$ a_{n-1} $$ x^{n-1} $+..................+$ a_{2} $$ x^{2} $+$ a_{1}x&nbsp;$+$ a_{0} $ ,</p>\n\n<p>Where&nbsp;$ a_{0} $ ,&nbsp;$ a_{1} $ ,&nbsp;$ a_{2} $ ,...........,$ a_{n} $ are respectively the coefficients of&nbsp;$ x^{0} $ ,&nbsp;$ x^{1} $ ,&nbsp;$ x^{2} $ , ............$ x^{n} $ and n is called the degree of the polynomial if&nbsp;$ a_{n} $$ \\neq $0. Each&nbsp;$ a_{n} $$ x^{n} $;&nbsp;&nbsp;$ a_{n-1} $$ x^{n-1} $ ;&nbsp;$ a_{0} $ , is called a term of the polynomial p(x).</p>\n\n<p>Polynomials can be classified as monomials, binomials, trinomials and polynomials based on the number of terms it contains</p>\n\n<p><strong>Monomial:</strong></p>\n\n<p>A polynomial having only one term is called a monomial.</p>\n\n<p>Ex: 7x,&nbsp;$ \\frac{-5}{2} $$ x^{2} $ , 4$ x^{3} $ etc.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Binomial:</strong></p>\n\n<p>A polynomial having&nbsp;two&nbsp;terms is called a binomial.</p>\n\n<p>Ex: 3x-4y, -7$ x^{2} $+4x etc.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Trinomial:</strong></p>\n\n<p>A polynomial having three&nbsp;terms is called a trinomial.</p>\n\n<p>Ex: 2x-7y+z , 2x+$ \\frac{y}{3} $ -&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $ , 2x -&nbsp;$ \\frac{3}{2}xyz $+ 9$ y^{2}$&nbsp;etc.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Multinomial:</strong></p>\n\n<p>An algebraic expression having one or more terms is called multinomial.</p>\n\n<p>Ex: 2 +&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{x} $ , 2$ x^{3} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{x} $ + 5</p>\n\n<p><strong>Degree of a monomial:</strong></p>\n\n<p>The degree of monomial in one variable is the highest power of the variable in that monomial.</p>\n\n<p>The degree of a monomial containing more than one variable is the sum of the powers of all the variable in that&nbsp;monomial.</p>\n\n<p>Ex: Degree of 2xy + 3x&nbsp;$ y^{3} $ +&nbsp;$ x^{2} $ is 4</p>\n\n<p><strong>Constant Polynomial:</strong></p>\n\n<p>A polynomial with only one non-zero numerical term is called constant polynomial.</p>\n\n<p>Ex: - 7, 4, 3, 15 are examples of a constant polynomial.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Note: The degree of the constant polynomial is zero.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Zero Polynomial:</strong></p>\n\n<p>A polynomial in which all the coefficients are equal to zero, is known as a zero polynomial</p>\n\n<p>Ex: (0).&nbsp;$ x^{2} $ +(0)x + 0</p>\n\n<p>Note: The degree of the zero polynomial is not defined.</p>\n\n<h3>Types of polynomials according to degree:</h3>\n\n<p>1) Linear Polynomial:</p>\n\n<p>A polynomial of degree one is called a linear polynomial.</p>\n\n<p>Ex: 2x- 7, 3y + 2</p>\n\n<p>2) Quadratic Polynomial:</p>\n\n<p>A polynomial of degree two is called a quadratic polynomial.</p>\n\n<p>Ex: 4$ x^{2} $ + 5x - 7</p>\n\n<p>3) Cubic Polynomial:</p>\n\n<p>A polynomial of degree three is called a cubic polynomial.</p>\n\n<p>Ex:&nbsp;$ x^{3} $ - 9&nbsp;$ x^{2} $ + 4x - 7</p>\n\n<p><strong>Polynomials in two or more variables:</strong></p>\n\n<p>An algebraic expression involving two or more variables with non-negative integral powers is called a polynomial in these variables.</p>\n\n<p>Ex:&nbsp;$ x^{2} $ + 2xy - y is a polynomial in x and y whose terms are of degree 2 , 2 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;and 1</p>\n\n<p><strong>Degree of a polynomial having two or more variables:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Degree of a polynomial is defined as highest of the degrees 