\n\n<p><strong>Degree of a polynomial having two or more variables:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Degree of a polynomial is defined as highest of the degrees of the terms in it .</p>\n\n<p>Ex : degree of 4x$ y^{2} $ - 7$ x^{2} $ + 4$ x^{2} $$ y^{2} $ - 8x - 4 is 4</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 0, 0),
(83, 'inline_html', '<p><strong>Zero of a polynomial :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>The zero of a polynomial<strong>&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;p(x) is the value of x , for which p(x) = 0 .</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; This value is also called a root of the polynomial p(x).</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Ex : Zero of 2x - 4 is x = 2</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Note : To find the zero of a polynomial we equate the polynomial to zero and solve for&nbsp;&nbsp;the value of the variable.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; * A linear polynomial in one variable has only one zero(root).</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; * Dividend &nbsp;= &nbsp;(Divisor x Quotient) + Remainder.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; * A polynomial of &nbsp;&#39;n&#39; degree will have &nbsp;&#39;n&#39; roots for it.</p>\n', 'Zero Of a Polynomial', '', '<p><strong>Zero of a polynomial :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>The zero of a polynomial<strong>&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;p(x) is the value of x , for which p(x) = 0 .</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; This value is also called a root of the polynomial p(x).</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Ex : Zero of 2x - 4 is x = 2</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Note : To find the zero of a polynomial we equate the polynomial to zero and solve for&nbsp;&nbsp;the value of the variable.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; * A linear polynomial in one variable has only one zero(root).</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; * Dividend &nbsp;= &nbsp;(Divisor x Quotient) + Remainder.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; * A polynomial of &nbsp;&#39;n&#39; degree will have &nbsp;&#39;n&#39; roots for it.</p>\n', 0, 0),
(84, 'inline_html', '<p><strong>Remainder Theorem :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>Let p(x) be&nbsp;any polynomial of degree greater than or equal to one and let &nbsp;&#39;a&#39; be any&nbsp;real number .&nbsp;If p(x) is divided by the linear polynomial (x - a) , then the remainder is p(a).</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Remainder Theorem', '', '<p><strong>Remainder Theorem :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>Let p(x) be&nbsp;any polynomial of degree greater than or equal to one and let &nbsp;&#39;a&#39; be any&nbsp;real number .&nbsp;If p(x) is divided by the linear polynomial (x - a) , then the remainder is p(a).</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 0, 0),
(85, 'inline_html', '<h3><strong>Factor theorem :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>If p(x) is a polynomial of degree&nbsp;$ \\ge $ and &nbsp;&#39;a&#39; is any real number , then&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;1) (x - a) is a factor of p(x) , if p(a) =&nbsp;0</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2) and its converse &quot; if&nbsp;(x - a)&nbsp;is a factor of a polynomial p(x),&nbsp;&nbsp;then p(a) = 0</p>\n', 'Factor Theorem', '', '<h3><strong>Factor theorem :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>If p(x) is a polynomial of degree&nbsp;$ \\ge $ and &nbsp;&#39;a&#39; is any real number , then&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;1) (x - a) is a factor of p(x) , if p(a) =&nbsp;0</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2) and its converse &quot; if&nbsp;(x - a)&nbsp;is a factor of a polynomial p(x),&nbsp;&nbsp;then p(a) = 0</p>\n', 0, 0),
(86, 'inline_html', '<div class="content-formula"><strong>Algebraic Identities :</strong></div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">1) $ (x+y)^{2} $ &nbsp;= $ x^{2} $ + 2xy +&nbsp;$ y^{2} $</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">2) $ (x-y)^{2} $ &nbsp;=&nbsp;$ x^{2} $ -&nbsp;2xy +&nbsp;$ y^{2} $</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">3) (x+y)&nbsp;(x-y) = &nbsp;$ x^{2} $ -&nbsp;$ y^{2} $</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">4) (x+a) (x+b) =&nbsp;$ x^{2} $ + (a+b)x + ab</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">5) $ (x+y+z)^{2} $ &nbsp;= $ x^{2} $ +&nbsp;$ y^{2} $ +&nbsp;$ z^{2} $ + 2xy + 2yz + 2zx</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">6) $ (x+y)^{3} $ &nbsp;= $ x^{3} $ + &nbsp;$ y^{3} $ &nbsp;+3xy (x+y)</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; =&nbsp;$ x^{3} $ +&nbsp;&nbsp;$ y^{3} $ + 3$ x^{2} $y + 3x$ y^{2} $</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">7) $ (x-y)^{3} $ &nbsp;= $ x^{3} $ -&nbsp; $ y^{3} $ &nbsp;-&nbsp;3xy (x-y)</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; =&nbsp;$ x^{3} $ -&nbsp; $ y^{3} $ -&nbsp;3$ x^{2} $y + 3x$ y^{2} $</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">8) (x + y + z)(&nbsp;$ x^{2} $ +&nbsp;$ y^{2} $ +&nbsp;$ z^{2} $ -&nbsp;xy -&nbsp;yz -&nbsp;zx) &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ x^{3} $ +&nbsp;$ y^{3} $ +&nbsp;$ z^{3} $ - 3xyz</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp;9) $ x^{3} $ + &nbsp;$ y^{3} $ &nbsp;= (x + y)($ x^{2} $ - &nbsp;xy +&nbsp;$ y^{2} $)</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">10) $ x^{3} $ -&nbsp; $ y^{3} $ &nbsp;= (x -&nbsp;y)($ x^{2} $ +&nbsp; xy +&nbsp;$ y^{2} $)</div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">11) If x+ y + z = 0 then&nbsp;$ x^{3} $ +&nbsp;$ y^{3} $ +&nbsp;$ z^{3} $ &nbsp;=&nbsp;&nbsp;3xyz</div>\n', 'Algebraic Identities', '', '<div class="content-formula"><strong>Algebraic Identities :</strong></div>\n\n<div class="content-formula">1) $ (x+y)^{2} $ &nbsp;= $ x^{2} $ + 2xy +&nbsp;$ y^{2} $</div>\n\n<