(88, 'inline_html', '<p>A &nbsp;body &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest &nbsp;or &nbsp;in &nbsp;motion &nbsp;is &nbsp;relative &nbsp;form. &nbsp;It &nbsp;changes &nbsp;with &nbsp;change &nbsp; in &nbsp;observer.</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;can &nbsp;also &nbsp;be &nbsp;considered &nbsp;as &nbsp;body &nbsp; at &nbsp;rest&nbsp; and &nbsp;vice &nbsp;versa</p>\n\n<p>For eg : &nbsp;Consider &nbsp;a &nbsp;school &nbsp;bus &nbsp;carrying &nbsp;students &nbsp;to &nbsp;school &nbsp;with &nbsp;respect &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;surroundings &nbsp;the &nbsp; students &nbsp;are &nbsp;moving , but with &nbsp;respect &nbsp;to &nbsp;each &nbsp;other , &nbsp;students &nbsp;are &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest.</p>\n\n<p>Thus &nbsp;the &nbsp;state of &nbsp;rest &nbsp;or &nbsp;motion &nbsp; changes &nbsp;with &nbsp;the &nbsp;change &nbsp; in &nbsp;reference &nbsp;point.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Body &nbsp;in &nbsp;motion :</strong></p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;said &nbsp;to &nbsp;be &nbsp;in &nbsp;state &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;if , &nbsp;with &nbsp;time &nbsp;its &nbsp;position &nbsp;changes &nbsp;continuously &nbsp;with &nbsp; respect &nbsp;to &nbsp;a reference &nbsp;point.</p>\n\n<p>Eg : &nbsp;Moving &nbsp;car , Football when &nbsp;kicked , Person &nbsp;walking &nbsp;or &nbsp;running &nbsp;etc</p>\n\n<p><strong>Body &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest :</strong></p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;said &nbsp;to &nbsp;be &nbsp;in &nbsp;state &nbsp;of &nbsp;rest &nbsp;if , with time its &nbsp;position changes &nbsp;continuously &nbsp;with &nbsp;respect &nbsp;to a reference &nbsp;point.</p>\n\n<p>Eg : Stationary &nbsp;car , &nbsp;Passengers &nbsp;of &nbsp;moving &nbsp;train &nbsp;with &nbsp;respect &nbsp;to &nbsp;each &nbsp;other , &nbsp;Stationary &nbsp;ball , Trees , &nbsp;Mountains &nbsp;etc</p>\n\n<p>No body &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;said &nbsp;to &nbsp;be &nbsp;in &nbsp;absolute &nbsp;motion &nbsp;or &nbsp;absolute &nbsp;rest</p>\n\n<p><strong>Different &nbsp;types &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>1) Transletory &nbsp;or &nbsp;linear :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>Motion<strong>&nbsp;</strong>in &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line</p>\n\n<p>Eg : &nbsp;Car &nbsp;moving &nbsp;on &nbsp;straight &nbsp;road</p>\n\n<p><strong>2) Rotatory &nbsp;or circular :</strong></p>\n\n<p>Motion &nbsp;in &nbsp;a circular &nbsp;path</p>\n\n<p>Eg :Spinning &nbsp;tap, &nbsp;Blades &nbsp;of &nbsp;fan</p>\n\n<p><strong>3) Vibratory or osallatory :</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;To &nbsp;and &nbsp;from &nbsp;motion &nbsp;about &nbsp;a &nbsp;fixed &nbsp;point</p>\n\n<p>Eg : pendulum &nbsp;of &nbsp;clock , &nbsp;see saw</p>\n', 'Rest  and  motion', '', '<p>A &nbsp;body &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest &nbsp;or &nbsp;in &nbsp;motion &nbsp;is &nbsp;relative &nbsp;form. &nbsp;It &nbsp;changes &nbsp;with &nbsp;change &nbsp; in &nbsp;observer.</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;can &nbsp;also &nbsp;be &nbsp;considered &nbsp;as &nbsp;body &nbsp; at &nbsp;rest&nbsp; and &nbsp;vice &nbsp;versa</p>\n\n<p>For eg : &nbsp;Consider &nbsp;a &nbsp;school &nbsp;bus &nbsp;carrying &nbsp;students &nbsp;to &nbsp;school &nbsp;with &nbsp;respect &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;surroundings &nbsp;the &nbsp; students &nbsp;are &nbsp;moving , but with &nbsp;respect &nbsp;to &nbsp;each &nbsp;other , &nbsp;students &nbsp;are &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest.</p>\n\n<p>Thus &nbsp;the &nbsp;state of &nbsp;rest &nbsp;or &nbsp;motion &nbsp; changes &nbsp;with &nbsp;the &nbsp;change &nbsp; in &nbsp;reference &nbsp;point.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Body &nbsp;in &nbsp;motion :</strong></p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;said &nbsp;to &nbsp;be &nbsp;in &nbsp;state &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;if , &nbsp;with &nbsp;time &nbsp;its &nbsp;position &nbsp;changes &nbsp;continuously &nbsp;with &nbsp; respect &nbsp;to &nbsp;a reference &nbsp;point.</p>\n\n<p>Eg : &nbsp;Moving &nbsp;car , Football when &nbsp;kicked , Person &nbsp;walking &nbsp;or &nbsp;running &nbsp;etc</p>\n\n<p><strong>Body &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest :</strong></p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;said &nbsp;to &nbsp;be &nbsp;in &nbsp;state &nbsp;of &nbsp;rest &nbsp;if , with time its &nbsp;position changes &nbsp;continuously &nbsp;with &nbsp;respect &nbsp;to a reference &nbsp;point.</p>\n\n<p>Eg : Stationary &nbsp;car , &nbsp;Passengers &nbsp;of &nbsp;moving &nbsp;train &nbsp;with &nbsp;respect &nbsp;to &nbsp;each &nbsp;other , &nbsp;Stationary &nbsp;ball , Trees , &nbsp;Mountains &nbsp;etc</p>\n\n<p>No body &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;said &nbsp;to &nbsp;be &nbsp;in &nbsp;absolute &nbsp;motion &nbsp;or &nbsp;absolute &nbsp;rest</p>\n\n<p><strong>Different &nbsp;types &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>1) Transletory &nbsp;or &nbsp;linear :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>Motion<strong>&nbsp;</strong>in &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line</p>\n\n<p>Eg : &nbsp;Car &nbsp;moving &nbsp;on &nbsp;straight &nbsp;road</p>\n\n<p><strong>2) Rotatory &nbsp;or circular :</strong></p>\n\n<p>Motion &nbsp;in &nbsp;a circular &nbsp;path</p>\n\n<p>Eg :Spinning &nbsp;tap, &nbsp;Blades &nbsp;of &nbsp;fan</p>\n\n<p><strong>3) Vibratory or osallatory :</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;To &nbsp;and &nbsp;from &nbsp;motion &nbsp;about &nbsp;a &nbsp;fixed &nbsp;point</p>\n\n<p>Eg : pendulum &nbsp;of &nbsp;clock , &nbsp;see saw</p>\n', 0, 0),
(89, 'inline_html', '<p>Distance &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;length &nbsp;of &nbsp;actual &nbsp;path &nbsp;taken &nbsp;by &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;in given &nbsp;time</p>\n\n<p>Units</p>\n\n<p>S I &nbsp;- &nbsp;meter ( m )</p>\n\n<p>CGS &nbsp;- &nbsp;centimeter ( cm )</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;1 m &nbsp;= &nbsp;100 cm &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ 10^{2} $ &nbsp;cm</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Higher &nbsp;units</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Kilometer &nbsp;( km )</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 1 km = &nbsp;1000 m &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ 10^{3} $ m</p>\n\n<p>Smaller &nbsp;units</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; millimeter &nbsp;( mm )</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 1 mm &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{1000} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ 10^{-3} $&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig1.png" style="height:422px; width:925px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong>Displacement :</strong></p>\n\n<p>A moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;changes &nbsp;its &nbsp;place &nbsp;i.e &nbsp; it gets &nbsp;displaced</p>\n\n<p>Diplacement &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;shortest &nbsp;distance &nbsp;between &nbsp;the &nbsp;initial &nbsp;and &nbsp;final &nbsp;points [ positions , places ] &nbsp;of &nbsp;a moving &nbsp;body.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;shortest &nbsp;distance &nbsp;between &nbsp;any &nbsp;2 &nbsp;points &nbsp;is a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line , hence &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;joining &nbsp;initial &nbsp;and &nbsp;final &nbsp;positions</p>\n\n<p>Units</p>\n\n<p>S I &nbsp;- &nbsp;meter ( m )</p>\n\n<p>CGS &nbsp;- &nbsp;centimeter ( cm )</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;1 m &nbsp;= &nbsp;100 cm &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ 10^{2} $ &nbsp;cm</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Higher &nbsp;units</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Kilometer &nbsp;( km )</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 1 km = &nbsp;1000 m &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ 10^{3} $ m</p>\n\n<p>Smaller &nbsp;units</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; millimeter &nbsp;( mm )</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 1 mm &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{1000} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ 10^{-3} $&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>While &nbsp;measuring &nbsp;displacement , &nbsp;initial &nbsp;or &nbsp;starting &nbsp;and &nbsp;final &nbsp;positions &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;are &nbsp;very &nbsp;important. This means &nbsp;it &nbsp;depends &nbsp;not &nbsp;only &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;but &nbsp;also &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body</p>\n\n<p>Therefore displacement &nbsp;is &nbsp;vector &nbsp;quantity .</p>\n\n<p>Remember &nbsp;a &nbsp;vector &nbsp;quantity &nbsp;has &nbsp;both &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;and &nbsp;direction.</p>\n\n<p>Thus &nbsp;even &nbsp;if &nbsp;the &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;remains &nbsp;unchanged &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;changes &nbsp;if &nbsp;the &nbsp;direction &nbsp;is &nbsp;changed.</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;vector &nbsp;quantity &nbsp;is &nbsp;represented &nbsp;by &nbsp;a &nbsp;directed &nbsp;line &nbsp;segment &nbsp;whose &nbsp;length &nbsp;gives &nbsp;th &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;while &nbsp;the &nbsp;arrow &nbsp;indicates &nbsp;direction.</p>\n\n<p>Eg :</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig2.png" style="float:left; height:257px; width:299px" />Initial &nbsp;point - A</p>\n\n<p>Final &nbsp;point - C</p>\n\n<p>Displacement &nbsp;will be &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;joining &nbsp;AC</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig3(1).png" style="height:215px; width:250px" />&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Looking &nbsp;at &nbsp;the &nbsp;geometry &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;figure , &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;clear &nbsp;that &nbsp;AC &nbsp;is &nbsp;also &nbsp;hypothereus &nbsp;of &nbsp;right&nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ &nbsp;ABC</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ AC^{2} $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;$ 4^{2} $ &nbsp;+ &nbsp;$ 3^{2} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ AC^{2} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;16 &nbsp;+ &nbsp;9 &nbsp;= &nbsp;25</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;AC &nbsp; = &nbsp;5 m</p>\n\n<p>Always &nbsp;while &nbsp;finding &nbsp;displacement , &nbsp;locate &nbsp;the &nbsp;initial &nbsp;and &nbsp;final &nbsp;points of &nbsp;the &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;and &nbsp;join then with &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line .</p>\n\n<p><strong>Difference &nbsp;between &nbsp;Distance &nbsp;and &nbsp;Displacement :</strong></p>\n\n<p>Let &nbsp;3 &nbsp;friends &nbsp;travel &nbsp;from &nbsp;Hyderabad &nbsp;to &nbsp;Delhi &nbsp;by &nbsp;plane, &nbsp;train &nbsp;and &nbsp;car &nbsp;respectively</p>\n\n<p>Though &nbsp;they &nbsp;start &nbsp;from &nbsp;same &nbsp;place &nbsp;and &nbsp;reaches &nbsp;same &nbsp;place , &nbsp;yet &nbsp;the &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;by &nbsp;them &nbsp;will be &nbsp;different . However &nbsp;their &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;will be &nbsp;same</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;can &nbsp;never &nbsp;be &nbsp;greater &nbsp;than &nbsp;the &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;distance &nbsp;though they &nbsp;can &nbsp;be same.</p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp;is obvious &nbsp;that &nbsp;they &nbsp;will &nbsp;be &nbsp;equal &nbsp;when &nbsp;body &nbsp;moves &nbsp;along &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line. In all other &nbsp;cases, &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;is &nbsp;always &nbsp;less than &nbsp;distance.&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Distance  and  Displacement', '', '<p>Distance &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;length &nbsp;of &nbsp;actual &nbsp;path &nbsp;taken &nbsp;by &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;in given &nbsp;time</p>\n\n<p>Units</p>\n\n<p>S I &nbsp;- &nbsp;meter ( m )</p>\n\n<p>CGS &nbsp;- &nbsp;centimeter ( cm )</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;1 m &nbsp;= &nbsp;100 cm &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ 10^{2} $ &nbsp;cm</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Higher &nbsp;units</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Kilometer &nbsp;( km )</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 1 km = &nbsp;1000 m &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ 10^{3} $ m</p>\n\n<p>Smaller &nbsp;units</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; millimeter &nbsp;( mm )</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 1 mm &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{1000} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ 10^{-3} $&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig1.png" style="height:422px; width:925px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong>Displacement :</strong></p>\n\n<p>A moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;changes &nbsp;its &nbsp;place &nbsp;i.e &nbsp; it gets &nbsp;displaced</p>\n\n<p>Diplacement &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;shortest &nbsp;distance &nbsp;between &nbsp;the &nbsp;initial &nbsp;and &nbsp;final &nbsp;points [ positions , places ] &nbsp;of &nbsp;a moving &nbsp;body.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;shortest &nbsp;distance &nbsp;between &nbsp;any &nbsp;2 &nbsp;points &nbsp;is a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line , hence &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;joining &nbsp;initial &nbsp;and &nbsp;final &nbsp;positions</p>\n\n<p>Units</p>\n\n<p>S I &nbsp;- &nbsp;meter ( m )</p>\n\n<p>CGS &nbsp;- &nbsp;centimeter ( cm )</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;1 m &nbsp;= &nbsp;100 cm &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ 10^{2} $ &nbsp;cm</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Higher &nbsp;units</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Kilometer &nbsp;( km )</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 1 km = &nbsp;1000 m &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ 10^{3} $ m</p>\n\n<p>Smaller &nbsp;units</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; millimeter &nbsp;( mm )</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 1 mm &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{1000} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ 10^{-3} $&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>While &nbsp;measuring &nbsp;displacement , &nbsp;initial &nbsp;or &nbsp;starting &nbsp;and &nbsp;final &nbsp;positions &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;are &nbsp;very &nbsp;important. This means &nbsp;it &nbsp;depends &nbsp;not &nbsp;only &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;but &nbsp;also &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body</p>\n\n<p>Therefore displacement &nbsp;is &nbsp;vector &nbsp;quantity .</p>\n\n<p>Remember &nbsp;a &nbsp;vector &nbsp;quantity &nbsp;has &nbsp;both &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;and &nbsp;direction.</p>\n\n<p>Thus &nbsp;even &nbsp;if &nbsp;the &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;remains &nbsp;unchanged &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;changes &nbsp;if &nbsp;the &nbsp;direction &nbsp;is &nbsp;changed.</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;vector &nbsp;quantity &nbsp;is &nbsp;represented &nbsp;by &nbsp;a &nbsp;directed &nbsp;line &nbsp;segment &nbsp;whose &nbsp;length &nbsp;gives &nbsp;th &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;while &nbsp;the &nbsp;arrow &nbsp;indicates &nbsp;direction.</p>\n\n<p>Eg :</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig2.png" style="float:left; height:257px; width:299px" />Initial &nbsp;point - A</p>\n\n<p>Final &nbsp;point - C</p>\n\n<p>Displacement &nbsp;will be &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;joining &nbsp;AC</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig3(1).png" style="height:215px; width:250px" />&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Looking &nbsp;at &nbsp;the &nbsp;geometry &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;figure , &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;clear &nbsp;that &nbsp;AC &nbsp;is &nbsp;also &nbsp;hypothereus &nbsp;of &nbsp;right&nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ &nbsp;ABC</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ AC^{2} $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;$ 4^{2} $ &nbsp;+ &nbsp;$ 3^{2} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ AC^{2} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;16 &nbsp;+ &nbsp;9 &nbsp;= &nbsp;25</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;AC &nbsp; = &nbsp;5 m</p>\n\n<p>Always &nbsp;while &nbsp;finding &nbsp;displacement , &nbsp;locate &nbsp;the &nbsp;initial &nbsp;and &nbsp;final &nbsp;points of &nbsp;the &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;and &nbsp;join then with &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line .</p>\n\n<p><strong>Difference &nbsp;between &nbsp;Distance &nbsp;and &nbsp;Displacement :</strong></p>\n\n<p>Let &nbsp;3 &nbsp;friends &nbsp;travel &nbsp;from &nbsp;Hyderabad &nbsp;to &nbsp;Delhi &nbsp;by &nbsp;plane, &nbsp;train &nbsp;and &nbsp;car &nbsp;respectively</p>\n\n<p>Though &nbsp;they &nbsp;start &nbsp;from &nbsp;same &nbsp;place &nbsp;and &nbsp;reaches &nbsp;same &nbsp;place , &nbsp;yet &nbsp;the &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;by &nbsp;them &nbsp;will be &nbsp;different . However &nbsp;their &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;will be &nbsp;same</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;can &nbsp;never &nbsp;be &nbsp;greater &nbsp;than &nbsp;the &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;distance &nbsp;though they &nbsp;can &nbsp;be same.</p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp;is obvious &nbsp;that &nbsp;they &nbsp;will &nbsp;be &nbsp;equal &nbsp;when &nbsp;body &nbsp;moves &nbsp;along &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line. In all other &nbsp;cases, &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;is &nbsp;always &nbsp;less than &nbsp;distance.&nbsp;</p>\n', 0, 0);
