(90, 'inline_html', '<p>Let &nbsp;3 &nbsp;friends &nbsp;travel &nbsp;from &nbsp;Hyderabad &nbsp;to &nbsp;Delhi &nbsp;by &nbsp;plane, &nbsp;train &nbsp;and &nbsp;car &nbsp;respectively. In &nbsp;this &nbsp;example &nbsp;its &nbsp;easy &nbsp;to &nbsp;say &nbsp;who &nbsp;reaches &nbsp;Delhi &nbsp;first. Different &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;take &nbsp;different &nbsp;time &nbsp;to &nbsp;cover &nbsp;same &nbsp;distance &nbsp;or &nbsp;cover &nbsp;different &nbsp;distances &nbsp;in &nbsp;same &nbsp;time.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;of &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;by &nbsp;a &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;time &nbsp;taken &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;its &nbsp;speed.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Symbol &nbsp;- &nbsp;v</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Speed &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{Distance}{Time} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;v &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{s}{t} $</p>\n\n<p>Speed &nbsp;tells &nbsp;us &nbsp;how &nbsp;fast &nbsp;or &nbsp;slow &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;moving&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Units</p>\n\n<p>S I &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;- &nbsp;Meter &nbsp;per &nbsp;second &nbsp;[ m$ s^{-1} $ ]</p>\n\n<p>C G S &nbsp;- &nbsp;Centimeter &nbsp;per &nbsp;second [ c m&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $ ]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 1&nbsp;m$ s^{-1} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;100&nbsp;c m&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $</p>\n\n<p>Speed &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;scalar &nbsp;quantity . It &nbsp;does &nbsp;not &nbsp;depend &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Other &nbsp;units&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Kilometer &nbsp;per &nbsp;hour [ k m&nbsp;$ h^{-1} $ ]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;above &nbsp;eg , &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;moving &nbsp;from &nbsp;A &nbsp;to &nbsp;B &nbsp;during &nbsp;its &nbsp;motion , &nbsp;its &nbsp;speed &nbsp;is &nbsp;changing &nbsp;i. e &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;moving &nbsp;with &nbsp;variable &nbsp;speed</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Let &nbsp;s &nbsp;= &nbsp;total &nbsp;distance &nbsp;between &nbsp;AB</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; s &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ s_{1} $ + $ s_{2} $ +&nbsp;$ s_{3} $ +&nbsp;$ s_{4} $&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Let &nbsp; &nbsp;t &nbsp;= &nbsp;total &nbsp;time</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; t &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ t_{1} $&nbsp;+&nbsp;$ t_{2} $ +&nbsp;$ t_{3} $ +&nbsp;$ t_{4} $&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>Speed :</strong></p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;of &nbsp;total &nbsp;distance &nbsp;and &nbsp;total &nbsp;time &nbsp;gives &nbsp;average &nbsp;speed &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;moving &nbsp;with &nbsp;variable &nbsp;speed</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Average &nbsp;speed &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{total &nbsp;distance}{total &nbsp;time} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; v &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{s}{t} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{&nbsp;s_{1} &nbsp;+&nbsp;&nbsp;s_{2} &nbsp;+&nbsp;&nbsp;s_{3} &nbsp;+&nbsp;&nbsp;s_{4} &nbsp;}{t_{1} &nbsp;+&nbsp;&nbsp;t_{2} &nbsp;+&nbsp;&nbsp;t_{3} &nbsp;+&nbsp;&nbsp;t_{4}} $</p>\n\n<p><strong>Instanteneous &nbsp;speed :</strong></p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;speed &nbsp;of &nbsp;moving &nbsp;at &nbsp;a &nbsp;given &nbsp;instant . &nbsp;The &nbsp;speedometer &nbsp;of &nbsp;automobiles &nbsp;gives &nbsp;instanteneous speed</p>\n\n<p><strong>Uniform [ constant ] &nbsp;speed :</strong></p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;covers &nbsp;equal &nbsp;distances &nbsp;in &nbsp;equal &nbsp;intervals &nbsp;of &nbsp;time &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;said &nbsp;to &nbsp;have &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;speed &nbsp;or &nbsp;constant &nbsp;speed.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;other &nbsp;words &nbsp;body &nbsp;moving &nbsp;with &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;speed &nbsp;covers &nbsp;same &nbsp;distance &nbsp;every &nbsp;second.</p>\n\n<p>Speed &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;found &nbsp;using &nbsp;distance - time [ s - t ] graph</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig4.png" style="height:200px; width:250px" />&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Distance &nbsp;is &nbsp;taken &nbsp;along &nbsp;Y - axis</p>\n\n<p>Time &nbsp;is &nbsp;taken &nbsp;along &nbsp;x &nbsp;- axis</p>\n\n<p>Slope &nbsp;of &nbsp;s - t graph &nbsp;gives &nbsp;the &nbsp;instantenous &nbsp;speed</p>\n\n<p>Tangent &nbsp;at &nbsp;any &nbsp;point &nbsp;on &nbsp;s - t &nbsp;curve &nbsp;represents &nbsp;its &nbsp;slope &nbsp;at &nbsp;that &nbsp;point .</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;steep &nbsp;or &nbsp;large &nbsp;slope &nbsp;means &nbsp;body &nbsp;with &nbsp;high &nbsp;speed .</p>\n\n<p><strong>Velocity :</strong></p>\n\n<p>Ratio &nbsp;of &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;time &nbsp;taken &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;its &nbsp;velocity</p>\n\n<p>Velocity &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;speed &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;moving &nbsp;in &nbsp;particular &nbsp;direction.</p>\n\n<p>As &nbsp;direction &nbsp;changes, &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;also &nbsp;changes &nbsp;thus &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;is &nbsp;vector &nbsp;quantity &nbsp;as &nbsp;it &nbsp;has &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;as &nbsp;well as &nbsp;direction.</p>\n\n<p>Velocity &nbsp;tells &nbsp;us &nbsp;how &nbsp;fast &nbsp;or &nbsp;slow &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;moving &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;particular &nbsp;direction .</p>\n\n<p>Symbol &nbsp; - &nbsp; $ \\bar{V} $ &nbsp; &nbsp;or &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\underset{V}{\\rightarrow} $ &nbsp;or &nbsp;V</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Velocity (&nbsp;$ \\bar{V} $ ) &nbsp; = &nbsp;$ \\frac{displacement ( &nbsp;\\bar{V} )&nbsp;}{time ( t )&nbsp;} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$ \\bar{V} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{\\bar{s}}{t} $</p>\n\n<p>Units</p>\n\n<p>S I &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;- &nbsp;Meter &nbsp;per &nbsp;second &nbsp;[ m$ s^{-1} $ ]</p>\n\n<p>C G S &nbsp;- &nbsp;Centimeter &nbsp;per &nbsp;second [ c m&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $ ]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 1&nbsp;m$ s^{-1} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;100&nbsp;c m&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Other &nbsp;units&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Kilometer &nbsp;per &nbsp;hour [ k m&nbsp;$ h^{-1} $ ]</p>\n\n<p>Magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;can &nbsp;never &nbsp;be &nbsp;greater &nbsp;than &nbsp;that &nbsp;of &nbsp;speed</p>\n\n<p>For &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;moving &nbsp;in &nbsp;st