(94, 'inline_html', '<p>Graphs &nbsp;give &nbsp;pictorial &nbsp;information. &nbsp;To &nbsp;represent &nbsp;the &nbsp;motion , to &nbsp;understand it , to &nbsp;analyse it &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;use &nbsp;graphs. We &nbsp;can &nbsp;get &nbsp;line &nbsp;graphs &nbsp;for &nbsp;motion &nbsp;by &nbsp;plotting &nbsp;various &nbsp;physical &nbsp;quantities &nbsp;associated &nbsp;with &nbsp;motion &nbsp;against &nbsp;time. Thus &nbsp;we &nbsp;get &nbsp;distance - time , velocity - time &nbsp;or &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp;- &nbsp;time &nbsp;graphs. Using &nbsp;these &nbsp;graph &nbsp;we can &nbsp;calculate &nbsp;unknown &nbsp;physical &nbsp;quantity &nbsp;in &nbsp;that &nbsp;motion. &nbsp;similarly &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;obtain &nbsp;equations &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;from &nbsp;the &nbsp;graphs.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>Distance &nbsp;- time &nbsp;graphs :</strong></p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;take &nbsp;distance [ s ] &nbsp;in &nbsp;meters &nbsp;or &nbsp;sometimes &nbsp;in &nbsp;centimeters &nbsp;on &nbsp;Y - axis , and &nbsp;time [ t ] &nbsp;in &nbsp;seconds &nbsp;on &nbsp;X&nbsp;- axis</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;resultant &nbsp;s - t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;can &nbsp;show &nbsp;as &nbsp;the &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;position &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body.</p>\n\n<p>Observing &nbsp;s &nbsp;- &nbsp;t &nbsp;graphs &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;accurately &nbsp; calculate &nbsp;the &nbsp;speed &nbsp;and &nbsp;also &nbsp;state &nbsp;whether &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;uniform ,&nbsp;non - uniform &nbsp;speed &nbsp;or &nbsp;whether &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>s &nbsp;- t &nbsp;graph for &nbsp;body &nbsp;moving &nbsp;with &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;speed</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig6.png" style="height:200px; width:250px" /></p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;moves &nbsp;with &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;speed , it coversequal &nbsp;distance &nbsp;every &nbsp;second or &nbsp;for &nbsp;equal increments in time , there is equal &nbsp;increments &nbsp;in &nbsp;distance. &nbsp;We &nbsp;can &nbsp;say &nbsp;distance &nbsp;is &nbsp;directly proportional &nbsp;to &nbsp;time &nbsp;in &nbsp;case of &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;speed.Obviously &nbsp;the &nbsp;s - t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;will be &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;inclined &nbsp;to &nbsp;both &nbsp;axes.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;the &nbsp;graph &nbsp;OB &nbsp;indicates &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;rise &nbsp;in &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;by moving &nbsp;body.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>For &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;moving &nbsp;in &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;distance - time &nbsp;graph &nbsp;also &nbsp;represents &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;time &nbsp;graph and &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;obtain &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;from &nbsp;t.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;motion , &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;distance &nbsp;and &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal. So &nbsp;are &nbsp;the &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;speed &nbsp;and &nbsp;velocity.</p>\n\n<p>Using &nbsp;s - t graph &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;easily &nbsp;find the &nbsp;speed.</p>\n\n<p>Consider &nbsp;point &nbsp;A &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;graph. &nbsp;It &nbsp;gives &nbsp;the &nbsp;position &nbsp;of &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;at &nbsp;that &nbsp;instant.</p>\n\n<p>To &nbsp;find &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;at &nbsp;position &nbsp;A, &nbsp;draw &nbsp;a &nbsp;horizental &nbsp;line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to X - axis from &nbsp;A &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;Y - axis. &nbsp;The &nbsp;point &nbsp;where &nbsp;it &nbsp;intersects Y - &nbsp;axis is &nbsp;called &nbsp;Y - co-ordinate &nbsp;of &nbsp;A. The &nbsp;Y - co-ordinate &nbsp;gives &nbsp;the &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;by &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;when &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;at &nbsp;A. For &nbsp;this &nbsp;we &nbsp;choose &nbsp;a &nbsp;suitable &nbsp;scale &nbsp;in &nbsp;terms &nbsp;of &nbsp;meters &nbsp;on &nbsp;y - &nbsp;axis</p>\n\n<p>Eg : &nbsp;1 cm &nbsp;on &nbsp;Y - axis &nbsp;= &nbsp;10 &nbsp;kilometers.</p>\n\n<p>Similarly &nbsp;by &nbsp;drawing &nbsp;a &nbsp;line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;Y - axis &nbsp;from &nbsp;A &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;X - axis, &nbsp;we &nbsp;get X - co-ordinate &nbsp;of &nbsp;A. &nbsp;The &nbsp;X - co-ordinate &nbsp;tells us &nbsp;the &nbsp;timesuitable &nbsp;scale &nbsp;like &nbsp;1 cm &nbsp;= &nbsp;20 min &nbsp;etc &nbsp;is &nbsp;selected &nbsp;on &nbsp;X - &nbsp;axis &nbsp;taken &nbsp;to &nbsp;reach &nbsp;position &nbsp;A</p>\n\n<p>This &nbsp;way &nbsp;for &nbsp;every &nbsp;point &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;inclined &nbsp;line, &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;find &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;and &nbsp;time &nbsp;taken . &nbsp;?What &nbsp;is &nbsp;speed ? It &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;of &nbsp;distance &nbsp;and &nbsp;time. It &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;of &nbsp;distance &nbsp;and &nbsp;time. &nbsp;Thus &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;find &nbsp;speed &nbsp;using &nbsp;s - t graph.</p>\n\n<p>Let &nbsp;$ s_{1} $ &nbsp;and &nbsp;$ s_{2} $ &nbsp;be &nbsp;the &nbsp;distances &nbsp;at &nbsp;A &nbsp;and &nbsp;B &nbsp;respectively.</p>\n\n<p>$ t_{1} $ , &nbsp;$ t_{2} $ &nbsp;be &nbsp;respective &nbsp;time</p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp;A &nbsp;draw &nbsp;a &nbsp;line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;X - axis &nbsp;from &nbsp;B &nbsp;draw &nbsp;a &nbsp;line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;Y - axis</p>\n\n<p>Both &nbsp;these &nbsp;lines &nbsp;intersect &nbsp;at &nbsp;&#39;C&#39; &nbsp;forming &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;ABC</p>\n\n<p>AC &nbsp;represents &nbsp;time &nbsp;interval &nbsp;$ t_{2} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ t_{1} $</p>\n\n<p>Bc &nbsp;represents &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;&nbsp;$ s_{2} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ s_{1} $ &nbsp;during &nbsp;this &nbsp;interval</p>\n\n<p>Speed &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;= &nbsp;v &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{s_{2} &nbsp; - &nbsp;&nbsp;s_{1}&nbsp;}{t_{2} &nbsp; - &nbsp;&nbsp;t_{1}} $</p>\n\n<p>As &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;moving &nbsp;with &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;speed , &nbsp;v &nbsp;represents &nbsp;speed &nbsp;at &nbsp;all positions &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;graph.</p>\n\n<p><strong>s - t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;for &nbsp;accelerated &nbsp;motion :</strong></p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;body &nbsp;covers &nbsp;unequal &nbsp;distance &nbsp;in &nbsp;equal &nbsp;intervals &nbsp;of &nbsp;time , &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;accelerated &nbsp;motion . &nbsp;Such &nbsp;a &nbsp;motion &nbsp;is &nbsp;also &nbsp;called &nbsp;non &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion. &nbsp;The &nbsp;body &nbsp;has &nbsp;non - &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;or &nbsp;variable &nbsp;speed.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;s - t graph &nbsp;will be &nbsp;a &nbsp;curve , a &nbsp;hyperbola &nbsp;or &nbsp;parabola.</p>\n\n<p>As &nbsp;explained &nbsp;before , &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;find &nbsp;$ s_{2} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ s_{1} $ &nbsp; in &nbsp;the &nbsp;time &nbsp;interval&nbsp;$ t_{2} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ t_{1} $</p>\n\n<p>Their &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;will give &nbsp;instanteneous &nbsp;speed</p>\n\n<p>$ v_{1} $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;$ \\frac{s_{2} &nbsp; - &nbsp;&nbsp;s_{1}&nbsp;}{t_{2} &nbsp; - &nbsp;&nbsp;t_{1}} $</p>\n\n<p>Since &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;non-uniform &nbsp;motion, &nbsp;speed &nbsp;will be &nbsp;different &nbsp;at &nbsp;different &nbsp;points &nbsp;on &nbsp;s - t &nbsp;curve.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;short , remember &nbsp;that &nbsp;slope &nbsp;of &nbsp;s - t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;gives &nbsp;speed</p>\n\n<p><strong>Velocity &nbsp;- &nbsp;time graphs :</strong></p>\n\n<p>Velocity [ v ] in &nbsp;m$ s^{-1&nbsp;} $ &nbsp;or &nbsp;km&nbsp;$ h^{-1&nbsp;} $ &nbsp;or &nbsp;cm&nbsp;$ s^{-1&nbsp;} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;taken &nbsp; on &nbsp;Y - axis &nbsp;with &nbsp;suitable &nbsp;scale . &nbsp;X - axis &nbsp;stands &nbsp;for &nbsp;time &nbsp;in &nbsp;second &nbsp;in &nbsp;suitable &nbsp;scale .</p>\n\n<p><strong>v - t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;for constant &nbsp;velocity :</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;It &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;horizantal &nbsp;line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;X - axis. The &nbsp;point &nbsp;where &nbsp;it &nbsp;intersects &nbsp;Y - axis &nbsp;gives &nbsp;the &nbsp;numerical &nbsp;value &nbsp;constant &nbsp;velocity.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig7.png" style="height:173px; width:300px" /></p>\n\n<p>Above &nbsp;graph &nbsp;represents &nbsp;body &nbsp;moving &nbsp;with &nbsp;instant &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;50 m$ s^{-1&nbsp;} $ .</p>\n\n<p>Area &nbsp;under &nbsp;v -t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;gives &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Lets &nbsp;say &nbsp;we &nbsp;want &nbsp;to &nbsp;find &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;A &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;during &nbsp;time &nbsp;interval &nbsp;CD &nbsp; i.e &nbsp;${t_{2} &nbsp; - &nbsp;&nbsp;t_{1}} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;30 - 10 &nbsp;= &nbsp;20 s</p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;can &nbsp;complete &nbsp;the &nbsp;rectangle &nbsp;ABCD.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;AB &nbsp;= &nbsp;CD &nbsp;= &nbsp;20</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;AC &nbsp;= &nbsp;BD &nbsp;= &nbsp;50</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; ABCD &nbsp;= &nbsp;20 &nbsp;X &nbsp;50 &nbsp;[ length &nbsp;x &nbsp;breadth ]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; = &nbsp;1000 &nbsp;m$ s^{-1&nbsp;} $ &nbsp;x &nbsp;s &nbsp;= &nbsp;1000 &nbsp;m &nbsp; = &nbsp;1 km</p>\n\n<p><strong>v - t graph &nbsp;for &nbsp;uniformly &nbsp;accelerated &nbsp;motion :</strong></p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;this &nbsp;motion , &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;increases &nbsp;by &nbsp;equal &nbsp;amounts &nbsp;in &nbsp;equal &nbsp;intervals &nbsp;of &nbsp;time. The &nbsp;accelaration &nbsp;is &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;or &nbsp;constant. If &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;increases &nbsp;by &nbsp;lets &nbsp;say &nbsp;5&nbsp;m$ s^{-1&nbsp;} $ &nbsp;in &nbsp;1st &nbsp;second, every &nbsp;second &nbsp;its increases by&nbsp;5&nbsp;m$ s^{-1&nbsp;} $ &nbsp;so &nbsp;that &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp;is &nbsp;constant &nbsp;at &nbsp;5&nbsp;m$ s^{-2&nbsp;} $ .</p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;can &nbsp;say &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;is &nbsp;directly &nbsp;proportional &nbsp;to &nbsp;time &nbsp;in &nbsp;uniformly &nbsp;accelerated &nbsp;motion . &nbsp;the &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;v &nbsp;- &nbsp;t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;will &nbsp;be &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;inclined &nbsp;to &nbsp;both &nbsp;axes.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig8.png" style="height:189px; width:250px" /></p>\n\n<p>Area &nbsp;under &nbsp;v - t graph &nbsp;is &nbsp;area &nbsp;of &nbsp;ABCDE.</p>\n\n<p>ABCDE &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;divided &nbsp;into &nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ &nbsp;ABC &nbsp;and ACDE</p>\n\n<p>Area &nbsp;of &nbsp;ABCDE &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ &nbsp;ABC &nbsp;+ &nbsp;ACDE</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; = &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $[ base x &nbsp;height ] &nbsp;+ &nbsp;[ length x &nbsp;breadth ]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; = &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $ [ AC x BC ] &nbsp;+ &nbsp;[ CD &nbsp;x &nbsp;DE ]</p>\n\n<p>Important &nbsp;thing &nbsp;to &nbsp;note &nbsp;here &nbsp;is &nbsp;that &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;is &nbsp;also &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;in &nbsp;case &nbsp;of &nbsp;uniformly &nbsp;accelerated &nbsp;motion. &nbsp;As &nbsp;the &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp;is &nbsp;costant, &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;must &nbsp;be &nbsp;moving &nbsp;in &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line.</p>\n\n<p>Thus &nbsp;area &nbsp;under &nbsp;v - t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;of &nbsp;uniformly &nbsp;accelerated &nbsp;motion &nbsp;gives &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;distance &nbsp;and &nbsp;displacemnt.</p>\n\n<p>For &nbsp;non &nbsp;uniformly &nbsp;accelerated &nbsp;motion, &nbsp;v - t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;can &nbsp;assume &nbsp;any &nbsp;shape .</p>\n\n<p><strong>Equations &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;by &nbsp;graphical &nbsp;method :</strong></p>\n\n<p>Here &nbsp;we &nbsp;consider &nbsp;only &nbsp;uniformly &nbsp;accelerated &nbsp;motion. This &nbsp;implies &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;moving &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;path &nbsp;with &nbsp;constant &nbsp;acceleration</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;We &nbsp;have &nbsp;3 &nbsp;equations &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; v &nbsp;= &nbsp;u &nbsp;+ &nbsp;at</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;s &nbsp;= &nbsp;ut &nbsp;+&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $ a$ t^{2} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;$ v^{2} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ u^{2} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;2as</p>\n\n<p>Although &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;derive &nbsp;these &nbsp;equations &nbsp;mathematically, &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;also &nbsp;use graphical &nbsp;methods &nbsp;as &nbsp;discussed &nbsp;below&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>Equation &nbsp;for &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;- &nbsp;time &nbsp;relation :</strong></p>\n\n<p>Let &nbsp;u &nbsp;be &nbsp;the &nbsp;initial &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;at &nbsp;t &nbsp;= &nbsp;0</p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp;increases &nbsp;uniformly &nbsp; at &nbsp;the &nbsp;rate &nbsp;&#39;a&#39; &nbsp;to &nbsp;&#39;v&#39; &nbsp;at &nbsp;time &nbsp;&#39;t&#39;</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig9.png" style="height:241px; width:350px" /></p>\n\n<p>BE &nbsp; = &nbsp;Y - coordinate &nbsp;of &nbsp;B &nbsp;[ velocity ]</p>\n\n<p>BC &nbsp;= &nbsp; X &nbsp;- coordinate &nbsp;of &nbsp;B &nbsp;[ time ]</p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp;the &nbsp;graph&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>initial &nbsp;velocity &nbsp; u &nbsp;= &nbsp;OA</p>\n\n<p>final &nbsp;velocity &nbsp; &nbsp;v &nbsp; = &nbsp;BC &nbsp;or &nbsp;OE</p>\n\n<p>time &nbsp; interval &nbsp; t &nbsp; = &nbsp; OC</p>\n\n<p>Draw &nbsp;AD &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;OC</p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp; the &nbsp;graph</p>\n\n<p>BC &nbsp;= &nbsp;BD &nbsp;+ &nbsp;DC &nbsp;= &nbsp;BD &nbsp;+ &nbsp;OA</p>\n\n<p>But &nbsp;BC &nbsp;= &nbsp;v&nbsp; and &nbsp; OA &nbsp;= &nbsp;u</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;v &nbsp; = &nbsp;BD &nbsp;+ &nbsp;u</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;BD &nbsp;= &nbsp;v &nbsp;- &nbsp;u &nbsp; ----------------- (1)</p>\n\n<p>Acceleration &nbsp; = &nbsp; $ \\frac{change &nbsp; in &nbsp;velocity}{time} $ &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; a &nbsp; = &nbsp;$ \\frac{BD}{AD} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; a &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{BD}{OC} $ &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; [ &nbsp; AD &nbsp;= &nbsp;OC]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;a &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{BD}{t} $ &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;[ &nbsp;OC &nbsp;= &nbsp;t ]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; BD &nbsp; = &nbsp;at ----------------- (2)</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;From &nbsp;equations &nbsp; (1) &nbsp; and &nbsp;(2)</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;v &nbsp;- u &nbsp;= &nbsp;at</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;v &nbsp;= &nbsp;u &nbsp;+ &nbsp;at</p>\n\n<p><strong>Equation &nbsp;for &nbsp;position &nbsp;- &nbsp;time &nbsp;relation :</strong></p>\n\n<p>Let &nbsp;s &nbsp;be &nbsp;thee &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;by &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;time &nbsp;t. &nbsp;we &nbsp;know &nbsp;area &nbsp;under &nbsp;v - t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;give &nbsp;s</p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp;the &nbsp;graph &nbsp;&#39;s&#39; &nbsp;is &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;area &nbsp;of &nbsp;OABC &nbsp;which &nbsp;forms &nbsp;trapezium</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; s &nbsp;= &nbsp;area &nbsp;[ OABC ]</p>\n\n<p>OABC &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;divided &nbsp;into &nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ ABD &nbsp;and &nbsp;OADC</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;s &nbsp;= &nbsp;area &nbsp;[$ \\bigtriangleup $ ABD] &nbsp;+ &nbsp;area &nbsp;[ OADC ]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $ [ AD x BD ] &nbsp;+ &nbsp;OA &nbsp;x &nbsp;OC</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; OA &nbsp;= u , &nbsp;OC &nbsp;= AD &nbsp;= &nbsp;t , &nbsp;BD &nbsp;= at</p>\n\n<p>s &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $ [ t&nbsp;x at&nbsp;] &nbsp;+ [ u&nbsp; x &nbsp;t ]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; = &nbsp;[ u&nbsp; x &nbsp;t ] &nbsp;+ &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $ [ t&nbsp;x at&nbsp;]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; s &nbsp;= &nbsp;ut &nbsp;+ &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $ a$ t^{2} $</p>\n\n<p><strong>Equation &nbsp;for &nbsp;position &nbsp;- &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;relation :</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;s &nbsp; = &nbsp; area &nbsp;of &nbsp;trapezium &nbsp;OABC</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; s &nbsp;= &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{(OA + BC) &nbsp;*&nbsp;&nbsp;OC}{2} $</p>\n\n<p>OA &nbsp;= &nbsp;u , &nbsp;BC &nbsp;= &nbsp;v , &nbsp;OC &nbsp;= &nbsp;t&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; s &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{(u + v) t}{2} $ --------------- (1)</p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;have &nbsp;already &nbsp;derived &nbsp;v &nbsp; = &nbsp;u &nbsp;+ &nbsp;at</p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp;this &nbsp;, &nbsp;we &nbsp;get</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;t &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{v &nbsp;- u}{a} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;Put &nbsp; in &nbsp;equation &nbsp;(1)</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; s &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$[ \\frac{(u + v) }{2}] $&nbsp;$ [\\frac{v &nbsp;-&nbsp;u}{a}] $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Rearranging , &nbsp;we get</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; s &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{(v &nbsp;+&nbsp;u)(v &nbsp;- u)}{2a}&nbsp;$</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; s &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$&nbsp;\\frac{&nbsp;v^{2} &nbsp; - &nbsp;&nbsp;u^{2} }{2a}&nbsp;$</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;$ v^{2} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ u^{2} $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;2as</p>\n', 'Graphical   Representation  of  motion', '', '<p>Graphs &nbsp;give &nbsp;pictorial &nbsp;information. &nbsp;To &nbsp;represent &nbsp;the &nbsp;motion , to &nbsp;understand it , to &nbsp;analyse it &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;use &nbsp;graphs. We &nbsp;can &nbsp;get &nbsp;line &nbsp;graphs &nbsp;for &nbsp;motion &nbsp;by &nbsp;plotting &nbsp;various &nbsp;physical &nbsp;quantities &nbsp;associated &nbsp;with &nbsp;motion &nbsp;against &nbsp;time. Thus &nbsp;we &nbsp;get &nbsp;distance - time , velocity - time &nbsp;or &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp;- &nbsp;time &nbsp;graphs. Using &nbsp;these &nbsp;graph &nbsp;we can &nbsp;calculate &nbsp;unknown &nbsp;physical &nbsp;quantity &nbsp;in &nbsp;that &nbsp;motion. &nbsp;similarly &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;obtain &nbsp;equations &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;from &nbsp;the &nbsp;graphs.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>Distance &nbsp;- time &nbsp;graphs :</strong></p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;take &nbsp;distance [ s ] &nbsp;in &nbsp;meters &nbsp;or &nbsp;sometimes &nbsp;in &nbsp;centimeters &nbsp;on &nbsp;Y - axis , and &nbsp;time [ t ] &nbsp;in &nbsp;seconds &nbsp;on &nbsp;X&nbsp;- axis</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;resultant &nbsp;s - t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;can &nbsp;show &nbsp;as &nbsp;the &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;position &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body.</p>\n\n<p>Observing &nbsp;s &nbsp;- &nbsp;t &nbsp;graphs &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;accurately &nbsp; calculate &nbsp;the &nbsp;speed &nbsp;and &nbsp;also &nbsp;state &nbsp;whether &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;uniform ,&nbsp;non - uniform &nbsp;speed &nbsp;or &nbsp;whether &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>s &nbsp;- t &nbsp;graph for &nbsp;body &nbsp;moving &nbsp;with &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;speed</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig6.png" style="height:200px; width:250px" /></p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;moves &nbsp;with &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;speed , it coversequal &nbsp;distance &nbsp;every &nbsp;second or &nbsp;for &nbsp;equal increments in time , there is equal &nbsp;increments &nbsp;in &nbsp;distance. &nbsp;We &nbsp;can &nbsp;say &nbsp;distance &nbsp;is &nbsp;directly proportional &nbsp;to &nbsp;time &nbsp;in &nbsp;case of &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;speed.Obviously &nbsp;the &nbsp;s - t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;will be &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;inclined &nbsp;to &nbsp;both &nbsp;axes.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;the &nbsp;graph &nbsp;OB &nbsp;indicates &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;rise &nbsp;in &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;by moving &nbsp;body.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>For &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;moving &nbsp;in &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;distance - time &nbsp;graph &nbsp;also &nbsp;represents &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;time &nbsp;graph and &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;obtain &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;from &nbsp;t.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;motion , &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;distance &nbsp;and &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal. So &nbsp;are &nbsp;the &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;speed &nbsp;and &nbsp;velocity.</p>\n\n<p>Using &nbsp;s - t graph &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;easily &nbsp;find the &nbsp;speed.</p>\n\n<p>Consider &nbsp;point &nbsp;A &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;graph. &nbsp;It &nbsp;gives &nbsp;the &nbsp;position &nbsp;of &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;at &nbsp;that &nbsp;instant.</p>\n\n<p>To &nbsp;find &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;at &nbsp;position &nbsp;A, &nbsp;draw &nbsp;a &nbsp;horizental &nbsp;line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to X - axis from &nbsp;A &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;Y - axis. &nbsp;The &nbsp;point &nbsp;where &nbsp;it &nbsp;intersects Y - &nbsp;axis is &nbsp;called &nbsp;Y - co-ordinate &nbsp;of &nbsp;A. The &nbsp;Y - co-ordinate &nbsp;gives &nbsp;the &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;by &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;when &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;at &nbsp;A. For &nbsp;this &nbsp;we &nbsp;choose &nbsp;a &nbsp;suitable &nbsp;scale &nbsp;in &nbsp;terms &nbsp;of &nbsp;meters &nbsp;on &nbsp;y - &nbsp;axis</p>\n\n<p>Eg : &nbsp;1 cm &nbsp;on &nbsp;Y - axis &nbsp;= &nbsp;10 &nbsp;kilometers.</p>\n\n<p>Similarly &nbsp;by &nbsp;drawing &nbsp;a &nbsp;line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;Y - axis &nbsp;from &nbsp;A &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;X - axis, &nbsp;we &nbsp;get X - co-ordinate &nbsp;of &nbsp;A. &nbsp;The &nbsp;X - co-ordinate &nbsp;tells us &nbsp;the &nbsp;timesuitable &nbsp;scale &nbsp;like &nbsp;1 cm &nbsp;= &nbsp;20 min &nbsp;etc &nbsp;is &nbsp;selected &nbsp;on &nbsp;X - &nbsp;axis &nbsp;taken &nbsp;to &nbsp;reach &nbsp;position &nbsp;A</p>\n\n<p>This &nbsp;way &nbsp;for &nbsp;every &nbsp;point &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;inclined &nbsp;line, &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;find &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;and &nbsp;time &nbsp;taken . &nbsp;?What &nbsp;is &nbsp;speed ? It &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;of &nbsp;distance &nbsp;and &nbsp;time. It &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;of &nbsp;distance &nbsp;and &nbsp;time. &nbsp;Thus &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;find &nbsp;speed &nbsp;using &nbsp;s - t graph.</p>\n\n<p>Let &nbsp;$ s_{1} $ &nbsp;and &nbsp;$ s_{2} $ &nbsp;be &nbsp;the &nbsp;distances &nbsp;at &nbsp;A &nbsp;and &nbsp;B &nbsp;respectively.</p>\n\n<p>$ t_{1} $ , &nbsp;$ t_{2} $ &nbsp;be &nbsp;respective &nbsp;time</p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp;A &nbsp;draw &nbsp;a &nbsp;line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;X - axis &nbsp;from &nbsp;B &nbsp;draw &nbsp;a &nbsp;line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;Y - axis</p>\n\n<p>Both &nbsp;these &nbsp;lines &nbsp;intersect &nbsp;at &nbsp;&#39;C&#39; &nbsp;forming &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;ABC</p>\n\n<p>AC &nbsp;represents &nbsp;time &nbsp;interval &nbsp;$ t_{2} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ t_{1} $</p>\n\n<p>Bc &nbsp;represents &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;&nbsp;$ s_{2} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ s_{1} $ &nbsp;during &nbsp;this &nbsp;interval</p>\n\n<p>Speed &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;= &nbsp;v &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{s_{2} &nbsp; - &nbsp;&nbsp;s_{1}&nbsp;}{t_{2} &nbsp; - &nbsp;&nbsp;t_{1}} $</p>\n\n<p>As &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;moving &nbsp;with &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;speed , &nbsp;v &nbsp;represents &nbsp;speed &nbsp;at &nbsp;all positions &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;graph.</p>\n\n<p><strong>s - t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;for &nbsp;accelerated &nbsp;motion :</strong></p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;body &nbsp;covers &nbsp;unequal &nbsp;distance &nbsp;in &nbsp;equal &nbsp;intervals &nbsp;of &nbsp;time , &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;accelerated &nbsp;motion . &nbsp;Such &nbsp;a &nbsp;motion &nbsp;is &nbsp;also &nbsp;called &nbsp;non &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion. &nbsp;The &nbsp;body &nbsp;has &nbsp;non - &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;or &nbsp;variable &nbsp;speed.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;s - t graph &nbsp;will be &nbsp;a &nbsp;curve , a &nbsp;hyperbola &nbsp;or &nbsp;parabola.</p>\n\n<p>As &nbsp;explained &nbsp;before , &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;find &nbsp;$ s_{2} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ s_{1} $ &nbsp; in &nbsp;the &nbsp;time &nbsp;interval&nbsp;$ t_{2} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ t_{1} $</p>\n\n<p>Their &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;will give &nbsp;instanteneous &nbsp;speed</p>\n\n<p>$ v_{1} $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;$ \\frac{s_{2} &nbsp; - &nbsp;&nbsp;s_{1}&nbsp;}{t_{2} &nbsp; - &nbsp;&nbsp;t_{1}} $</p>\n\n<p>Since &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;non-uniform &nbsp;motion, &nbsp;speed &nbsp;will be &nbsp;different &nbsp;at &nbsp;different &nbsp;points &nbsp;on &nbsp;s - t &nbsp;curve.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;short , remember &nbsp;that &nbsp;slope &nbsp;of &nbsp;s - t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;gives &nbsp;speed</p>\n\n<p><strong>Velocity &nbsp;- &nbsp;time graphs :</strong></p>\n\n<p>Velocity [ v ] in &nbsp;m$ s^{-1&nbsp;} $ &nbsp;or &nbsp;km&nbsp;$ h^{-1&nbsp;} $ &nbsp;or &nbsp;cm&nbsp;$ s^{-1&nbsp;} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;taken &nbsp; on &nbsp;Y - axis &nbsp;with &nbsp;suitable &nbsp;scale . &nbsp;X - axis &nbsp;stands &nbsp;for &nbsp;time &nbsp;in &nbsp;second &nbsp;in &nbsp;suitable &nbsp;scale .</p>\n\n<p><strong>v - t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;for constant &nbsp;velocity :</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;It &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;horizantal &nbsp;line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;X - axis. The &nbsp;point &nbsp;where &nbsp;it &nbsp;intersects &nbsp;Y - axis &nbsp;gives &nbsp;the &nbsp;numerical &nbsp;value &nbsp;constant &nbsp;velocity.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig7.png" style="height:173px; width:300px" /></p>\n\n<p>Above &nbsp;graph &nbsp;represents &nbsp;body &nbsp;moving &nbsp;with &nbsp;instant &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;50 m$ s^{-1&nbsp;} $ .</p>\n\n<p>Area &nbsp;under &nbsp;v -t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;gives &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Lets &nbsp;say &nbsp;we &nbsp;want &nbsp;to &nbsp;find &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;A &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;during &nbsp;time &nbsp;interval &nbsp;CD &nbsp; i.e &nbsp;${t_{2} &nbsp; - &nbsp;&nbsp;t_{1}} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;30 - 10 &nbsp;= &nbsp;20 s</p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;can &nbsp;complete &nbsp;the &nbsp;rectangle &nbsp;ABCD.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;AB &nbsp;= &nbsp;CD &nbsp;= &nbsp;20</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;AC &nbsp;= &nbsp;BD &nbsp;= &nbsp;50</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; ABCD &nbsp;= &nbsp;20 &nbsp;X &nbsp;50 &nbsp;[ length &nbsp;x &nbsp;breadth ]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; = &nbsp;1000 &nbsp;m$ s^{-1&nbsp;} $ &nbsp;x &nbsp;s &nbsp;= &nbsp;1000 &nbsp;m &nbsp; = &nbsp;1 km</p>\n\n<p><strong>v - t graph &nbsp;for &nbsp;uniformly &nbsp;accelerated &nbsp;motion :</strong></p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;this &nbsp;motion , &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;increases &nbsp;by &nbsp;equal &nbsp;amounts &nbsp;in &nbsp;equal &nbsp;intervals &nbsp;of &nbsp;time. The &nbsp;accelaration &nbsp;is &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;or &nbsp;constant. If &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;increases &nbsp;by &nbsp;lets &nbsp;say &nbsp;5&nbsp;m$ s^{-1&nbsp;} $ &nbsp;in &nbsp;1st &nbsp;second, every &nbsp;second &nbsp;its increases by&nbsp;5&nbsp;m$ s^{-1&nbsp;} $ &nbsp;so &nbsp;that &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp;is &nbsp;constant &nbsp;at &nbsp;5&nbsp;m$ s^{-2&nbsp;} $ .</p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;can &nbsp;say &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;is &nbsp;directly &nbsp;proportional &nbsp;to &nbsp;time &nbsp;in &nbsp;uniformly &nbsp;accelerated &nbsp;motion . &nbsp;the &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;v &nbsp;- &nbsp;t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;will &nbsp;be &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;inclined &nbsp;to &nbsp;both &nbsp;axes.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig8.png" style="height:189px; width:250px" /></p>\n\n<p>Area &nbsp;under &nbsp;v - t graph &nbsp;is &nbsp;area &nbsp;of &nbsp;ABCDE.</p>\n\n<p>ABCDE &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;divided &nbsp;into &nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ &nbsp;ABC &nbsp;and ACDE</p>\n\n<p>Area &nbsp;of &nbsp;ABCDE &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ &nbsp;ABC &nbsp;+ &nbsp;ACDE</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; = &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $[ base x &nbsp;height ] &nbsp;+ &nbsp;[ length x &nbsp;breadth ]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; = &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $ [ AC x BC ] &nbsp;+ &nbsp;[ CD &nbsp;x &nbsp;DE ]</p>\n\n<p>Important &nbsp;thing &nbsp;to &nbsp;note &nbsp;here &nbsp;is &nbsp;that &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;displacement &nbsp;is &nbsp;also &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;in &nbsp;case &nbsp;of &nbsp;uniformly &nbsp;accelerated &nbsp;motion. &nbsp;As &nbsp;the &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp;is &nbsp;costant, &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;must &nbsp;be &nbsp;moving &nbsp;in &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line.</p>\n\n<p>Thus &nbsp;area &nbsp;under &nbsp;v - t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;of &nbsp;uniformly &nbsp;accelerated &nbsp;motion &nbsp;gives &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;distance &nbsp;and &nbsp;displacemnt.</p>\n\n<p>For &nbsp;non &nbsp;uniformly &nbsp;accelerated &nbsp;motion, &nbsp;v - t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;can &nbsp;assume &nbsp;any &nbsp;shape .</p>\n\n<p><strong>Equations &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;by &nbsp;graphical &nbsp;method :</strong></p>\n\n<p>Here &nbsp;we &nbsp;consider &nbsp;only &nbsp;uniformly &nbsp;accelerated &nbsp;motion. This &nbsp;implies &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;moving &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;path &nbsp;with &nbsp;constant &nbsp;acceleration</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;We &nbsp;have &nbsp;3 &nbsp;equations &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; v &nbsp;= &nbsp;u &nbsp;+ &nbsp;at</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;s &nbsp;= &nbsp;ut &nbsp;+&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $ a$ t^{2} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;$ v^{2} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ u^{2} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;2as</p>\n\n<p>Although &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;derive &nbsp;these &nbsp;equations &nbsp;mathematically, &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;also &nbsp;use graphical &nbsp;methods &nbsp;as &nbsp;discussed &nbsp;below&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>Equation &nbsp;for &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;- &nbsp;time &nbsp;relation :</strong></p>\n\n<p>Let &nbsp;u &nbsp;be &nbsp;the &nbsp;initial &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;at &nbsp;t &nbsp;= &nbsp;0</p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp;increases &nbsp;uniformly &nbsp; at &nbsp;the &nbsp;rate &nbsp;&#39;a&#39; &nbsp;to &nbsp;&#39;v&#39; &nbsp;at &nbsp;time &nbsp;&#39;t&#39;</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig9.png" style="height:241px; width:350px" /></p>\n\n<p>BE &nbsp; = &nbsp;Y - coordinate &nbsp;of &nbsp;B &nbsp;[ velocity ]</p>\n\n<p>BC &nbsp;= &nbsp; X &nbsp;- coordinate &nbsp;of &nbsp;B &nbsp;[ time ]</p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp;the &nbsp;graph&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>initial &nbsp;velocity &nbsp; u &nbsp;= &nbsp;OA</p>\n\n<p>final &nbsp;velocity &nbsp; &nbsp;v &nbsp; = &nbsp;BC &nbsp;or &nbsp;OE</p>\n\n<p>time &nbsp; interval &nbsp; t &nbsp; = &nbsp; OC</p>\n\n<p>Draw &nbsp;AD &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;OC</p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp; the &nbsp;graph</p>\n\n<p>BC &nbsp;= &nbsp;BD &nbsp;+ &nbsp;DC &nbsp;= &nbsp;BD &nbsp;+ &nbsp;OA</p>\n\n<p>But &nbsp;BC &nbsp;= &nbsp;v&nbsp; and &nbsp; OA &nbsp;= &nbsp;u</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;v &nbsp; = &nbsp;BD &nbsp;+ &nbsp;u</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;BD &nbsp;= &nbsp;v &nbsp;- &nbsp;u &nbsp; ----------------- (1)</p>\n\n<p>Acceleration &nbsp; = &nbsp; $ \\frac{change &nbsp; in &nbsp;velocity}{time} $ &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; a &nbsp; = &nbsp;$ \\frac{BD}{AD} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; a &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{BD}{OC} $ &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; [ &nbsp; AD &nbsp;= &nbsp;OC]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;a &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{BD}{t} $ &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;[ &nbsp;OC &nbsp;= &nbsp;t ]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; BD &nbsp; = &nbsp;at ----------------- (2)</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;From &nbsp;equations &nbsp; (1) &nbsp; and &nbsp;(2)</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;v &nbsp;- u &nbsp;= &nbsp;at</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;v &nbsp;= &nbsp;u &nbsp;+ &nbsp;at</p>\n\n<p><strong>Equation &nbsp;for &nbsp;position &nbsp;- &nbsp;time &nbsp;relation :</strong></p>\n\n<p>Let &nbsp;s &nbsp;be &nbsp;thee &nbsp;distance &nbsp;covered &nbsp;by &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;time &nbsp;t. &nbsp;we &nbsp;know &nbsp;area &nbsp;under &nbsp;v - t &nbsp;graph &nbsp;give &nbsp;s</p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp;the &nbsp;graph &nbsp;&#39;s&#39; &nbsp;is &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;area &nbsp;of &nbsp;OABC &nbsp;which &nbsp;forms &nbsp;trapezium</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; s &nbsp;= &nbsp;area &nbsp;[ OABC ]</p>\n\n<p>OABC &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;divided &nbsp;into &nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ ABD &nbsp;and &nbsp;OADC</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;s &nbsp;= &nbsp;area &nbsp;[$ \\bigtriangleup $ ABD] &nbsp;+ &nbsp;area &nbsp;[ OADC ]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $ [ AD x BD ] &nbsp;+ &nbsp;OA &nbsp;x &nbsp;OC</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; OA &nbsp;= u , &nbsp;OC &nbsp;= AD &nbsp;= &nbsp;t , &nbsp;BD &nbsp;= at</p>\n\n<p>s &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $ [ t&nbsp;x at&nbsp;] &nbsp;+ [ u&nbsp; x &nbsp;t ]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; = &nbsp;[ u&nbsp; x &nbsp;t ] &nbsp;+ &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $ [ t&nbsp;x at&nbsp;]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; s &nbsp;= &nbsp;ut &nbsp;+ &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $ a$ t^{2} $</p>\n\n<p><strong>Equation &nbsp;for &nbsp;position &nbsp;- &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;relation :</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;s &nbsp; = &nbsp; area &nbsp;of &nbsp;trapezium &nbsp;OABC</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; s &nbsp;= &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{(OA + BC) &nbsp;*&nbsp;&nbsp;OC}{2} $</p>\n\n<p>OA &nbsp;= &nbsp;u , &nbsp;BC &nbsp;= &nbsp;v , &nbsp;OC &nbsp;= &nbsp;t&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; s &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{(u + v) t}{2} $ --------------- (1)</p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;have &nbsp;already &nbsp;derived &nbsp;v &nbsp; = &nbsp;u &nbsp;+ &nbsp;at</p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp;this &nbsp;, &nbsp;we &nbsp;get</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;t &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{v &nbsp;- u}{a} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;Put &nbsp; in &nbsp;equation &nbsp;(1)</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; s &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$[ \\frac{(u + v) }{2}] $&nbsp;$ [\\frac{v &nbsp;-&nbsp;u}{a}] $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Rearranging , &nbsp;we get</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; s &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{(v &nbsp;+&nbsp;u)(v &nbsp;- u)}{2a}&nbsp;$</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; s &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$&nbsp;\\frac{&nbsp;v^{2} &nbsp; - &nbsp;&nbsp;u^{2} }{2a}&nbsp;$</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;$ v^{2} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ u^{2} $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;2as</p>\n', 0, 0),
(95, 'inline_html', '<p>A &nbsp;body &nbsp;moving &nbsp;on &nbsp;a &nbsp;circular &nbsp;path &nbsp;executes &nbsp;circular &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p>Eg : &nbsp;Cyclist &nbsp;in &nbsp;velodrome</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;performs &nbsp;circular &nbsp;motion &nbsp;at &nbsp;constant &nbsp;speed &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;is &nbsp;uniform, &nbsp;such &nbsp;a &nbsp;motion &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;circular &nbsp;motion.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;circular &nbsp;motion , &nbsp;even &nbsp;though &nbsp;speed &nbsp;is &nbsp;constant, &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;continuously &nbsp;changes &nbsp;due &nbsp;to &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p>As &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;changes, &nbsp;body &nbsp;experiences &nbsp;acceleration. &nbsp;As &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;velocity ( speed ) is &nbsp;constant, &nbsp;acceleration is &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;or &nbsp;constant.</p>\n\n<p>Let &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;move &nbsp;along &nbsp;a &nbsp;circle &nbsp;of &nbsp;radius &nbsp;r. &nbsp;In &nbsp;one &nbsp;revoluation &nbsp;it &nbsp;covers &nbsp;distance &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;its &nbsp;circumference &nbsp;which &nbsp;is &nbsp;2$ \\prod $ r</p>\n\n<p>Let &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;completes &nbsp;one &nbsp;revoluation &nbsp;in &nbsp;time &nbsp;t</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Its &nbsp;velocity ( v ) &nbsp;is</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;v &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{2&nbsp;\\prod &nbsp;r}{t} $</p>\n\n<p>At &nbsp;any &nbsp;point &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;found &nbsp;by &nbsp;drawing &nbsp;a &nbsp;tangent &nbsp;at &nbsp;the &nbsp;point &nbsp;on &nbsp;the circumference</p>\n', 'Uniform  Circular  Motion :', '', '<p>A &nbsp;body &nbsp;moving &nbsp;on &nbsp;a &nbsp;circular &nbsp;path &nbsp;executes &nbsp;circular &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p>Eg : &nbsp;Cyclist &nbsp;in &nbsp;velodrome</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;performs &nbsp;circular &nbsp;motion &nbsp;at &nbsp;constant &nbsp;speed &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;is &nbsp;uniform, &nbsp;such &nbsp;a &nbsp;motion &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;circular &nbsp;motion.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;circular &nbsp;motion , &nbsp;even &nbsp;though &nbsp;speed &nbsp;is &nbsp;constant, &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;continuously &nbsp;changes &nbsp;due &nbsp;to &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p>As &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;changes, &nbsp;body &nbsp;experiences &nbsp;acceleration. &nbsp;As &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;velocity ( speed ) is &nbsp;constant, &nbsp;acceleration is &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;or &nbsp;constant.</p>\n\n<p>Let &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;move &nbsp;along &nbsp;a &nbsp;circle &nbsp;of &nbsp;radius &nbsp;r. &nbsp;In &nbsp;one &nbsp;revoluation &nbsp;it &nbsp;covers &nbsp;distance &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;its &nbsp;circumference &nbsp;which &nbsp;is &nbsp;2$ \\prod $ r</p>\n\n<p>Let &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;completes &nbsp;one &nbsp;revoluation &nbsp;in &nbsp;time &nbsp;t</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Its &nbsp;velocity ( v ) &nbsp;is</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;v &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{2&nbsp;\\prod &nbsp;r}{t} $</p>\n\n<p>At &nbsp;any &nbsp;point &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;found &nbsp;by &nbsp;drawing &nbsp;a &nbsp;tangent &nbsp;at &nbsp;the &nbsp;point &nbsp;on &nbsp;the circumference</p>\n', 0, 0),
(96, 'inline_html', '<p>We &nbsp;have &nbsp;studied &nbsp;various &nbsp;aspects &nbsp;like &nbsp;position , &nbsp;rest , &nbsp; velocity &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;moving &nbsp;linearly &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;in &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line. &nbsp;However , we &nbsp;overlooked &nbsp;one &nbsp;important &nbsp;fact. &nbsp;What &nbsp;causes &nbsp;the &nbsp;motion &nbsp;in &nbsp;first &nbsp;place ? &nbsp;Why &nbsp;do &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;move&nbsp;?&nbsp; How &nbsp;moving &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;change &nbsp;their &nbsp;velocity ? &nbsp;How &nbsp;do &nbsp;they &nbsp;come &nbsp;to &nbsp;rest ? &nbsp;What &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;natural &nbsp;state &nbsp;or &nbsp;tendency &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;body ? &nbsp;Is &nbsp;it &nbsp;rest &nbsp;or &nbsp;is &nbsp;it &nbsp;motion ?</p>\n\n<p>All these &nbsp;questions &nbsp;have &nbsp;been &nbsp;puzzling &nbsp;scientists , &nbsp;philosophers &nbsp;since &nbsp;anicent &nbsp;times.</p>\n\n<p>Many &nbsp;along &nbsp;with &nbsp;aristotle &nbsp;considered &nbsp;it &nbsp;to &nbsp;be &nbsp;rest. &nbsp;Any &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;after &nbsp;some &nbsp;time &nbsp;comes &nbsp;to &nbsp;rest. &nbsp;This &nbsp;is &nbsp;what &nbsp;we &nbsp;observe &nbsp;every where. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;You &nbsp;kick &nbsp;a &nbsp;ball , &nbsp;it &nbsp;moves &nbsp;some &nbsp;distance &nbsp;then &nbsp;stop. A &nbsp;moving &nbsp;vechile &nbsp;when &nbsp;switched &nbsp;off &nbsp;covers &nbsp;some &nbsp;distance &nbsp;then &nbsp;comes &nbsp;to &nbsp;rest.</p>\n\n<p>This &nbsp;was &nbsp;commonly &nbsp;held &nbsp;belief , &nbsp;untill &nbsp;Galileo &nbsp;first , &nbsp;then &nbsp;Newton &nbsp;proposed &nbsp;completely &nbsp;new &nbsp;point &nbsp;of &nbsp;view &nbsp;regarding &nbsp;motion &nbsp;and &nbsp;what &nbsp;causes &nbsp;it.</p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp;is &nbsp;common &nbsp;observation &nbsp;that &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest &nbsp;cannot &nbsp;move &nbsp;on &nbsp;its &nbsp;own. &nbsp;Some &nbsp;effort &nbsp;is &nbsp;needed. &nbsp;Even &nbsp;when &nbsp;we &nbsp;talk &nbsp;or &nbsp;run , &nbsp;after &nbsp;some &nbsp;time &nbsp;we &nbsp;get &nbsp;tired . &nbsp;This &nbsp;means &nbsp;we &nbsp;are &nbsp;putting &nbsp;some &nbsp;effort. &nbsp;Similarly &nbsp;you &nbsp;have &nbsp;to &nbsp;kick &nbsp;a &nbsp;ball &nbsp;or &nbsp;pedal &nbsp;a &nbsp;cycle &nbsp;to &nbsp;move &nbsp;them.</p>\n\n<p>These &nbsp;examples &nbsp;shows &nbsp;that &nbsp;some &nbsp;muscular &nbsp;effort &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;form &nbsp;of &nbsp; push &nbsp;or &nbsp;pull &nbsp;or &nbsp;hit &nbsp;is &nbsp;involved &nbsp;to &nbsp;set &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;in &nbsp;motion.</p>\n\n<p>Thus &nbsp;push &nbsp;or &nbsp;pull &nbsp;or &nbsp;hit &nbsp;is &nbsp;what &nbsp;we &nbsp;call &nbsp;force &nbsp;from &nbsp;our &nbsp;daily &nbsp;observations &nbsp;we &nbsp;know &nbsp;that &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;required &nbsp;to &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>1. &nbsp;Set &nbsp;a &nbsp;stationary &nbsp;body &nbsp;in &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p>2. &nbsp;To &nbsp;bring &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;to &nbsp;rest</p>\n\n<p>3. &nbsp;Change &nbsp;[either &nbsp;increase &nbsp;or &nbsp;decrease ] &nbsp;speed</p>\n\n<p>4. &nbsp;Change &nbsp;the &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body.</p>\n\n<p>5. &nbsp;Change &nbsp;size &nbsp;or &nbsp;shape &nbsp;or &nbsp;both [ dimensions ] of &nbsp;a &nbsp;body. &nbsp;Eg: &nbsp;A &nbsp;spring &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;streched &nbsp;or &nbsp;compressed &nbsp;by &nbsp;applying &nbsp;suitable &nbsp;force &nbsp;to &nbsp;it.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Introduction', '', '<p>We &nbsp;have &nbsp;studied &nbsp;various &nbsp;aspects &nbsp;like &nbsp;position , &nbsp;rest , &nbsp; velocity &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;moving &nbsp;linearly &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;in &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line. &nbsp;However , we &nbsp;overlooked &nbsp;one &nbsp;important &nbsp;fact. &nbsp;What &nbsp;causes &nbsp;the &nbsp;motion &nbsp;in &nbsp