(97, 'inline_html', '<p>Consider &nbsp;a &nbsp;iron &nbsp;ball &nbsp;with &nbsp;chain &nbsp;attached &nbsp;to &nbsp;its &nbsp;two &nbsp;sides</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig1(1).png" style="height:100px; width:350px" /></p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;you &nbsp;pull &nbsp;only &nbsp;chain &nbsp;A , &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball moves &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;right.</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;you &nbsp;pull &nbsp;only &nbsp;chain &nbsp;B , &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball &nbsp;moves &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;left.</p>\n\n<p>Observe &nbsp;that &nbsp;ball &nbsp;is &nbsp;moving &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;pull &nbsp;or &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>Now &nbsp;apply &nbsp;equal &nbsp;pull &nbsp;force &nbsp;to &nbsp;both &nbsp;A &nbsp;and &nbsp;B. What &nbsp;do &nbsp;you &nbsp;observe ? &nbsp;Does &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball &nbsp;move ? &nbsp;The &nbsp;ball &nbsp;does &nbsp;not &nbsp;move &nbsp;at &nbsp;all , &nbsp;neither &nbsp;to &nbsp;right &nbsp;nor &nbsp;to &nbsp;left. &nbsp;Gradually &nbsp;increase &nbsp;the &nbsp;force &nbsp;equally , still &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball &nbsp;does &nbsp;not &nbsp;move.</p>\n\n<p>You &nbsp;will &nbsp;notice &nbsp;that &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;A &nbsp;is &nbsp;exactly &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;B &nbsp;in &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;but &nbsp;exactly &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;in &nbsp;direction. Even &nbsp;though &nbsp;2 &nbsp;forces &nbsp;are &nbsp;acting &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball , &nbsp;it &nbsp;still does &nbsp;not &nbsp;move. Such &nbsp;forces &nbsp;which &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;and &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;to &nbsp;each &nbsp;other , &nbsp;cancelling &nbsp;each &nbsp;others &nbsp;effect &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;on &nbsp;which &nbsp;they &nbsp;act &nbsp;simultenously , &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;balanced &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig2(1).png" style="height:147px; width:500px" />Remember &nbsp;that &nbsp;when &nbsp;number &nbsp;of &nbsp;balanced &nbsp;forces &nbsp;act &nbsp;on &nbsp;a &nbsp;body , &nbsp;the &nbsp;net &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;zero. &nbsp;hence &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;does &nbsp;not &nbsp;move. &nbsp;The &nbsp;resultent &nbsp;of &nbsp;balanced &nbsp;forces &nbsp;is &nbsp;always &nbsp;zero.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Now &nbsp;apply &nbsp;unequal &nbsp;forces &nbsp;[&nbsp;$ F_{A} $ &nbsp;&gt; &nbsp;$ F_{B} $ &nbsp;or &nbsp;$ F_{B} $ &nbsp;&gt; &nbsp;$ F_{A} $ ]</p>\n\n<p>You &nbsp;will &nbsp;see &nbsp;that &nbsp;ball &nbsp;moves &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;greater &nbsp;force. &nbsp;Such &nbsp;forces &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;un balanced &nbsp;forces.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;resultant &nbsp;of &nbsp;unbalanced &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;never &nbsp;zero. &nbsp;Hence &nbsp;net &nbsp;force &nbsp;acts &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;greatest &nbsp;force &nbsp;and &nbsp;body &nbsp;moves &nbsp;in &nbsp;this &nbsp;direction .</p>\n\n<p>Whenever &nbsp;you &nbsp;try &nbsp;to &nbsp;push &nbsp;any &nbsp;object &nbsp;for &nbsp;example &nbsp;table , &nbsp;it &nbsp;initially &nbsp;shows &nbsp;some &nbsp;resistance &nbsp;to &nbsp;movement. &nbsp;Force &nbsp;of &nbsp;friction &nbsp;is &nbsp;set &nbsp;up &nbsp;between &nbsp;surfaces &nbsp;of &nbsp;that &nbsp;object &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;ground. &nbsp;This &nbsp;frinctional &nbsp;force &nbsp;always &nbsp;acts &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;direction &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;applied &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>Now &nbsp;if &nbsp;you &nbsp;increase &nbsp;the &nbsp;applied &nbsp;force , &nbsp;it &nbsp;may &nbsp;still &nbsp;not &nbsp;move &nbsp;as &nbsp;long &nbsp;as &nbsp;frictional &nbsp;force &nbsp;balances &nbsp;the &nbsp;applied &nbsp;force. &nbsp;The &nbsp;table &nbsp;will &nbsp;move &nbsp;only &nbsp;when &nbsp;the applied &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;greater &nbsp;than &nbsp;frictional &nbsp;force. &nbsp;Here &nbsp;the &nbsp;resultant &nbsp;force &nbsp;or &nbsp;net &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;$ F_{R} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;&nbsp;$ F_{A} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;&nbsp;$ F_{f} $</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig3(3).png" style="height:243px; width:630px" /></p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;you &nbsp;stop &nbsp;pedalling &nbsp;the &nbsp;cycle , &nbsp;it &nbsp;gradually &nbsp;shows &nbsp;down &nbsp;and &nbsp;finally &nbsp;comes &nbsp;to &nbsp;rest. &nbsp;We &nbsp;know &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;needed &nbsp;to &nbsp;decrease &nbsp;the &nbsp;speed. &nbsp;Here &nbsp;frictional &nbsp;force &nbsp;between &nbsp;the &nbsp;tyres &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;road &nbsp;act &nbsp;in &nbsp;direction &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;motion &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;cycle. &nbsp;To &nbsp;keep &nbsp;it &nbsp;moving &nbsp;you &nbsp;have &nbsp;to &nbsp;pedal &nbsp;again &nbsp;thus &nbsp;appareatly &nbsp;any &nbsp;body &nbsp;moves &nbsp;only &nbsp;till &nbsp;continuous &nbsp;unbalanced &nbsp;force &nbsp;acts &nbsp;on &nbsp;it.</p>\n\n<p>Consider &nbsp;hypothetically , &nbsp;you &nbsp;stop &nbsp;pedalling &nbsp;simultenously &nbsp;the &nbsp;opposing &nbsp;force &nbsp;of &nbsp;friction &nbsp;also &nbsp;vanishes.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;cycle &nbsp;will &nbsp;keep &nbsp;on &nbsp;moving &nbsp;forever &nbsp;with &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;constant &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;it &nbsp;had &nbsp;acquired &nbsp;just &nbsp;when &nbsp;you &nbsp;stopped &nbsp;pedalling.</p>\n\n<p>Its &nbsp;speed &nbsp;will &nbsp;neither &nbsp;increase &nbsp;nor &nbsp;decrease &nbsp;nor &nbsp;will &nbsp;it &nbsp;ever &nbsp;change &nbsp;its &nbsp;direction. &nbsp;The &nbsp;cycle &nbsp;will &nbsp;be &nbsp;in &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion &nbsp;forever. &nbsp;This &nbsp;is &nbsp;true &nbsp;for &nbsp;all &nbsp;moving &nbsp;bodies. &nbsp;A &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;cannot &nbsp;come &nbsp;to rest &nbsp;on &nbsp;its &nbsp;own. &nbsp;It &nbsp;needs &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>Force &nbsp;is &nbsp;required &nbsp;to &nbsp;move &nbsp;any &nbsp;body &nbsp;only &nbsp;when &nbsp;opposing &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;also &nbsp;there.</p>\n\n<p>For &nbsp; a &nbsp;body &nbsp;in &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion, &nbsp;applied &nbsp;force &nbsp;unbalanced &nbsp;force &nbsp;causes &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp; i.e &nbsp;change [ increase &nbsp;or &nbsp;decrease ] &nbsp;in &nbsp;speed &nbsp;or &nbsp;direction</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;the &nbsp;light &nbsp;of &nbsp;above &nbsp;discussion , do &nbsp;you &nbsp;agree &nbsp;with &nbsp;Aristotle&#39;s &nbsp;view &nbsp;that &nbsp;natural &nbsp;state &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;rest &nbsp;or &nbsp;do &nbsp;you &nbsp;believe &nbsp;the &nbsp;natural &nbsp;state &nbsp;is &nbsp;motion ? &nbsp;well &nbsp;you &nbsp;are &nbsp;wrong &nbsp;in &nbsp;both &nbsp;cases. Then &nbsp;what &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;natural &nbsp;state &nbsp;?</p>\n\n<p>For &nbsp;the &nbsp;answer &nbsp;you &nbsp;have &nbsp;to &nbsp;understand &nbsp;theory &nbsp;proposed &nbsp;by &nbsp;Galileo &nbsp;and &nbsp;3 &nbsp;laws &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;given &nbsp;by &nbsp;Newton.</p>\n\n<p>Famous &nbsp;Italian &nbsp; scientist &nbsp;and &nbsp;thinker &nbsp;Galileo &nbsp;Galilee &nbsp;however &nbsp;differed . &nbsp;He &nbsp;proposed &nbsp;that &nbsp;natural &nbsp;state &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;neither &nbsp;rest &nbsp;nor &nbsp;motion &nbsp;per &nbsp;se , &nbsp;but &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;ball &nbsp; moving &nbsp;over &nbsp;a &nbsp;plane &nbsp;surface &nbsp;covers &nbsp;more &nbsp;and&nbsp; more &nbsp;distance &nbsp;as &nbsp;the &nbsp;surface &nbsp;is &nbsp;made &nbsp;smoother. This &nbsp;means &nbsp;if &nbsp;friction &nbsp;which &nbsp;opposes &nbsp;the &nbsp;motion &nbsp;of &nbsp;ball &nbsp;is &nbsp;completely &nbsp;eliminated , &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball &nbsp;will &nbsp;move &nbsp;forever.</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;ball &nbsp;rolling &nbsp;down &nbsp;a &nbsp;slope &nbsp;accelerates &nbsp; due &nbsp;to &nbsp;gravity , &nbsp;while &nbsp;going &nbsp;going &nbsp;up &nbsp;it &nbsp;decelerates &nbsp;again &nbsp;due &nbsp;to &nbsp;gravity. &nbsp;A &nbsp;ball &nbsp;moving &nbsp;on &nbsp;a &nbsp;level &nbsp;plane &nbsp;surface &nbsp;will &nbsp;have &nbsp;no &nbsp;reason &nbsp;to &nbsp;accelarate &nbsp;or &nbsp;decelerate. &nbsp;It &nbsp;should &nbsp;move &nbsp;with &nbsp;constant &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;for &nbsp;ever.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Balanced   and   Unbalanced  Forces', '', '<p>Consider &nbsp;a &nbsp;iron &nbsp;ball &nbsp;with &nbsp;chain &nbsp;attached &nbsp;to &nbsp;its &nbsp;two &nbsp;sides</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig1(1).png" style="height:100px; width:350px" /></p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;you &nbsp;pull &nbsp;only &nbsp;chain &nbsp;A , &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball moves &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;right.</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;you &nbsp;pull &nbsp;only &nbsp;chain &nbsp;B , &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball &nbsp;moves &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;left.</p>\n\n<p>Observe &nbsp;that &nbsp;ball &nbsp;is &nbsp;moving &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;pull &nbsp;or &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>Now &nbsp;apply &nbsp;equal &nbsp;pull &nbsp;force &nbsp;to &nbsp;both &nbsp;A &nbsp;and &nbsp;B. What &nbsp;do &nbsp;you &nbsp;observe ? &nbsp;Does &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball &nbsp;move ? &nbsp;The &nbsp;ball &nbsp;does &nbsp;not &nbsp;move &nbsp;at &nbsp;all , &nbsp;neither &nbsp;to &nbsp;right &nbsp;nor &nbsp;to &nbsp;left. &nbsp;Gradually &nbsp;increase &nbsp;the &nbsp;force &nbsp;equally , still &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball &nbsp;does &nbsp;not &nbsp;move.</p>\n\n<p>You &nbsp;will &nbsp;notice &nbsp;that &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;A &nbsp;is &nbsp;exactly &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;B &nbsp;in &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;but &nbsp;exactly &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;in &nbsp;direction. Even &nbsp;though &nbsp;2 &nbsp;forces &nbsp;are &nbsp;acting &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball , &nbsp;it &nbsp;still does &nbsp;not &nbsp;move. Such &nbsp;forces &nbsp;which &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;and &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;to &nbsp;each &nbsp;other , &nbsp;cancelling &nbsp;each &nbsp;others &nbsp;effect &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;on &nbsp;which &nbsp;they &nbsp;act &nbsp;simultenously , &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;balanced &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig2(1).png" style="height:147px; width:500px" />Remember &nbsp;that &nbsp;when &nbsp;number &nbsp;of &nbsp;balanced &nbsp;forces &nbsp;act &nbsp;on &nbsp;a &nbsp;body , &nbsp;the &nbsp;net &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;zero. &nbsp;hence &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;does &nbsp;not &nbsp;move. &nbsp;The &nbsp;resultent &nbsp;of &nbsp;balanced &nbsp;forces &nbsp;is &nbsp;always &nbsp;zero.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Now &nbsp;apply &nbsp;unequal &nbsp;forces &nbsp;[&nbsp;$ F_{A} $ &nbsp;&gt; &nbsp;$ F_{B} $ &nbsp;or &nbsp;$ F_{B} $ &nbsp;&gt; &nbsp;$ F_{A} $ ]</p>\n\n<p>You &nbsp;will &nbsp;see &nbsp;that &nbsp;ball &nbsp;moves &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;greater &nbsp;force. &nbsp;Such &nbsp;forces &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;un balanced &nbsp;forces.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;resultant &nbsp;of &nbsp;unbalanced &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;never &nbsp;zero. &nbsp;Hence &nbsp;net &nbsp;force &nbsp;acts &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;greatest &nbsp;force &nbsp;and &nbsp;body &nbsp;moves &nbsp;in &nbsp;this &nbsp;direction .</p>\n\n<p>Whenever &nbsp;you &nbsp;try &nbsp;to &nbsp;push &nbsp;any &nbsp;object &nbsp;for &nbsp;example &nbsp;table , &nbsp;it &nbsp;initially &nbsp;shows &nbsp;some &nbsp;resistance &nbsp;to &nbsp;movement. &nbsp;Force &nbsp;of &nbsp;friction &nbsp;is &nbsp;set &nbsp;up &nbsp;between &nbsp;surfaces &nbsp;of &nbsp;that &nbsp;object &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;ground. &nbsp;This &nbsp;frinctional &nbsp;force &nbsp;always &nbsp;acts &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;direction &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;applied &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>Now &nbsp;if &nbsp;you &nbsp;increase &nbsp;the &nbsp;applied &nbsp;force , &nbsp;it &nbsp;may &nbsp;still &nbsp;not &nbsp;move &nbsp;as &nbsp;long &nbsp;as &nbsp;frictional &nbsp;force &nbsp;balances &nbsp;the &nbsp;applied &nbsp;force. &nbsp;The &nbsp;table &nbsp;will &nbsp;move &nbsp;only &nbsp;when &nbsp;the applied &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;greater &nbsp;than &nbsp;frictional &nbsp;force. &nbsp;Here &nbsp;the &nbsp;resultant &nbsp;force &nbsp;or &nbsp;net &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;$ F_{R} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;&nbsp;$ F_{A} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;&nbsp;$ F_{f} $</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig3(3).png" style="height:243px; width:630px" /></p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;you &nbsp;stop &nbsp;pedalling &nbsp;the &nbsp;cycle , &nbsp;it &nbsp;gradually &nbsp;shows &nbsp;down &nbsp;and &nbsp;finally &nbsp;comes &nbsp;to &nbsp;rest. &nbsp;We &nbsp;know &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;needed &nbsp;to &nbsp;decrease &nbsp;the &nbsp;speed. &nbsp;Here &nbsp;frictional &nbsp;force &nbsp;between &nbsp;the &nbsp;tyres &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;road &nbsp;act &nbsp;in &nbsp;direction &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;motion &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;cycle. &nbsp;To &nbsp;keep &nbsp;it &nbsp;moving &nbsp;you &nbsp;have &nbsp;to &nbsp;pedal &nbsp;again &nbsp;thus &nbsp;appareatly &nbsp;any &nbsp;body &nbsp;moves &nbsp;only &nbsp;till &nbsp;continuous &nbsp;unbalanced &nbsp;force &nbsp;acts &nbsp;on &nbsp;it.</p>\n\n<p>Consider &nbsp;hypothetically , &nbsp;you &nbsp;stop &nbsp;pedalling &nbsp;simultenously &nbsp;the &nbsp;opposing &nbsp;force &nbsp;of &nbsp;friction &nbsp;also &nbsp;vanishes.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;cycle &nbsp;will &nbsp;keep &nbsp;on &nbsp;moving &nbsp;forever &nbsp;with &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;constant &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;it &nbsp;had &nbsp;acquired &nbsp;just &nbsp;when &nbsp;you &nbsp;stopped &nbsp;pedalling.</p>\n\n<p>Its &nbsp;speed &nbsp;will &nbsp;neither &nbsp;increase &nbsp;nor &nbsp;decrease &nbsp;nor &nbsp;will &nbsp;it &nbsp;ever &nbsp;change &nbsp;its &nbsp;direction. &nbsp;The &nbsp;cycle &nbsp;will &nbsp;be &nbsp;in &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion &nbsp;forever. &nbsp;This &nbsp;is &nbsp;true &nbsp;for &nbsp;all &nbsp;moving &nbsp;bodies. &nbsp;A &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;cannot &nbsp;come &nbsp;to rest &nbsp;on &nbsp;its &nbsp;own. &nbsp;It &nbsp;needs &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>Force &nbsp;is &nbsp;required &nbsp;to &nbsp;move &nbsp;any &nbsp;body &nbsp;only &nbsp;when &nbsp;opposing &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;also &nbsp;there.</p>\n\n<p>For &nbsp; a &nbsp;body &nbsp;in &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion, &nbsp;applied &nbsp;force &nbsp;unbalanced &nbsp;force &nbsp;causes &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp; i.e &nbsp;change [ increase &nbsp;or &nbsp;decrease ] &nbsp;in &nbsp;speed &nbsp;or &nbsp;direction</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;the &nbsp;light &nbsp;of &nbsp;above &nbsp;discussion , do &nbsp;you &nbsp;agree &nbsp;with &nbsp;Aristotle&#39;s &nbsp;view &nbsp;that &nbsp;natural &nbsp;state &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;rest &nbsp;or &nbsp;do &nbsp;you &nbsp;believe &nbsp;the &nbsp;natural &nbsp;state &nbsp;is &nbsp;motion ? &nbsp;well &nbsp;you &nbsp;are &nbsp;wrong &nbsp;in &nbsp;both &nbsp;cases. Then &nbsp;what &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;natural &nbsp;state &nbsp;?</p>\n\n<p>For &nbsp;the &nbsp;answer &nbsp;you &nbsp;have &nbsp;to &nbsp;understand &nbsp;theory &nbsp;proposed &nbsp;by &nbsp;Galileo &nbsp;and &nbsp;3 &nbsp;laws &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;given &nbsp;by &nbsp;Newton.</p>\n\n<p>Famous &nbsp;Italian &nbsp; scientist &nbsp;and &nbsp;thinker &nbsp;Galileo &nbsp;Galilee &nbsp;however &nbsp;differed . &nbsp;He &nbsp;proposed &nbsp;that &nbsp;natural &nbsp;state &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;neither &nbsp;rest &nbsp;nor &nbsp;motion &nbsp;per &nbsp;se , &nbsp;but &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;ball &nbsp; moving &nbsp;over &nbsp;a &nbsp;plane &nbsp;surface &nbsp;covers &nbsp;more &nbsp;and&nbsp; more &nbsp;distance &nbsp;as &nbsp;the &nbsp;surface &nbsp;is &nbsp;made &nbsp;smoother. This &nbsp;means &nbsp;if &nbsp;friction &nbsp;which &nbsp;opposes &nbsp;the &nbsp;motion &nbsp;of &nbsp;ball &nbsp;is &nbsp;completely &nbsp;eliminated , &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball &nbsp;will &nbsp;move &nbsp;forever.</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;ball &nbsp;rolling &nbsp;down &nbsp;a &nbsp;slope &nbsp;accelerates &nbsp; due &nbsp;to &nbsp;gravity , &nbsp;while &nbsp;going &nbsp;going &nbsp;up &nbsp;it &nbsp;decelerates &nbsp;again &nbsp;due &nbsp;to &nbsp;gravity. &nbsp;A &nbsp;ball &nbsp;moving &nbsp;on &nbsp;a &nbsp;level &nbsp;plane &nbsp;surface &nbsp;will &nbsp;have &nbsp;no &nbsp;reason &nbsp;to &nbsp;accelarate &nbsp;or &nbsp;decelerate. &nbsp;It &nbsp;should &nbsp;move &nbsp;with &nbsp;constant &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;for &nbsp;ever.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 0, 0),
(98, 'inline_html', '<p><strong>Galileo&#39;s &nbsp;experiment :</strong></p>\n\n<p>As &nbsp;shown &nbsp;in &nbsp;figure , &nbsp; Galileo &nbsp;set &nbsp;up &nbsp;two &nbsp;inclined &nbsp;planes &nbsp;back &nbsp;to &nbsp;back</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig1%20(1).png" style="height:216px; width:380px" /></p>\n\n<p>Intially &nbsp;slope &nbsp;of &nbsp;both &nbsp;the &nbsp;inclines &nbsp;are &nbsp;same . &nbsp;He &nbsp;rolled &nbsp;down &nbsp;a &nbsp;ball &nbsp;on &nbsp;one &nbsp;plane &nbsp;from &nbsp;certain &nbsp;height &nbsp;and &nbsp;observed &nbsp;that &nbsp;ball &nbsp;reached &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;height &nbsp;while &nbsp;going &nbsp;up &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;second &nbsp;plane.</p>\n\n<p>Now &nbsp;progressive &nbsp;he &nbsp;reduced &nbsp;the &nbsp;angle &nbsp;of &nbsp;second &nbsp;slope &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;upward &nbsp;slope. &nbsp;He &nbsp;observed &nbsp;every &nbsp;time &nbsp;ball &nbsp;travelled &nbsp;more &nbsp;distance &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;upward &nbsp;slope &nbsp;so &nbsp;as &nbsp;to &nbsp;achieve &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;height &nbsp;from &nbsp;which &nbsp;it &nbsp;was &nbsp;rolled &nbsp;down &nbsp;the &nbsp;first &nbsp;plane.</p>\n\n<p>As &nbsp;the &nbsp;angle &nbsp;of &nbsp;upward &nbsp;slope &nbsp;was &nbsp;decreased &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball &nbsp;travelled &nbsp;more &nbsp;distance. This &nbsp;made &nbsp;him &nbsp;think &nbsp;what &nbsp;will &nbsp;happen &nbsp;if &nbsp;the &nbsp;angle &nbsp;of &nbsp;slope &nbsp;is &nbsp;made &nbsp;zero &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;inclined &nbsp;plane &nbsp;converted &nbsp;to level &nbsp;plane ? &nbsp;How &nbsp;far &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball &nbsp;will &nbsp;move &nbsp;to &nbsp;reach &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;height &nbsp; Galileo &nbsp;thought &nbsp;that &nbsp;since &nbsp;the &nbsp;slope &nbsp;is &nbsp;zero , the &nbsp;ball &nbsp;should &nbsp;travel &nbsp;forever &nbsp;with &nbsp;constant &nbsp;velocity. &nbsp;Unless &nbsp;ofcourse &nbsp;some &nbsp;force &nbsp;acts &nbsp;on &nbsp;it &nbsp;to &nbsp;oppose &nbsp;this.</p>\n\n<p>Thus &nbsp;Galileo &nbsp;proved &nbsp;that &nbsp;natural &nbsp;state &nbsp;of &nbsp;any &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;always &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;absence &nbsp;of &nbsp;opposing &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>As &nbsp;explained &nbsp; in &nbsp;previous &nbsp;chapter , &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;motion &nbsp; with &nbsp;constant &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;same &nbsp;speed &nbsp;with &nbsp;no &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;directions.</p>\n', 'Galileo ''s   Theory', '', '<p><strong>Galileo&#39;s &nbsp;experiment :</strong></p>\n\n<p>As &nbsp;shown &nbsp;in &nbsp;figure , &nbsp; Galileo &nbsp;set &nbsp;up &nbsp;two &nbsp;inclined &nbsp;planes &nbsp;back &nbsp;to &nbsp;back</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig1%20(1).png" style="height:216px; width:380px" /></p>\n\n<p>Intially &nbsp;slope &nbsp;of &nbsp;both &nbsp;the &nbsp;inclines &nbsp;are &nbsp;same . &nbsp;He &nbsp;rolled &nbsp;down &nbsp;a &nbsp;ball &nbsp;on &nbsp;one &nbsp;plane &nbsp;from &nbsp;certain &nbsp;height &nbsp;and &nbsp;observed &nbsp;that &nbsp;ball &nbsp;reached &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;height &nbsp;while &nbsp;going &nbsp;up &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;second &nbsp;plane.</p>\n\n<p>Now &nbsp;progressive &nbsp;he &nbsp;reduced &nbsp;the &nbsp;angle &nbsp;of &nbsp;second &nbsp;slope &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;upward &nbsp;slope. &nbsp;He &nbsp;observed &nbsp;every &nbsp;time &nbsp;ball &nbsp;travelled &nbsp;more &nbsp;distance &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;upward &nbsp;slope &nbsp;so &nbsp;as &nbsp;to &nbsp;achieve &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;height &nbsp;from &nbsp;which &nbsp;it &nbsp;was &nbsp;rolled &nbsp;down &nbsp;the &nbsp;first &nbsp;plane.</p>\n\n<p>As &nbsp;the &nbsp;angle &nbsp;of &nbsp;upward &nbsp;slope &nbsp;was &nbsp;decreased &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball &nbsp;travelled &nbsp;more &nbsp;distance. This &nbsp;made &nbsp;him &nbsp;think &nbsp;what &nbsp;will &nbsp;happen &nbsp;if &nbsp;the &nbsp;angle &nbsp;of &nbsp;slope &nbsp;is &nbsp;made &nbsp;zero &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;inclined &nbsp;plane &nbsp;converted &nbsp;to level &nbsp;plane ? &nbsp;How &nbsp;far &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball &nbsp;will &nbsp;move &nbsp;to &nbsp;reach &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;height &nbsp; Galileo &nbsp;thought &nbsp;that &nbsp;since &nbsp;the &nbsp;slope &nbsp;is &nbsp;zero , the &nbsp;ball &nbsp;should &nbsp;travel &nbsp;forever &nbsp;with &nbsp;constant &nbsp;velocity. &nbsp;Unless &nbsp;ofcourse &nbsp;some &nbsp;force &nbsp;acts &nbsp;on &nbsp;it &nbsp;to &nbsp;oppose &nbsp;this.</p>\n\n<p>Thus &nbsp;Galileo &nbsp;proved &nbsp;that &nbsp;natural &nbsp;state &nbsp;of &nbsp;any &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;always &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;absence &nbsp;of &nbsp;opposing &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>As &nbsp;explained &nbsp; in &nbsp;previous &nbsp;chapter , &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;motion &nbsp; with &nbsp;constant &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;same &nbsp;speed &nbsp;with &nbsp;no &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;directions.</p>\n', 0, 0);
