(99, 'inline_html', '<p>Much &nbsp;later &nbsp;based &nbsp;on &nbsp;Galileo&#39;s &nbsp; observation,&nbsp;&nbsp;another &nbsp;famous &nbsp;scientist &nbsp;sir &nbsp;Issac &nbsp;Newton &nbsp;proposed &nbsp;whether &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;in &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest &nbsp;or &nbsp;in &nbsp;motion , &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;always &nbsp;governed &nbsp;some &nbsp;rules.</p>\n\n<p>He &nbsp;gave &nbsp;3 &nbsp;rules &nbsp;which &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;Newton&#39;s &nbsp;laws &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p><strong>First &nbsp;Law &nbsp;of &nbsp;Motion :</strong></p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;body &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest &nbsp;tends &nbsp;to &nbsp;remain &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest<strong>&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;and &nbsp;body &nbsp;in &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;motion &nbsp;tends &nbsp;to &nbsp;remain &nbsp;in &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion &nbsp;unless &nbsp;and &nbsp;until &nbsp;at &nbsp;is &nbsp;acted &nbsp;upon &nbsp;by &nbsp;net &nbsp;external &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>First &nbsp;law &nbsp;tells &nbsp;us &nbsp;how &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;behave &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;absence &nbsp;of &nbsp;net &nbsp;external &nbsp;force.This &nbsp;natural &nbsp;tendency &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;to &nbsp;maintain &nbsp;its &nbsp;state &nbsp;of &nbsp;rest &nbsp;or &nbsp;motion is &nbsp;called &nbsp;Inertia</p>\n\n<p>Newton&#39;s &nbsp;1st &nbsp;law &nbsp;is &nbsp;also &nbsp;called &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;Inertia.</p>\n\n<p>Eg : &nbsp;Passangers &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;moving &nbsp;bus &nbsp;lunge &nbsp;forward &nbsp;if &nbsp;the &nbsp;bus &nbsp;stops &nbsp;suddenly.</p>\n\n<p>Even &nbsp;as &nbsp;brakes &nbsp;are &nbsp;applied &nbsp;in the &nbsp;bus &nbsp;and &nbsp;it &nbsp;stop &nbsp;suddenly, &nbsp;the &nbsp;passangers &nbsp;continue &nbsp;to &nbsp;be &nbsp;in &nbsp;state &nbsp;of &nbsp;&#39;motion, &nbsp;due &nbsp;to inertia. Similarly &nbsp;when &nbsp;a &nbsp;bus &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest &nbsp;accelerates &nbsp;suddenly, &nbsp;the &nbsp;passangers &nbsp;are &nbsp;thrown &nbsp;backwards &nbsp;this &nbsp;is &nbsp;also &nbsp;due &nbsp;to &nbsp;inertia.</p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;the &nbsp;moving &nbsp;bus &nbsp;turns &nbsp;towards &nbsp;right &nbsp;or &nbsp;left , &nbsp;the &nbsp;passangers &nbsp;are &nbsp;thrown &nbsp;in &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;direction</p>\n\n<p>Thus &nbsp;there &nbsp;are &nbsp;3 &nbsp;types &nbsp;of &nbsp;Inertia&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>1 . Inertia &nbsp;of &nbsp;rest</p>\n\n<p>2 .&nbsp;Inertia &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p>3 .&nbsp;Inertia &nbsp;of &nbsp;direction</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;body &nbsp;in &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion &nbsp;moves &nbsp;with &nbsp;constant &nbsp;velocity [ same &nbsp;speed &nbsp;and &nbsp;same &nbsp;direction ] . A &nbsp;body &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;considered &nbsp;to &nbsp;be &nbsp;moving &nbsp;with &nbsp;constant &nbsp;zero &nbsp;velocity.</p>\n\n<p>All &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;maintain &nbsp;constant &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;unless &nbsp;net &nbsp;force &nbsp;act &nbsp;on &nbsp;them. &nbsp;Net &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;required &nbsp;to &nbsp;change &nbsp;velocity. &nbsp;This &nbsp;gives &nbsp;rise &nbsp;to &nbsp;inertia.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Inertia &nbsp;and &nbsp;mass :</strong></p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp;is easier &nbsp;to &nbsp;throw &nbsp;a &nbsp;small &nbsp;stone &nbsp;than &nbsp;push &nbsp;a &nbsp;big &nbsp;boulder .</p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp;is &nbsp;easier &nbsp;to &nbsp;handle &nbsp;a &nbsp;car &nbsp;than &nbsp;a &nbsp;fully &nbsp;loaded &nbsp;18 &nbsp;wheeler . &nbsp;You &nbsp;can &nbsp;start , stop &nbsp;or &nbsp;turn &nbsp;the &nbsp;car &nbsp;as &nbsp;you &nbsp;wish &nbsp;but &nbsp;same &nbsp;cannot &nbsp;be &nbsp;said &nbsp;for &nbsp;the &nbsp;truck</p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp;above &nbsp;example , &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;clear &nbsp;that &nbsp;inertion &nbsp;[ of &nbsp;rest &nbsp;or motion ] &nbsp;is &nbsp;not &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;for &nbsp;all &nbsp;bodies. Infact &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;directly &nbsp;proportional &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;mass.</p>\n\n<p>More &nbsp;the &nbsp;mass , more &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;inertia. &nbsp;To &nbsp;sum &nbsp;it &nbsp;up ; &nbsp;Inertia &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;measure &nbsp;of &nbsp;natural &nbsp;tendency &nbsp;of &nbsp;all &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;to &nbsp;resist &nbsp;any &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;their &nbsp;state &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion.</p>\n\n<p>Mass &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;measure &nbsp;of &nbsp;this &nbsp;inertia .</p>\n\n<p><strong>Second &nbsp;Law &nbsp;of &nbsp;Motion :</strong></p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp;the 1st &nbsp;law &nbsp;we &nbsp;know &nbsp;that &nbsp; net &nbsp;external &nbsp;unbalanced &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;needed &nbsp;to &nbsp;change &nbsp;the &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;body. &nbsp;Rate &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;of &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;is &nbsp;acceleration. &nbsp;This &nbsp;means &nbsp;unbalanced &nbsp;force &nbsp;causes &nbsp;acceleration.</p>\n\n<p>But &nbsp;how &nbsp;do &nbsp;we &nbsp;measure &nbsp;such &nbsp;a &nbsp;force ? We &nbsp;cannot &nbsp;see &nbsp;it , we &nbsp;cannot &nbsp;touch &nbsp;it. &nbsp;But &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;feel &nbsp;its &nbsp;effect &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;form &nbsp;of &nbsp;acceleration.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;second &nbsp;law &nbsp;gives &nbsp;us &nbsp;the &nbsp;measures &nbsp;of &nbsp;force &nbsp;and &nbsp;exactly &nbsp;how &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp;depend &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;applied &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;you &nbsp;try &nbsp;to &nbsp;scare &nbsp;your &nbsp;friend &nbsp;by &nbsp;hitting &nbsp;with &nbsp;tennis &nbsp;ball &nbsp;he &nbsp;may &nbsp;not &nbsp;be &nbsp;effected. &nbsp;Try &nbsp;doing &nbsp;same &nbsp;with &nbsp;cricket &nbsp;ball , &nbsp;he &nbsp;may &nbsp;ran &nbsp;away. &nbsp;This &nbsp;shows &nbsp;the &nbsp;impact &nbsp;of &nbsp;cricket &nbsp;ball &nbsp;is &nbsp;different &nbsp;and &nbsp;greater &nbsp;then &nbsp;that &nbsp;of tennis &nbsp;ball.</p>\n\n<p>Throw &nbsp; a &nbsp;bullet &nbsp;with &nbsp;your &nbsp;hand &nbsp;at &nbsp;a &nbsp;wooden &nbsp;block. &nbsp;The &nbsp;bullet &nbsp;simply &nbsp;touches &nbsp;it &nbsp;and &nbsp;falls &nbsp;down &nbsp;without &nbsp;having &nbsp;any &nbsp;impact &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;block. &nbsp;Now &nbsp;fine &nbsp;the &nbsp; same &nbsp;bullet &nbsp;from &nbsp;a &nbsp;gun. &nbsp;The &nbsp;bullet penetrates &nbsp; the &nbsp;thick &nbsp;wooden &nbsp;block &nbsp;and &nbsp;gets &nbsp;firmly &nbsp;embedded &nbsp;into &nbsp;it. &nbsp;It &nbsp;may &nbsp;even &nbsp;come &nbsp;out &nbsp;of &nbsp;it &nbsp;from &nbsp;the &nbsp;other &nbsp;side.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;above &nbsp;example &nbsp;show &nbsp;that &nbsp;impact &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;depends &nbsp;both &nbsp;on &nbsp;its &nbsp;mass &nbsp;and &nbsp;velocity.</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;body &nbsp;with &nbsp;small mass &nbsp;can &nbsp;have &nbsp;large &nbsp;impact &nbsp;if &nbsp;its &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;is &nbsp;high.</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;slowly &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;can &nbsp;create &nbsp;huge &nbsp;impact &nbsp;if &nbsp;its &nbsp;mass is &nbsp;high.</p>\n\n<p>Newton &nbsp;called &nbsp;this &nbsp;property &nbsp;of &nbsp;moving &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;or &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;in &nbsp;motion &nbsp;which &nbsp;takes &nbsp;into &nbsp;account &nbsp;both &nbsp;mass &nbsp;and &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;as &nbsp;momentum ( p ).</p>\n\n<p>Momentum ( p ) &nbsp;of &nbsp;a moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;defined &nbsp;as &nbsp;the &nbsp;product &nbsp;of &nbsp;its &nbsp;mass ( m&nbsp;) &nbsp;and &nbsp;velocity ( v ).</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Mathematically</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; p &nbsp;= &nbsp;mv</p>\n\n<p>Momentum &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;vector &nbsp;quantity. &nbsp;It &nbsp;has &nbsp;both &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;and &nbsp;direction. Its &nbsp;value &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;+ve , &nbsp; -ve &nbsp; or &nbsp;zero.</p>\n\n<p>Units : &nbsp;Its &nbsp;unit &nbsp;is &nbsp;product &nbsp;of &nbsp;units &nbsp;of &nbsp;mass &nbsp;and &nbsp;velocity.</p>\n\n<p>S I &nbsp;unit : &nbsp;Kilogram &nbsp;meter &nbsp;per &nbsp;second</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Kg &nbsp;m&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $</p>\n\n<p>C G S &nbsp;unit &nbsp;: &nbsp;gram &nbsp;centimeter &nbsp;per &nbsp;second &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;g cm&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $</p>\n\n<p>Units &nbsp;of &nbsp;mass ------------------- kg &nbsp; ; &nbsp; g</p>\n\n<p>Units &nbsp;of &nbsp;velocity----------------- &nbsp;m&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $ &nbsp;; &nbsp;c&nbsp;m&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $</p>\n\n<p>Their &nbsp;product---------------------- [ kg ] [ m&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $ ] &nbsp; = &nbsp; kg m&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;[ &nbsp;g ] &nbsp;[ c m&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $] &nbsp; = &nbsp; g &nbsp;cm&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $</p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp;is &nbsp;clear &nbsp;that &nbsp;any &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;will &nbsp;produce &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum. &nbsp;Now &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;is &nbsp;caused &nbsp;by &nbsp;applied &nbsp;force. &nbsp;Hence &nbsp;any &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;is direct &nbsp;result &nbsp;of &nbsp;applied &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;were &nbsp;discussing &nbsp;how &nbsp;to &nbsp;measure &nbsp;force , &nbsp;now &nbsp;you &nbsp;can &nbsp;say &nbsp;if &nbsp;you &nbsp;measure &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum , &nbsp;you &nbsp;can &nbsp;get &nbsp;measure &nbsp;of &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>But , &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;not &nbsp;only &nbsp;depends &nbsp;on &nbsp;force &nbsp;but &nbsp;also &nbsp;on &nbsp;the duration &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;force &nbsp;so &nbsp;if &nbsp;you &nbsp;know &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;time &nbsp;during &nbsp;which &nbsp;the &nbsp;change &nbsp;is &nbsp;taking &nbsp;place , &nbsp;you &nbsp;get &nbsp;the &nbsp;measure &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;applied &nbsp;force &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;for &nbsp;what &nbsp;time &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;acting &nbsp;on &nbsp;a &nbsp;body.</p>\n\n<p>Expressed &nbsp;mathematically &nbsp;the &nbsp;rate &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;of &nbsp; momentum &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;and &nbsp;time &nbsp;during &nbsp;which &nbsp;the &nbsp;change &nbsp;occurs &nbsp;gives &nbsp;us &nbsp;the &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;force. &nbsp;This &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;significance &nbsp;of &nbsp;Newton&#39;s &nbsp; 2nd &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion.</p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp;gives &nbsp;us &nbsp;mathematical &nbsp;expression &nbsp;for &nbsp;force. &nbsp;as &nbsp;you &nbsp;will see, &nbsp;it &nbsp;also &nbsp;tells &nbsp;us &nbsp;exactly &nbsp;how &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp;depends &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Mathematical &nbsp;expression &nbsp; for &nbsp; second &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion :</strong></p>\n\n<p>Consider &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;of &nbsp;mass ( m ) &nbsp;moving &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;with &nbsp;intial &nbsp;velocity ( u ). Let &nbsp;a &nbsp;constant &nbsp;force &nbsp;( F ) &nbsp; acts &nbsp;on &nbsp;it &nbsp;for &nbsp;time &nbsp;( t ) &nbsp;due &nbsp;to &nbsp;which &nbsp;at &nbsp;experience &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp;( a )</p>\n\n<p>Let &nbsp; its &nbsp;final &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;be &nbsp;v</p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;know &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;( p ) &nbsp;= &nbsp;mass &nbsp;X &nbsp;velocity</p>\n\n<p>Initial &nbsp;momentum ( $ p_{1} $ )&nbsp; of &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ p_{1} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp; mass &nbsp;X &nbsp;initial &nbsp;velocity</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ p_{1} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp; m u</p>\n\n<p>Final &nbsp;momentum (&nbsp;$ p_{2} $ )&nbsp; of &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ p_{2} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp; mass &nbsp;X &nbsp;initial &nbsp;velocity</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ p_{2} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp; m v</p>\n\n<p>Change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;( &nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ &nbsp;p &nbsp;) &nbsp;= &nbsp;&nbsp;$ p_{2} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;&nbsp;$ p_{1} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ &nbsp;p &nbsp; &nbsp; = &nbsp; m v &nbsp;- &nbsp; m u</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ &nbsp;p &nbsp; &nbsp; = &nbsp;m( v &nbsp;- &nbsp;u )</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;changes &nbsp;over &nbsp;time &nbsp;t&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Rate &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;of &nbsp;momentum &nbsp; is &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\bigtriangleup &nbsp; p}{t} $ &nbsp; &nbsp;= &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{m( v &nbsp;- &nbsp;u )}{t} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; From &nbsp;2nd &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; F &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\alpha $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{\\bigtriangleup&nbsp;&nbsp; p}{t} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;F &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\alpha $ &nbsp; = &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\frac{m( v &nbsp;- &nbsp;u )}{t} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;F &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\alpha $ &nbsp; = &nbsp; ma &nbsp; [ &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{( v &nbsp;- &nbsp;u )}{t} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp; acceleration &nbsp;( a ) ]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;F &nbsp; &nbsp;= &nbsp; K m a</p>\n\n<p>Wher &nbsp;K &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;constant &nbsp;of &nbsp;proportionality. &nbsp;we &nbsp;choose &nbsp;S.I &nbsp;unit &nbsp;for &nbsp;force &nbsp;such &nbsp;that &nbsp;K becomes &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;one.</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;unit &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;that &nbsp;force &nbsp;which &nbsp;when &nbsp;acting &nbsp;on &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;of &nbsp;mass &nbsp;1 kg &nbsp;produces &nbsp;an &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp;of &nbsp;1 m$ s^{-2} $ &nbsp;in &nbsp;it.</p>\n\n<p>Thus &nbsp;unit &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;1 &nbsp;newton &nbsp;force</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 1 &nbsp;newton ( N ) &nbsp; = &nbsp;K &nbsp;X &nbsp;1 kg &nbsp;X &nbsp;1&nbsp;m$ s^{-2} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;K &nbsp;= &nbsp;1</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;F &nbsp;= &nbsp;m a</p>\n\n<p>S.I &nbsp;unit &nbsp;of &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;kg&nbsp;m$ s^{-2} $ &nbsp;or &nbsp;newton.</p>\n\n<p>Its &nbsp;symbol &nbsp;is &nbsp;N</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;1 &nbsp;N &nbsp;= &nbsp;1 &nbsp;kg m$ s^{-2} $</p>\n\n<p>Similarly &nbsp;CGS &nbsp;unit &nbsp;of &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp; g c m&nbsp;$ s^{-2} $ &nbsp;or &nbsp;dyne.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;1 &nbsp;dyne &nbsp; = &nbsp;1&nbsp;g c m&nbsp;$ s^{-2} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;1 N &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ 10^{5} $ &nbsp;dyne</p>\n\n<p>* Force &nbsp;is &nbsp;rate &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;of &nbsp;momentum. &nbsp;This &nbsp;fact &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;illustrated &nbsp;through &nbsp;many &nbsp;examples.</p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;a &nbsp;fielder &nbsp;wants &nbsp;to &nbsp;catch &nbsp;a &nbsp;ferocously &nbsp;hit &nbsp;ball , he &nbsp;moves &nbsp;his &nbsp;hand &nbsp;backwards &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball. This &nbsp;way &nbsp;he &nbsp;extends &nbsp;the &nbsp;time &nbsp;during &nbsp;which &nbsp;ball &nbsp;moving &nbsp;with &nbsp;high &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;comes &nbsp;to &nbsp;rest. &nbsp;As &nbsp;time &nbsp;increases &nbsp;rate &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;of &nbsp;momentumis &nbsp;considerabely &nbsp;decreased, &nbsp;decreasing &nbsp;the &nbsp;force &nbsp;and &nbsp;hence &nbsp;the &nbsp;impacton &nbsp;the &nbsp;hands &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;fielder. On &nbsp;the &nbsp;other &nbsp;hand &nbsp;if &nbsp;he &nbsp;directly &nbsp;catches &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball, &nbsp;its &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;falls &nbsp;to &nbsp;zero &nbsp;instantly.&nbsp;The &nbsp; rate &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;of &nbsp;becomes &nbsp;very &nbsp;high. &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball hits &nbsp;the &nbsp;fielder &nbsp;hand &nbsp;with &nbsp;very &nbsp;large &nbsp;force &nbsp;causing &nbsp;hurt &nbsp;or &nbsp;injury.</p>\n\n<p>Shock &nbsp;absorbers &nbsp;in &nbsp;vechiles &nbsp;work &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;principle. &nbsp;They &nbsp;increase &nbsp;the &nbsp;time &nbsp;of &nbsp;impact &nbsp;there &nbsp;by &nbsp;reducing &nbsp;the &nbsp;force &nbsp;and &nbsp;impact.</p>\n\n<p>Another &nbsp;signification &nbsp;of &nbsp;2nd &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;is &nbsp;that &nbsp;it &nbsp;can &nbsp;also &nbsp;give &nbsp;mathematical &nbsp;expression &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;1 st &nbsp;law.</p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;know &nbsp;from &nbsp;2nd &nbsp;law</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; F&nbsp; = &nbsp;ma</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; F &nbsp;= &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\frac{m( v - u )}{t} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Ft &nbsp;= &nbsp; m v &nbsp;- &nbsp;mu</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp; F &nbsp;= &nbsp;0 &nbsp;, &nbsp; then &nbsp; v &nbsp;= &nbsp;u &nbsp;irrespective &nbsp;of &nbsp;t</p>\n\n<p>This &nbsp;means , &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;absence &nbsp;of &nbsp;external &nbsp;for &nbsp;unbalanced &nbsp; force , &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;continues &nbsp;to &nbsp;move &nbsp;with &nbsp;constant &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;forever. &nbsp;The &nbsp;body &nbsp;remains &nbsp;in &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion.</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp; u &nbsp;= &nbsp;v &nbsp;= &nbsp;0 , then &nbsp;body &nbsp;remains &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest &nbsp;forever &nbsp;until &nbsp;external &nbsp;unbalanced &nbsp;force &nbsp;F &nbsp;acts &nbsp;on &nbsp;it.</p>\n\n<p>Remember:</p>\n\n<p>1 st &nbsp;law &nbsp;gives &nbsp;cause &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;force</p>\n\n<p>2 nd &nbsp;law gives mathematical expression &nbsp;or &nbsp;measure &nbsp;for &nbsp;cause &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;force</p>\n\n<p>What &nbsp;about &nbsp;the &nbsp;3 rd &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion ? well..... &nbsp;it &nbsp;tells &nbsp;us &nbsp;literally &nbsp;how &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;reacts &nbsp;when &nbsp;acted &nbsp;upon &nbsp;by &nbsp;a &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Third &nbsp; Law &nbsp;of &nbsp;Motion :</strong></p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp; states &nbsp;that &nbsp;when &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;exerts &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;another &nbsp;body, &nbsp;the &nbsp;2nd &nbsp;body &nbsp;immediately &nbsp;exerts &nbsp;equal &nbsp;and &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;first &nbsp;body.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;force &nbsp;exerted &nbsp;by &nbsp;the &nbsp;1st &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;action &nbsp;force &nbsp;or &nbsp;simply &nbsp;action.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;force &nbsp;exerted &nbsp;by &nbsp;the &nbsp;2 nd &nbsp;body &nbsp;back &nbsp;on &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;first &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;reaction &nbsp;force &nbsp;or &nbsp;simply &nbsp;reaction.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;otherwords , newton&#39;s &nbsp;3 rd &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;stated &nbsp;as &nbsp;For &nbsp;every &nbsp;action &nbsp;there &nbsp;is &nbsp;equal &nbsp;and &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;reaction.</p>\n\n<p>Note &nbsp;: &nbsp;These &nbsp;forces &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;in &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;but &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;in &nbsp;direction.</p>\n\n<p>Equally &nbsp;important &nbsp;is &nbsp;to &nbsp;note &nbsp;that &nbsp;action &nbsp;and &nbsp;reaction &nbsp;act &nbsp;on &nbsp;two &nbsp;different &nbsp;bodies. &nbsp;Hence &nbsp;they &nbsp;do &nbsp;not &nbsp;cancel &nbsp;each &nbsp;other. Both &nbsp;simultenuously &nbsp;produce &nbsp;their &nbsp;own &nbsp;effects.</p>\n\n<p>Our &nbsp;daily &nbsp;lives &nbsp;are &nbsp;full &nbsp;of &nbsp;examples &nbsp;of &nbsp;3 rd &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p>How &nbsp;do &nbsp;you &nbsp;walk &nbsp;or &nbsp;run ? You &nbsp;exert &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;earth &nbsp;through &nbsp;your &nbsp;legs &nbsp;in &nbsp;backward &nbsp;direction.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;earth &nbsp;immediately &nbsp;exerts &nbsp;same &nbsp;force &nbsp;in &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;forward &nbsp;direction &nbsp;on &nbsp;your &nbsp;legs. &nbsp;This &nbsp;propels &nbsp;you &nbsp;forward.</p>\n\n<p>Recoil &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;gun :</p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;you &nbsp;fire &nbsp;a &nbsp;gun , &nbsp;it &nbsp;exerts &nbsp;a &nbsp;large &nbsp;action &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;bullet &nbsp;effecting &nbsp;it &nbsp;out &nbsp;with &nbsp;large &nbsp;velocity.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;bullet &nbsp;in &nbsp;turn &nbsp;exerts &nbsp;equal &nbsp;reaction &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;gun &nbsp;in &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;direction. &nbsp;Hence &nbsp;the &nbsp;gun &nbsp;recoils &nbsp;back &nbsp;whenever &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;shot.</p>\n\n<p>Sailor &nbsp;:</p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;a &nbsp;sailor &nbsp;jumps &nbsp;from &nbsp;his &nbsp;ship &nbsp;onto &nbsp;ground, &nbsp;he &nbsp;pushes &nbsp;the &nbsp;ship &nbsp;in &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;direction.This &nbsp;is &nbsp;action &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;ship &nbsp;immediately &nbsp;exerts &nbsp;equal &nbsp;and &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;reaction &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;sailor. &nbsp;as &nbsp;a &nbsp;result, &nbsp;the &nbsp;sailor &nbsp;can &nbsp;jump &nbsp;forward.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Newton', '', '<p>Much &nbsp;later &nbsp;based &nbsp;on &nbsp;Galileo&#39;s &nbsp; observation,&nbsp;&nbsp;another &nbsp;famous &nbsp;scientist &nbsp;sir &nbsp;Issac &nbsp;Newton &nbsp;proposed &nbsp;whether &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;in &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest &nbsp;or &nbsp;in &nbsp;motion , &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;always &nbsp;governed &nbsp;some &nbsp;rules.</p>\n\n<p>He &nbsp;gave &nbsp;3 &nbsp;rules &nbsp;which &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;Newton&#39;s &nbsp;laws &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p><strong>First &nbsp;Law &nbsp;of &nbsp;Motion :</strong></p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;body &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest &nbsp;tends &nbsp;to &nbsp;remain &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest<strong>&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;and &nbsp;body &nbsp;in &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;motion &nbsp;tends &nbsp;to &nbsp;remain &nbsp;in &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion &nbsp;unless &nbsp;and &nbsp;until &nbsp;at &nbsp;is &nbsp;acted &nbsp;upon &nbsp;by &nbsp;net &nbsp;external &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>First &nbsp;law &nbsp;tells &nbsp;us &nbsp;how &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;behave &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;absence &nbsp;of &nbsp;net &nbsp;external &nbsp;force.This &nbsp;natural &nbsp;tendency &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;to &nbsp;maintain &nbsp;its &nbsp;state &nbsp;of &nbsp;rest &nbsp;or &nbsp;motion is &nbsp;called &nbsp;Inertia</p>\n\n<p>Newton&#39;s &nbsp;1st &nbsp;law &nbsp;is &nbsp;also &nbsp;called &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;Inertia.</p>\n\n<p>Eg : &nbsp;Passangers &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;moving &nbsp;bus &nbsp;lunge &nbsp;forward &nbsp;if &nbsp;the &nbsp;bus &nbsp;stops &nbsp;suddenly.</p>\n\n<p>Even &nbsp;as &nbsp;brakes &nbsp;are &nbsp;applied &nbsp;in the &nbsp;bus &nbsp;and &nbsp;it &nbsp;stop &nbsp;suddenly, &nbsp;the &nbsp;passangers &nbsp;continue &nbsp;to &nbsp;be &nbsp;in &nbsp;state &nbsp;of &nbsp;&#39;motion, &nbsp;due &nbsp;to inertia. Similarly &nbsp;when &nbsp;a &nbsp;bus &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest &nbsp;accelerates &nbsp;suddenly, &nbsp;the &nbsp;passangers &nbsp;are &nbsp;thrown &nbsp;backwards &nbsp;this &nbsp;is &nbsp;also &nbsp;due &nbsp;to &nbsp;inertia.</p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;the &nbsp;moving &nbsp;bus &nbsp;turns &nbsp;towards &nbsp;right &nbsp;or &nbsp;left , &nbsp;the &nbsp;passangers &nbsp;are &nbsp;thrown &nbsp;in &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;direction</p>\n\n<p>Thus &nbsp;there &nbsp;are &nbsp;3 &nbsp;types &nbsp;of &nbsp;Inertia&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>1 . Inertia &nbsp;of &nbsp;rest</p>\n\n<p>2 .&nbsp;Inertia &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p>3 .&nbsp;Inertia &nbsp;of &nbsp;direction</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;body &nbsp;in &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion &nbsp;moves &nbsp;with &nbsp;constant &nbsp;velocity [ same &nbsp;speed &nbsp;and &nbsp;same &nbsp;direction ] . A &nbsp;body &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;considered &nbsp;to &nbsp;be &nbsp;moving &nbsp;with &nbsp;constant &nbsp;zero &nbsp;velocity.</p>\n\n<p>All &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;maintain &nbsp;constant &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;unless &nbsp;net &nbsp;force &nbsp;act &nbsp;on &nbsp;them. &nbsp;Net &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;required &nbsp;to &nbsp;change &nbsp;velocity. &nbsp;This &nbsp;gives &nbsp;rise &nbsp;to &nbsp;inertia.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Inertia &nbsp;and &nbsp;mass :</strong></p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp;is easier &nbsp;to &nbsp;throw &nbsp;a &nbsp;small &nbsp;stone &nbsp;than &nbsp;push &nbsp;a &nbsp;big &nbsp;boulder .</p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp;is &nbsp;easier &nbsp;to &nbsp;handle &nbsp;a &nbsp;car &nbsp;than &nbsp;a &nbsp;fully &nbsp;loaded &nbsp;18 &nbsp;wheeler . &nbsp;You &nbsp;can &nbsp;start , stop &nbsp;or &nbsp;turn &nbsp;the &nbsp;car &nbsp;as &nbsp;you &nbsp;wish &nbsp;but &nbsp;same &nbsp;cannot &nbsp;be &nbsp;said &nbsp;for &nbsp;the &nbsp;truck</p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp;above &nbsp;example , &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;clear &nbsp;that &nbsp;inertion &nbsp;[ of &nbsp;rest &nbsp;or motion ] &nbsp;is &nbsp;not &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;for &nbsp;all &nbsp;bodies. Infact &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;directly &nbsp;proportional &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;mass.</p>\n\n<p>More &nbsp;the &nbsp;mass , more &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;inertia. &nbsp;To &nbsp;sum &nbsp;it &nbsp;up ; &nbsp;Inertia &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;measure &nbsp;of &nbsp;natural &nbsp;tendency &nbsp;of &nbsp;all &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;to &nbsp;resist &nbsp;any &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;their &nbsp;state &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion.</p>\n\n<p>Mass &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;measure &nbsp;of &nbsp;this &nbsp;inertia .</p>\n\n<p><strong>Second &nbsp;Law &nbsp;of &nbsp;Motion :</strong></p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp;the 1st &nbsp;law &nbsp;we &nbsp;know &nbsp;that &nbsp; net &nbsp;external &nbsp;unbalanced &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;needed &nbsp;to &nbsp;change &nbsp;the &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;body. &nbsp;Rate &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;of &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;is &nbsp;acceleration. &nbsp;This &nbsp;means &nbsp;unbalanced &nbsp;force &nbsp;causes &nbsp;acceleration.</p>\n\n<p>But &nbsp;how &nbsp;do &nbsp;we &nbsp;measure &nbsp;such &nbsp;a &nbsp;force ? We &nbsp;cannot &nbsp;see &nbsp;it , we &nbsp;cannot &nbsp;touch &nbsp;it. &nbsp;But &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;feel &nbsp;its &nbsp;effect &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;form &nbsp;of &nbsp;acceleration.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;second &nbsp;law &nbsp;gives &nbsp;us &nbsp;the &nbsp;measures &nbsp;of &nbsp;force &nbsp;and &nbsp;exactly &nbsp;how &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp;depend &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;applied &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;you &nbsp;try &nbsp;to &nbsp;scare &nbsp;your &nbsp;friend &nbsp;by &nbsp;hitting &nbsp;with &nbsp;tennis &nbsp;ball &nbsp;he &nbsp;may &nbsp;not &nbsp;be &nbsp;effected. &nbsp;Try &nbsp;doing &nbsp;same &nbsp;with &nbsp;cricket &nbsp;ball , &nbsp;he &nbsp;may &nbsp;ran &nbsp;away. &nbsp;This &nbsp;shows &nbsp;the &nbsp;impact &nbsp;of &nbsp;cricket &nbsp;ball &nbsp;is &nbsp;different &nbsp;and &nbsp;greater &nbsp;then &nbsp;that &nbsp;of tennis &nbsp;ball.</p>\n\n<p>Throw &nbsp; a &nbsp;bullet &nbsp;with &nbsp;your &nbsp;hand &nbsp;at &nbsp;a &nbsp;wooden &nbsp;block. &nbsp;The &nbsp;bullet &nbsp;simply &nbsp;touches &nbsp;it &nbsp;and &nbsp;falls &nbsp;down &nbsp;without &nbsp;having &nbsp;any &nbsp;impact &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;block. &nbsp;Now &nbsp;fine &nbsp;the &nbsp; same &nbsp;bullet &nbsp;from &nbsp;a &nbsp;gun. &nbsp;The &nbsp;bullet penetrates &nbsp; the &nbsp;thick &nbsp;wooden &nbsp;block &nbsp;and &nbsp;gets &nbsp;firmly &nbsp;embedded &nbsp;into &nbsp;it. &nbsp;It &nbsp;may &nbsp;even &nbsp;come &nbsp;out &nbsp;of &nbsp;it &nbsp;from &nbsp;the &nbsp;other &nbsp;side.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;above &nbsp;example &nbsp;show &nbsp;that &nbsp;impact &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;depends &nbsp;both &nbsp;on &nbsp;its &nbsp;mass &nbsp;and &nbsp;velocity.</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;body &nbsp;with &nbsp;small mass &nbsp;can &nbsp;have &nbsp;large &nbsp;impact &nbsp;if &nbsp;its &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;is &nbsp;high.</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;slowly &nbsp;moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;can &nbsp;create &nbsp;huge &nbsp;impact &nbsp;if &nbsp;its &nbsp;mass is &nbsp;high.</p>\n\n<p>Newton &nbsp;called &nbsp;this &nbsp;property &nbsp;of &nbsp;moving &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;or &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;in &nbsp;motion &nbsp;which &nbsp;takes &nbsp;into &nbsp;account &nbsp;both &nbsp;mass &nbsp;and &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;as &nbsp;momentum ( p ).</p>\n\n<p>Momentum ( p ) &nbsp;of &nbsp;a moving &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;defined &nbsp;as &nbsp;the &nbsp;product &nbsp;of &nbsp;its &nbsp;mass ( m&nbsp;) &nbsp;and &nbsp;velocity ( v ).</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Mathematically</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; p &nbsp;= &nbsp;mv</p>\n\n<p>Momentum &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;vector &nbsp;quantity. &nbsp;It &nbsp;has &nbsp;both &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;and &nbsp;direction. Its &nbsp;value &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;+ve , &nbsp; -ve &nbsp; or &nbsp;zero.</p>\n\n<p>Units : &nbsp;Its &nbsp;unit &nbsp;is &nbsp;product &nbsp;of &nbsp;units &nbsp;of &nbsp;mass &nbsp;and &nbsp;velocity.</p>\n\n<p>S I &nbsp;unit : &nbsp;Kilogram &nbsp;meter &nbsp;per &nbsp;second</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Kg &nbsp;m&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $</p>\n\n<p>C G S &nbsp;unit &nbsp;: &nbsp;gram &nbsp;centimeter &nbsp;per &nbsp;second &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;g cm&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $</p>\n\n<p>Units &nbsp;of &nbsp;mass ------------------- kg &nbsp; ; &nbsp; g</p>\n\n<p>Units &nbsp;of &nbsp;velocity----------------- &nbsp;m&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $ &nbsp;; &nbsp;c&nbsp;m&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $</p>\n\n<p>Their &nbsp;product---------------------- [ kg ] [ m&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $ ] &nbsp; = &nbsp; kg m&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;[ &nbsp;g ] &nbsp;[ c m&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $] &nbsp; = &nbsp; g &nbsp;cm&nbsp;$ s^{-1} $</p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp;is &nbsp;clear &nbsp;that &nbsp;any &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;will &nbsp;produce &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum. &nbsp;Now &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;is &nbsp;caused &nbsp;by &nbsp;applied &nbsp;force. &nbsp;Hence &nbsp;any &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;is direct &nbsp;result &nbsp;of &nbsp;applied &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;were &nbsp;discussing &nbsp;how &nbsp;to &nbsp;measure &nbsp;force , &nbsp;now &nbsp;you &nbsp;can &nbsp;say &nbsp;if &nbsp;you &nbsp;measure &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum , &nbsp;you &nbsp;can &nbsp;get &nbsp;measure &nbsp;of &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>But , &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;not &nbsp;only &nbsp;depends &nbsp;on &nbsp;force &nbsp;but &nbsp;also &nbsp;on &nbsp;the duration &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;force &nbsp;so &nbsp;if &nbsp;you &nbsp;know &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;time &nbsp;during &nbsp;which &nbsp;the &nbsp;change &nbsp;is &nbsp;taking &nbsp;place , &nbsp;you &nbsp;get &nbsp;the &nbsp;measure &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;applied &nbsp;force &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;for &nbsp;what &nbsp;time &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;acting &nbsp;on &nbsp;a &nbsp;body.</p>\n\n<p>Expressed &nbsp;mathematically &nbsp;the &nbsp;rate &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;of &nbsp; momentum &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;and &nbsp;time &nbsp;during &nbsp;which &nbsp;the &nbsp;change &nbsp;occurs &nbsp;gives &nbsp;us &nbsp;the &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;force. &nbsp;This &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;significance &nbsp;of &nbsp;Newton&#39;s &nbsp; 2nd &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion.</p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp;gives &nbsp;us &nbsp;mathematical &nbsp;expression &nbsp;for &nbsp;force. &nbsp;as &nbsp;you &nbsp;will see, &nbsp;it &nbsp;also &nbsp;tells &nbsp;us &nbsp;exactly &nbsp;how &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp;depends &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Mathematical &nbsp;expression &nbsp; for &nbsp; second &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion :</strong></p>\n\n<p>Consider &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;of &nbsp;mass ( m ) &nbsp;moving &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;with &nbsp;intial &nbsp;velocity ( u ). Let &nbsp;a &nbsp;constant &nbsp;force &nbsp;( F ) &nbsp; acts &nbsp;on &nbsp;it &nbsp;for &nbsp;time &nbsp;( t ) &nbsp;due &nbsp;to &nbsp;which &nbsp;at &nbsp;experience &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp;( a )</p>\n\n<p>Let &nbsp; its &nbsp;final &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;be &nbsp;v</p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;know &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;( p ) &nbsp;= &nbsp;mass &nbsp;X &nbsp;velocity</p>\n\n<p>Initial &nbsp;momentum ( $ p_{1} $ )&nbsp; of &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ p_{1} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp; mass &nbsp;X &nbsp;initial &nbsp;velocity</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ p_{1} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp; m u</p>\n\n<p>Final &nbsp;momentum (&nbsp;$ p_{2} $ )&nbsp; of &nbsp;the &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ p_{2} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp; mass &nbsp;X &nbsp;initial &nbsp;velocity</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ p_{2} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp; m v</p>\n\n<p>Change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;( &nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ &nbsp;p &nbsp;) &nbsp;= &nbsp;&nbsp;$ p_{2} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;&nbsp;$ p_{1} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ &nbsp;p &nbsp; &nbsp; = &nbsp; m v &nbsp;- &nbsp; m u</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ &nbsp;p &nbsp; &nbsp; = &nbsp;m( v &nbsp;- &nbsp;u )</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;changes &nbsp;over &nbsp;time &nbsp;t&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Rate &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;of &nbsp;momentum &nbsp; is &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\bigtriangleup &nbsp; p}{t} $ &nbsp; &nbsp;= &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{m( v &nbsp;- &nbsp;u )}{t} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; From &nbsp;2nd &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; F &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\alpha $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{\\bigtriangleup&nbsp;&nbsp; p}{t} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;F &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\alpha $ &nbsp; = &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\frac{m( v &nbsp;- &nbsp;u )}{t} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;F &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\alpha $ &nbsp; = &nbsp; ma &nbsp; [ &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{( v &nbsp;- &nbsp;u )}{t} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp; acceleration &nbsp;( a ) ]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;F &nbsp; &nbsp;= &nbsp; K m a</p>\n\n<p>Wher &nbsp;K &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;constant &nbsp;of &nbsp;proportionality. &nbsp;we &nbsp;choose &nbsp;S.I &nbsp;unit &nbsp;for &nbsp;force &nbsp;such &nbsp;that &nbsp;K becomes &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;one.</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;unit &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;that &nbsp;force &nbsp;which &nbsp;when &nbsp;acting &nbsp;on &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;of &nbsp;mass &nbsp;1 kg &nbsp;produces &nbsp;an &nbsp;acceleration &nbsp;of &nbsp;1 m$ s^{-2} $ &nbsp;in &nbsp;it.</p>\n\n<p>Thus &nbsp;unit &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;1 &nbsp;newton &nbsp;force</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 1 &nbsp;newton ( N ) &nbsp; = &nbsp;K &nbsp;X &nbsp;1 kg &nbsp;X &nbsp;1&nbsp;m$ s^{-2} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;K &nbsp;= &nbsp;1</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;F &nbsp;= &nbsp;m a</p>\n\n<p>S.I &nbsp;unit &nbsp;of &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;kg&nbsp;m$ s^{-2} $ &nbsp;or &nbsp;newton.</p>\n\n<p>Its &nbsp;symbol &nbsp;is &nbsp;N</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;1 &nbsp;N &nbsp;= &nbsp;1 &nbsp;kg m$ s^{-2} $</p>\n\n<p>Similarly &nbsp;CGS &nbsp;unit &nbsp;of &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp; g c m&nbsp;$ s^{-2} $ &nbsp;or &nbsp;dyne.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;1 &nbsp;dyne &nbsp; = &nbsp;1&nbsp;g c m&nbsp;$ s^{-2} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;1 N &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ 10^{5} $ &nbsp;dyne</p>\n\n<p>* Force &nbsp;is &nbsp;rate &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;of &nbsp;momentum. &nbsp;This &nbsp;fact &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;illustrated &nbsp;through &nbsp;many &nbsp;examples.</p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;a &nbsp;fielder &nbsp;wants &nbsp;to &nbsp;catch &nbsp;a &nbsp;ferocously &nbsp;hit &nbsp;ball , he &nbsp;moves &nbsp;his &nbsp;hand &nbsp;backwards &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball. This &nbsp;way &nbsp;he &nbsp;extends &nbsp;the &nbsp;time &nbsp;during &nbsp;which &nbsp;ball &nbsp;moving &nbsp;with &nbsp;high &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;comes &nbsp;to &nbsp;rest. &nbsp;As &nbsp;time &nbsp;increases &nbsp;rate &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;of &nbsp;momentumis &nbsp;considerabely &nbsp;decreased, &nbsp;decreasing &nbsp;the &nbsp;force &nbsp;and &nbsp;hence &nbsp;the &nbsp;impacton &nbsp;the &nbsp;hands &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;fielder. On &nbsp;the &nbsp;other &nbsp;hand &nbsp;if &nbsp;he &nbsp;directly &nbsp;catches &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball, &nbsp;its &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;falls &nbsp;to &nbsp;zero &nbsp;instantly.&nbsp;The &nbsp; rate &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;of &nbsp;becomes &nbsp;very &nbsp;high. &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball hits &nbsp;the &nbsp;fielder &nbsp;hand &nbsp;with &nbsp;very &nbsp;large &nbsp;force &nbsp;causing &nbsp;hurt &nbsp;or &nbsp;injury.</p>\n\n<p>Shock &nbsp;absorbers &nbsp;in &nbsp;vechiles &nbsp;work &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;principle. &nbsp;They &nbsp;increase &nbsp;the &nbsp;time &nbsp;of &nbsp;impact &nbsp;there &nbsp;by &nbsp;reducing &nbsp;the &nbsp;force &nbsp;and &nbsp;impact.</p>\n\n<p>Another &nbsp;signification &nbsp;of &nbsp;2nd &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;is &nbsp;that &nbsp;it &nbsp;can &nbsp;also &nbsp;give &nbsp;mathematical &nbsp;expression &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;1 st &nbsp;law.</p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;know &nbsp;from &nbsp;2nd &nbsp;law</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; F&nbsp; = &nbsp;ma</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; F &nbsp;= &nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\frac{m( v - u )}{t} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Ft &nbsp;= &nbsp; m v &nbsp;- &nbsp;mu</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp; F &nbsp;= &nbsp;0 &nbsp;, &nbsp; then &nbsp; v &nbsp;= &nbsp;u &nbsp;irrespective &nbsp;of &nbsp;t</p>\n\n<p>This &nbsp;means , &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;absence &nbsp;of &nbsp;external &nbsp;for &nbsp;unbalanced &nbsp; force , &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;continues &nbsp;to &nbsp;move &nbsp;with &nbsp;constant &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;forever. &nbsp;The &nbsp;body &nbsp;remains &nbsp;in &nbsp;uniform &nbsp;motion.</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp; u &nbsp;= &nbsp;v &nbsp;= &nbsp;0 , then &nbsp;body &nbsp;remains &nbsp;at &nbsp;rest &nbsp;forever &nbsp;until &nbsp;external &nbsp;unbalanced &nbsp;force &nbsp;F &nbsp;acts &nbsp;on &nbsp;it.</p>\n\n<p>Remember:</p>\n\n<p>1 st &nbsp;law &nbsp;gives &nbsp;cause &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;force</p>\n\n<p>2 nd &nbsp;law gives mathematical expression &nbsp;or &nbsp;measure &nbsp;for &nbsp;cause &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;force</p>\n\n<p>What &nbsp;about &nbsp;the &nbsp;3 rd &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion ? well..... &nbsp;it &nbsp;tells &nbsp;us &nbsp;literally &nbsp;how &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;reacts &nbsp;when &nbsp;acted &nbsp;upon &nbsp;by &nbsp;a &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Third &nbsp; Law &nbsp;of &nbsp;Motion :</strong></p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp; states &nbsp;that &nbsp;when &nbsp;a &nbsp;body &nbsp;exerts &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;another &nbsp;body, &nbsp;the &nbsp;2nd &nbsp;body &nbsp;immediately &nbsp;exerts &nbsp;equal &nbsp;and &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;first &nbsp;body.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;force &nbsp;exerted &nbsp;by &nbsp;the &nbsp;1st &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;action &nbsp;force &nbsp;or &nbsp;simply &nbsp;action.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;force &nbsp;exerted &nbsp;by &nbsp;the &nbsp;2 nd &nbsp;body &nbsp;back &nbsp;on &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;first &nbsp;body &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;reaction &nbsp;force &nbsp;or &nbsp;simply &nbsp;reaction.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;otherwords , newton&#39;s &nbsp;3 rd &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;stated &nbsp;as &nbsp;For &nbsp;every &nbsp;action &nbsp;there &nbsp;is &nbsp;equal &nbsp;and &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;reaction.</p>\n\n<p>Note &nbsp;: &nbsp;These &nbsp;forces &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;in &nbsp;magnitude &nbsp;but &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;in &nbsp;direction.</p>\n\n<p>Equally &nbsp;important &nbsp;is &nbsp;to &nbsp;note &nbsp;that &nbsp;action &nbsp;and &nbsp;reaction &nbsp;act &nbsp;on &nbsp;two &nbsp;different &nbsp;bodies. &nbsp;Hence &nbsp;they &nbsp;do &nbsp;not &nbsp;cancel &nbsp;each &nbsp;other. Both &nbsp;simultenuously &nbsp;produce &nbsp;their &nbsp;own &nbsp;effects.</p>\n\n<p>Our &nbsp;daily &nbsp;lives &nbsp;are &nbsp;full &nbsp;of &nbsp;examples &nbsp;of &nbsp;3 rd &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p>How &nbsp;do &nbsp;you &nbsp;walk &nbsp;or &nbsp;run ? You &nbsp;exert &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;earth &nbsp;through &nbsp;your &nbsp;legs &nbsp;in &nbsp;backward &nbsp;direction.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;earth &nbsp;immediately &nbsp;exerts &nbsp;same &nbsp;force &nbsp;in &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;forward &nbsp;direction &nbsp;on &nbsp;your &nbsp;legs. &nbsp;This &nbsp;propels &nbsp;you &nbsp;forward.</p>\n\n<p>Recoil &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;gun :</p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;you &nbsp;fire &nbsp;a &nbsp;gun , &nbsp;it &nbsp;exerts &nbsp;a &nbsp;large &nbsp;action &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;bullet &nbsp;effecting &nbsp;it &nbsp;out &nbsp;with &nbsp;large &nbsp;velocity.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;bullet &nbsp;in &nbsp;turn &nbsp;exerts &nbsp;equal &nbsp;reaction &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;gun &nbsp;in &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;direction. &nbsp;Hence &nbsp;the &nbsp;gun &nbsp;recoils &nbsp;back &nbsp;whenever &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;shot.</p>\n\n<p>Sailor &nbsp;:</p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;a &nbsp;sailor &nbsp;jumps &nbsp;from &nbsp;his &nbsp;ship &nbsp;onto &nbsp;ground, &nbsp;he &nbsp;pushes &nbsp;the &nbsp;ship &nbsp;in &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;direction.This &nbsp;is &nbsp;action &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;ship &nbsp;immediately &nbsp;exerts &nbsp;equal &nbsp;and &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;reaction &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;sailor. &nbsp;as &nbsp;a &nbsp;result, &nbsp;the &nbsp;sailor &nbsp;can &nbsp;jump &nbsp;forward.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 0, 0),
