(101, 'inline_html', '<p>When &nbsp;two &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;collide &nbsp;with &nbsp;each &nbsp;other , &nbsp;the &nbsp;total &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;of &nbsp;both &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;before &nbsp;collision &nbsp;is &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;their &nbsp;total &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;after &nbsp;collision &nbsp;provided. No &nbsp;external &nbsp;un balanced &nbsp;force &nbsp;acts &nbsp;on &nbsp;them. This &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;conservation &nbsp;of &nbsp;momentum.</p>\n\n<p><strong>mathematical &nbsp;proof</strong> :</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Consider &nbsp;2 &nbsp;balls &nbsp;A &nbsp;and &nbsp;B of &nbsp;masses &nbsp;be$ M_{A} $ &nbsp; and &nbsp;$ M_{B} $ &nbsp; respectively.</p>\n\n<p>As &nbsp;shown &nbsp;in &nbsp;figure , &nbsp;both &nbsp;balls &nbsp;are &nbsp;moving &nbsp;in &nbsp;same &nbsp;directions.</p>\n\n<p>Let ,</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ u_{A} $ &nbsp; ------------ &nbsp;initial &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;of &nbsp;A</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ u_{B} $ &nbsp; ------------ &nbsp;initial &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;of &nbsp;B</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Such &nbsp;that &nbsp;$ u_{A} $ &nbsp;&gt; &nbsp;$ u_{B} $</p>\n\n<p>After &nbsp;some &nbsp;time, &nbsp;ball &nbsp;A &nbsp;collides &nbsp;with &nbsp;ball &nbsp;B. After &nbsp;the &nbsp;collision &nbsp;which &nbsp;last &nbsp;for &nbsp;say &nbsp;time &nbsp;t , &nbsp;both &nbsp;balls &nbsp;separate &nbsp;and &nbsp;move &nbsp;in &nbsp;same &nbsp;direction &nbsp;but &nbsp;with &nbsp;different &nbsp;velocities &nbsp;as &nbsp;a &nbsp;result &nbsp;of &nbsp;their &nbsp;collision.</p>\n\n<p>Let &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ v_{A} $ &nbsp; ------------ &nbsp;initial &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;of &nbsp;A</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ v_{B} $ &nbsp; ------------ &nbsp;initial &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;of &nbsp;B</p>\n\n<p>As &nbsp;ball &nbsp;A &nbsp;strikes &nbsp;B , it exerts &nbsp;force &nbsp;&nbsp;$ F_{AB} $ &nbsp; on &nbsp;B.</p>\n\n<p>According &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;3 rd &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion, B &nbsp;exerts &nbsp;equal &nbsp;and &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;force &nbsp;$ F_{BA} $ &nbsp;on &nbsp;A.</p>\n\n<p>Lets &nbsp;1 st &nbsp;calculate &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;of &nbsp;both &nbsp;balls</p>\n\n<p>Ball &nbsp;A &nbsp; &nbsp; [Momentum &nbsp; = &nbsp; mass &nbsp;X &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Initial &nbsp; momentum &nbsp;$ P_{A1} $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ u_{A} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Final &nbsp; momentum &nbsp;$ P_{A2} $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ v_{A} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;($ \\bigtriangleup $&nbsp;$ P_{A} $ ) &nbsp;= &nbsp;&nbsp;$ P_{A2} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ P_{A1} $</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigtriangleup $&nbsp;$ P_{A} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ v_{A} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ u_{A} $</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigtriangleup $&nbsp;$ P_{A} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;( $ v_{A} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp; &nbsp; $ u_{A} $)</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;The &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;occurs &nbsp;during &nbsp;collision &nbsp;which &nbsp;lasts for &nbsp;time &nbsp;t&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Rate &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;of &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;$ \\frac{\\bigtriangleup&nbsp;P_{A}}{t} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;M_{A} &nbsp; ( &nbsp;v_{A} &nbsp; - &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;u_{A} )}{t} $</p>\n\n<p>But &nbsp;rate &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;is &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;force &nbsp;exerted &nbsp;by &nbsp;A &nbsp;or &nbsp;B</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;$ F_{AB} $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{\\bigtriangleup&nbsp;P_{A}}{t} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$ F_{AB} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;M_{A}&nbsp;&nbsp; (&nbsp;&nbsp;v_{A}&nbsp;&nbsp; - &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;u_{A}&nbsp;)}{t} $ &nbsp;------------------(1)</p>\n\n<p>Similarly &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;carry &nbsp;out &nbsp;above &nbsp;steps &nbsp;for &nbsp;ball B &nbsp;for &nbsp;force &nbsp;$ F_{BA} $ &nbsp;exerted &nbsp; by &nbsp;B &nbsp;on &nbsp;A</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;$ F_{BA} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;M_{B}&nbsp;&nbsp; (&nbsp;&nbsp;v_{B}&nbsp;&nbsp; - &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;u_{B}&nbsp;)}{t} $ &nbsp;---------------(2)</p>\n\n<p>According &nbsp;to &nbsp;3 rd &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ F_{AB} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ F_{BA} $&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp; (1) &nbsp; and &nbsp;(2)</p>\n\n<p>[ $ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;M_{A}&nbsp;&nbsp; (&nbsp;&nbsp;v_{A}&nbsp;&nbsp; - &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;u_{A}&nbsp;)}{t} $] &nbsp;= &nbsp;- [ $ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;M_{B}&nbsp;&nbsp; (&nbsp;&nbsp;v_{B}&nbsp;&nbsp; - &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;u_{B}&nbsp;)}{t} $]</p>\n\n<p>Solving &nbsp;the &nbsp;brackets, &nbsp;we &nbsp;get</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ v_{A} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ u_{A} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;- &nbsp;&nbsp;$ M_{B} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ v_{B} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ M_{B} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ u_{B} $&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Rearranging &nbsp;we &nbsp;get</p>\n\n<p>$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ u_{A} $ &nbsp;+&nbsp;$ M_{B} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ u_{B} $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ v_{A} $ &nbsp;+ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ M_{B} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ v_{B} $</p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;will &nbsp;notice &nbsp;that &nbsp;left &nbsp;side &nbsp;represents &nbsp;total &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;of &nbsp;both &nbsp;balls &nbsp;before &nbsp;collision &nbsp;while &nbsp;right &nbsp;represent &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;after &nbsp;collision</p>\n\n<p>Therefore &nbsp;total &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;before &nbsp;collision &nbsp;is &nbsp;always &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;total &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;after &nbsp;collision</p>\n\n<p>Ex :</p>\n\n<p>An &nbsp;intensity &nbsp;feature &nbsp;of &nbsp;any &nbsp;conservation &nbsp;law [ there &nbsp;are &nbsp;many &nbsp;eg : &nbsp;conservation &nbsp;of &nbsp;charge , energy &nbsp;etc ] &nbsp;is &nbsp;that &nbsp;it &nbsp;cannot &nbsp;be &nbsp;proved . &nbsp;These &nbsp;laws &nbsp;are &nbsp;fundamentals &nbsp;laws &nbsp;in &nbsp;physics &nbsp;based &nbsp;on &nbsp;observations &nbsp;and &nbsp;experiments . These &nbsp;laws &nbsp;can &nbsp;be either &nbsp;verified&nbsp; or &nbsp;disproved &nbsp;by &nbsp;experiments &nbsp;results &nbsp;are &nbsp;in &nbsp;conformity &nbsp;the &nbsp;laws &nbsp;are &nbsp;said &nbsp;to &nbsp;be verified. A &nbsp;single &nbsp;experiment, &nbsp;whose &nbsp;result &nbsp;conclusively &nbsp;does &nbsp;not &nbsp;confirm &nbsp;with &nbsp;law, &nbsp;is &nbsp;enough &nbsp;to &nbsp;disprove &nbsp;the &nbsp;law.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;conservation &nbsp;of &nbsp;energy &nbsp;was &nbsp;formulated &nbsp;nearly &nbsp;300 years &nbsp;ago.it &nbsp;has &nbsp;been &nbsp;repeatedly &nbsp;verified &nbsp;from &nbsp;large &nbsp;number &nbsp;of &nbsp;experiments &nbsp;and &nbsp;observation &nbsp;till now &nbsp;not. &nbsp;Single &nbsp;situation, &nbsp;observation &nbsp;has &nbsp;contradiccted &nbsp;this &nbsp;law.</p>\n', 'Conservation  of  Momentum', '', '<p>When &nbsp;two &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;collide &nbsp;with &nbsp;each &nbsp;other , &nbsp;the &nbsp;total &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;of &nbsp;both &nbsp;bodies &nbsp;before &nbsp;collision &nbsp;is &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;their &nbsp;total &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;after &nbsp;collision &nbsp;provided. No &nbsp;external &nbsp;un balanced &nbsp;force &nbsp;acts &nbsp;on &nbsp;them. This &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;conservation &nbsp;of &nbsp;momentum.</p>\n\n<p><strong>mathematical &nbsp;proof</strong> :</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Consider &nbsp;2 &nbsp;balls &nbsp;A &nbsp;and &nbsp;B of &nbsp;masses &nbsp;be$ M_{A} $ &nbsp; and &nbsp;$ M_{B} $ &nbsp; respectively.</p>\n\n<p>As &nbsp;shown &nbsp;in &nbsp;figure , &nbsp;both &nbsp;balls &nbsp;are &nbsp;moving &nbsp;in &nbsp;same &nbsp;directions.</p>\n\n<p>Let ,</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ u_{A} $ &nbsp; ------------ &nbsp;initial &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;of &nbsp;A</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ u_{B} $ &nbsp; ------------ &nbsp;initial &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;of &nbsp;B</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Such &nbsp;that &nbsp;$ u_{A} $ &nbsp;&gt; &nbsp;$ u_{B} $</p>\n\n<p>After &nbsp;some &nbsp;time, &nbsp;ball &nbsp;A &nbsp;collides &nbsp;with &nbsp;ball &nbsp;B. After &nbsp;the &nbsp;collision &nbsp;which &nbsp;last &nbsp;for &nbsp;say &nbsp;time &nbsp;t , &nbsp;both &nbsp;balls &nbsp;separate &nbsp;and &nbsp;move &nbsp;in &nbsp;same &nbsp;direction &nbsp;but &nbsp;with &nbsp;different &nbsp;velocities &nbsp;as &nbsp;a &nbsp;result &nbsp;of &nbsp;their &nbsp;collision.</p>\n\n<p>Let &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ v_{A} $ &nbsp; ------------ &nbsp;initial &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;of &nbsp;A</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$ v_{B} $ &nbsp; ------------ &nbsp;initial &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;of &nbsp;B</p>\n\n<p>As &nbsp;ball &nbsp;A &nbsp;strikes &nbsp;B , it exerts &nbsp;force &nbsp;&nbsp;$ F_{AB} $ &nbsp; on &nbsp;B.</p>\n\n<p>According &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;3 rd &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion, B &nbsp;exerts &nbsp;equal &nbsp;and &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;force &nbsp;$ F_{BA} $ &nbsp;on &nbsp;A.</p>\n\n<p>Lets &nbsp;1 st &nbsp;calculate &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;of &nbsp;both &nbsp;balls</p>\n\n<p>Ball &nbsp;A &nbsp; &nbsp; [Momentum &nbsp; = &nbsp; mass &nbsp;X &nbsp;velocity &nbsp;]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Initial &nbsp; momentum &nbsp;$ P_{A1} $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ u_{A} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Final &nbsp; momentum &nbsp;$ P_{A2} $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ v_{A} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;($ \\bigtriangleup $&nbsp;$ P_{A} $ ) &nbsp;= &nbsp;&nbsp;$ P_{A2} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ P_{A1} $</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigtriangleup $&nbsp;$ P_{A} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ v_{A} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ u_{A} $</p>\n\n<p>$ \\bigtriangleup $&nbsp;$ P_{A} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;( $ v_{A} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp; &nbsp; $ u_{A} $)</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;The &nbsp;change &nbsp;in &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;occurs &nbsp;during &nbsp;collision &nbsp;which &nbsp;lasts for &nbsp;time &nbsp;t&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Rate &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;of &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;$ \\frac{\\bigtriangleup&nbsp;P_{A}}{t} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;M_{A} &nbsp; ( &nbsp;v_{A} &nbsp; - &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;u_{A} )}{t} $</p>\n\n<p>But &nbsp;rate &nbsp;of &nbsp;change &nbsp;is &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;force &nbsp;exerted &nbsp;by &nbsp;A &nbsp;or &nbsp;B</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;$ F_{AB} $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{\\bigtriangleup&nbsp;P_{A}}{t} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$ F_{AB} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;M_{A}&nbsp;&nbsp; (&nbsp;&nbsp;v_{A}&nbsp;&nbsp; - &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;u_{A}&nbsp;)}{t} $ &nbsp;------------------(1)</p>\n\n<p>Similarly &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;carry &nbsp;out &nbsp;above &nbsp;steps &nbsp;for &nbsp;ball B &nbsp;for &nbsp;force &nbsp;$ F_{BA} $ &nbsp;exerted &nbsp; by &nbsp;B &nbsp;on &nbsp;A</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;$ F_{BA} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;M_{B}&nbsp;&nbsp; (&nbsp;&nbsp;v_{B}&nbsp;&nbsp; - &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;u_{B}&nbsp;)}{t} $ &nbsp;---------------(2)</p>\n\n<p>According &nbsp;to &nbsp;3 rd &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ F_{AB} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ F_{BA} $&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp; (1) &nbsp; and &nbsp;(2)</p>\n\n<p>[ $ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;M_{A}&nbsp;&nbsp; (&nbsp;&nbsp;v_{A}&nbsp;&nbsp; - &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;u_{A}&nbsp;)}{t} $] &nbsp;= &nbsp;- [ $ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;M_{B}&nbsp;&nbsp; (&nbsp;&nbsp;v_{B}&nbsp;&nbsp; - &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;u_{B}&nbsp;)}{t} $]</p>\n\n<p>Solving &nbsp;the &nbsp;brackets, &nbsp;we &nbsp;get</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ v_{A} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ u_{A} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;- &nbsp;&nbsp;$ M_{B} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ v_{B} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ M_{B} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ u_{B} $&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Rearranging &nbsp;we &nbsp;get</p>\n\n<p>$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ u_{A} $ &nbsp;+&nbsp;$ M_{B} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ u_{B} $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$ M_{A} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ v_{A} $ &nbsp;+ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ M_{B} $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ v_{B} $</p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;will &nbsp;notice &nbsp;that &nbsp;left &nbsp;side &nbsp;represents &nbsp;total &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;of &nbsp;both &nbsp;balls &nbsp;before &nbsp;collision &nbsp;while &nbsp;right &nbsp;represent &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;after &nbsp;collision</p>\n\n<p>Therefore &nbsp;total &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;before &nbsp;collision &nbsp;is &nbsp;always &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;total &nbsp;momentum &nbsp;after &nbsp;collision</p>\n\n<p>Ex :</p>\n\n<p>An &nbsp;intensity &nbsp;feature &nbsp;of &nbsp;any &nbsp;conservation &nbsp;law [ there &nbsp;are &nbsp;many &nbsp;eg : &nbsp;conservation &nbsp;of &nbsp;charge , energy &nbsp;etc ] &nbsp;is &nbsp;that &nbsp;it &nbsp;cannot &nbsp;be &nbsp;proved . &nbsp;These &nbsp;laws &nbsp;are &nbsp;fundamentals &nbsp;laws &nbsp;in &nbsp;physics &nbsp;based &nbsp;on &nbsp;observations &nbsp;and &nbsp;experiments . These &nbsp;laws &nbsp;can &nbsp;be either &nbsp;verified&nbsp; or &nbsp;disproved &nbsp;by &nbsp;experiments &nbsp;results &nbsp;are &nbsp;in &nbsp;conformity &nbsp;the &nbsp;laws &nbsp;are &nbsp;said &nbsp;to &nbsp;be verified. A &nbsp;single &nbsp;experiment, &nbsp;whose &nbsp;result &nbsp;conclusively &nbsp;does &nbsp;not &nbsp;confirm &nbsp;with &nbsp;law, &nbsp;is &nbsp;enough &nbsp;to &nbsp;disprove &nbsp;the &nbsp;law.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;conservation &nbsp;of &nbsp;energy &nbsp;was &nbsp;formulated &nbsp;nearly &nbsp;300 years &nbsp;ago.it &nbsp;has &nbsp;been &nbsp;repeatedly &nbsp;verified &nbsp;from &nbsp;large &nbsp;number &nbsp;of &nbsp;experiments &nbsp;and &nbsp;observation &nbsp;till now &nbsp;not. &nbsp;Single &nbsp;situation, &nbsp;observation &nbsp;has &nbsp;contradiccted &nbsp;this &nbsp;law.</p>\n', 0, 0),
(102, 'inline_html', '<p>Cells &nbsp;are &nbsp;the &nbsp;smallest &nbsp;living &nbsp;units &nbsp;in &nbsp;all &nbsp;living &nbsp;organisms. Every &nbsp;organism &nbsp;is &nbsp;made &nbsp;up &nbsp;of &nbsp;cell. Robert &nbsp;Hooke &nbsp;discovered &nbsp;cell &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;year &nbsp;1965 &nbsp;with &nbsp;the &nbsp;help &nbsp;of &nbsp;microscope. Now &nbsp;the &nbsp;microscopes &nbsp;are &nbsp;advanced. The &nbsp;common &nbsp;microscope &nbsp;which &nbsp;we &nbsp;use &nbsp;in &nbsp;study &nbsp;or &nbsp;laboratory &nbsp;purpose &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;compound &nbsp;microscope. ( Cell &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;basic &nbsp;structural &nbsp;functional &nbsp;and &nbsp;biological &nbsp;unit &nbsp; of &nbsp;all &nbsp;known &nbsp;lving &nbsp;organisms. &nbsp;Cells &nbsp;are &nbsp;the &nbsp;smallest &nbsp;unit &nbsp;of &nbsp;life &nbsp;that &nbsp;can &nbsp;replicate &nbsp;independentaly &nbsp;and &nbsp;are &nbsp;often &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;building &nbsp;blocks &nbsp;of &nbsp;life.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Compound &nbsp;microscope &nbsp;consists &nbsp;of &nbsp;two &nbsp;lenses ; &nbsp;eyepiece &nbsp;and &nbsp;objective. The &nbsp;objective &nbsp;or &nbsp;specimen &nbsp;is &nbsp;put &nbsp;in &nbsp;aslide &nbsp;and &nbsp;is &nbsp;placed &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;stage. Fine &nbsp;adjustement &nbsp;focuses &nbsp;the &nbsp;object. &nbsp;There &nbsp;are &nbsp;various &nbsp;other &nbsp;parts that &nbsp;helps &nbsp;to &nbsp;obtain &nbsp;a clearer &nbsp;image.</p>\n', 'Introduction', '', '<p>Cells &nbsp;are &nbsp;the &nbsp;smallest &nbsp;living &nbsp;units &nbsp;in &nbsp;all &nbsp;living &nbsp;organisms. Every &nbsp;organism &nbsp;is &nbsp;made &nbsp;up &nbsp;of &nbsp;cell. Robert &nbsp;Hooke &nbsp;discovered &nbsp;cell &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;year &nbsp;1965 &nbsp;with &nbsp;the &nbsp;help &nbsp;of &nbsp;microscope. Now &nbsp;the &nbsp;microscopes &nbsp;are &nbsp;advanced. The &nbsp;common &nbsp;microscope &nbsp;which &nbsp;we &nbsp;use &nbsp;in &nbsp;study &nbsp;or &nbsp;laboratory &nbsp;purpose &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;compound &nbsp;microscope. ( Cell &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;basic &nbsp;structural &nbsp;functional &nbsp;and &nbsp;biological &nbsp;unit &nbsp; of &nbsp;all &nbsp;known &nbsp;lving &nbsp;organisms. &nbsp;Cells &nbsp;are &nbsp;the &nbsp;smallest &nbsp;unit &nbsp;of &nbsp;life &nbsp;that &nbsp;can &nbsp;replicate &nbsp;independentaly &nbsp;and &nbsp;are &nbsp;often &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;building &nbsp;blocks &nbsp;of &nbsp;life.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Compound &nbsp;microscope &nbsp;consists &nbsp;of &nbsp;two &nbsp;lenses ; &nbsp;eyepiece &nbsp;and &nbsp;objective. The &nbsp;objective &nbsp;or &nbsp;specimen &nbsp;is &nbsp;put &nbsp;in &nbsp;aslide &nbsp;and &nbsp;is &nbsp;placed &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;stage. Fine &nbsp;adjustement &nbsp;focuses &nbsp;the &nbsp;object. &nbsp;There &nbsp;are &nbsp;various &nbsp;other &nbsp;parts that &nbsp;helps &nbsp;to &nbsp;obtain &nbsp;a clearer &nbsp;image.</p>\n', 0, 0),
