(108, 'inline_html', '<h3><strong>History :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;word &#39; geometry &#39; &nbsp;is &nbsp;derived &nbsp;from &nbsp;the &nbsp;Greek. &nbsp;&#39; geo &#39; &nbsp;means &nbsp;earth &nbsp;and &nbsp;&#39; metrein &#39; means &nbsp;measure.</p>\n\n<p>Geometry &nbsp;is &nbsp;widely &nbsp;used &nbsp;in &nbsp;daily &nbsp;life &nbsp;activities &nbsp;such &nbsp;as &nbsp;painting , &nbsp;handicrafts &nbsp;laying &nbsp;of &nbsp;floor &nbsp;design , &nbsp;ploughing &nbsp;and &nbsp;sowing &nbsp;of &nbsp;seeds &nbsp;in &nbsp;fields.</p>\n\n<p>Euclid ( 325 - 265 &nbsp;B . C ) &nbsp;of &nbsp;Alexandria &nbsp;in &nbsp;Egypt &nbsp;wrote &nbsp;13 &nbsp;books &nbsp;called &nbsp;&#39; The &nbsp;Elements &#39;.</p>\n\n<p>Euclid &nbsp;defined &nbsp;point , &nbsp;line , &nbsp;plane. &nbsp;In &nbsp;Book &nbsp;1 &nbsp;of &nbsp;his &nbsp;elements , &nbsp;Euclid &nbsp;listed &nbsp; 23 &nbsp;definitions.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Point&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;:</h3>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;point &nbsp;is &nbsp;that &nbsp;which &nbsp;has &nbsp;no &nbsp;part.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Line &nbsp;:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;breadthless &nbsp;length. &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;A &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;made &nbsp;up &nbsp;of &nbsp;an &nbsp;infinite &nbsp;number &nbsp;of &nbsp;points &nbsp;and &nbsp;it &nbsp;has &nbsp;only &nbsp;length.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; It &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;extended &nbsp;in &nbsp;both &nbsp;directions. &nbsp;A &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;denoted &nbsp;by &nbsp;&quot;&nbsp;$ \\underset{AB}{\\leftrightarrow} $ &quot;</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig1(2).png" style="height:124px; width:300px" /></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Line &nbsp;segment &nbsp;:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;line &nbsp;segment &nbsp;has &nbsp;two &nbsp;end &nbsp;points. &nbsp;It &nbsp;is &nbsp;denoted &nbsp;by &nbsp;&quot;$ \\bar{AB} $ &quot;</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig2(2).png" style="height:83px; width:300px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Ray &nbsp;:</strong></p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;ray &nbsp;extends &nbsp;indefinitely in &nbsp;one &nbsp;direction &nbsp;from &nbsp;any &nbsp;given &nbsp;point. &nbsp;It &nbsp;is &nbsp;denoted &nbsp;by &nbsp;&quot;&nbsp;$ \\underset{OA}{\\rightarrow} $ &quot;</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig3(4).png" style="height:86px; width:230px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Plane &nbsp;:</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;It &nbsp;is &nbsp;flat &nbsp;surface &nbsp;having &nbsp;length &nbsp;and &nbsp;breadth , &nbsp;but &nbsp;no &nbsp;thickness. &nbsp;It &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;two &nbsp;dimensional &nbsp;figure.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig4(1).png" style="height:119px; width:200px" /></p>\n\n<h3><strong>Space &nbsp;:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Space &nbsp;exists &nbsp;in &nbsp;three &nbsp;dimensions. &nbsp;Space &nbsp;is &nbsp;made &nbsp;up &nbsp;of &nbsp;all &nbsp;possible &nbsp;planes , &nbsp;lines &nbsp;and &nbsp;points. &nbsp;It &nbsp;extends &nbsp;indefinitely &nbsp;in &nbsp;all &nbsp;directions.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;geometry &nbsp;there &nbsp;are &nbsp;undefined &nbsp;terms &nbsp;like &nbsp;point , &nbsp;plane &nbsp;and &nbsp;line.</p>\n\n<p>Angles , &nbsp;circle &nbsp;and &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;are &nbsp;examples &nbsp;for &nbsp;defined &nbsp;terms</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Some &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;Euclid&#39;s &nbsp;axioms &nbsp;:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Things &nbsp;which &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;things &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;one &nbsp;another.</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;equals &nbsp;are &nbsp;added &nbsp;to &nbsp;equals , &nbsp;the &nbsp;wholes &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal.</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;equals &nbsp;are &nbsp;substracted &nbsp;from &nbsp;equals , &nbsp;the &nbsp;remainders &nbsp;are &nbsp;also &nbsp;equal.</p>\n\n<p>Things &nbsp;which &nbsp;coincide &nbsp;with &nbsp;one &nbsp;another &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;one &nbsp;another.</p>\n\n<p>Things &nbsp;which &nbsp;are &nbsp;double &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;things &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;one &nbsp;another.</p>\n\n<p>Things &nbsp;which &nbsp;are &nbsp;halves &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;things &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;one &nbsp;another.</p>\n\n<h2><strong>Euclid&#39;s &nbsp;postulates :</strong></h2>\n\n<h3><strong>Postulate - 1 :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>There &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;unique &nbsp;line &nbsp;that &nbsp;passes &nbsp;through &nbsp;the &nbsp;given &nbsp;two &nbsp;distinct &nbsp;points.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;Euclid&#39;s &nbsp;terms ,&quot; To &nbsp;draw &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;from &nbsp;any &nbsp;point &nbsp;to &nbsp;any &nbsp;point&quot;.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig5(1).png" style="height:79px; width:280px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Postulate - 2&nbsp;:</strong></p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;line &nbsp;segment &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;extended &nbsp;on &nbsp;either &nbsp;side &nbsp;to &nbsp;form &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;Euclid&#39;s &nbsp;terms ,&quot; To &nbsp;produce &nbsp;a &nbsp;finate &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;continuously &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line&quot;.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig6(1).png" style="height:85px; width:420px" /></p>\n\n<h3><strong>Postulate - 3&nbsp;:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;can &nbsp;describe &nbsp;a &nbsp;circle &nbsp;with &nbsp;any &nbsp;centre&nbsp; and &nbsp;radius.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Radii &nbsp;of &nbsp;four &nbsp;circles &nbsp;are &nbsp;given &nbsp;as &nbsp;3 cm , &nbsp;4 cm , &nbsp;4.5 cm &nbsp;and &nbsp;5 cm. &nbsp;Using &nbsp;a &nbsp;compass , &nbsp;draw &nbsp;circles &nbsp;with &nbsp;these &nbsp;radii &nbsp;taking &nbsp; P , Q , R &nbsp;and &nbsp;S &nbsp;as &nbsp;their &nbsp;centres.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig7(1).png" style="height:135px; width:300px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Postulate - 4&nbsp;:</strong></p>\n\n<p>All &nbsp;right &nbsp;angles &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;one &nbsp;another.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Postulate - 5&nbsp;:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;falling &nbsp;on &nbsp;two &nbsp;straight &nbsp;lines &nbsp;makes &nbsp;the &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;it &nbsp;taken &nbsp;together &nbsp;is &nbsp;less &nbsp;than &nbsp;two &nbsp;right &nbsp;angles , &nbsp;then &nbsp;the &nbsp;two &nbsp;straight &nbsp;lines , &nbsp;if &nbsp;produced &nbsp;infinitely , &nbsp;meet &nbsp;on &nbsp;that &nbsp;side &nbsp;which &nbsp;the &nbsp;sum &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;angles &nbsp;is &nbsp;less &nbsp;than &nbsp;two &nbsp;right &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n', 'Elements   of   Geometry', '', '<h3><strong>History :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;word &#39; geometry &#39; &nbsp;is &nbsp;derived &nbsp;from &nbsp;the &nbsp;Greek. &nbsp;&#39; geo &#39; &nbsp;means &nbsp;earth &nbsp;and &nbsp;&#39; metrein &#39; means &nbsp;measure.</p>\n\n<p>Geometry &nbsp;is &nbsp;widely &nbsp;used &nbsp;in &nbsp;daily &nbsp;life &nbsp;activities &nbsp;such &nbsp;as &nbsp;painting , &nbsp;handicrafts &nbsp;laying &nbsp;of &nbsp;floor &nbsp;design , &nbsp;ploughing &nbsp;and &nbsp;sowing &nbsp;of &nbsp;seeds &nbsp;in &nbsp;fields.</p>\n\n<p>Euclid ( 325 - 265 &nbsp;B . C ) &nbsp;of &nbsp;Alexandria &nbsp;in &nbsp;Egypt &nbsp;wrote &nbsp;13 &nbsp;books &nbsp;called &nbsp;&#39; The &nbsp;Elements &#39;.</p>\n\n<p>Euclid &nbsp;defined &nbsp;point , &nbsp;line , &nbsp;plane. &nbsp;In &nbsp;Book &nbsp;1 &nbsp;of &nbsp;his &nbsp;elements , &nbsp;Euclid &nbsp;listed &nbsp; 23 &nbsp;definitions.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Point&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;:</h3>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;point &nbsp;is &nbsp;that &nbsp;which &nbsp;has &nbsp;no &nbsp;part.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Line &nbsp;:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;breadthless &nbsp;length. &nbsp;i.e &nbsp;A &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;made &nbsp;up &nbsp;of &nbsp;an &nbsp;infinite &nbsp;number &nbsp;of &nbsp;points &nbsp;and &nbsp;it &nbsp;has &nbsp;only &nbsp;length.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; It &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;extended &nbsp;in &nbsp;both &nbsp;directions. &nbsp;A &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;denoted &nbsp;by &nbsp;&quot;&nbsp;$ \\underset{AB}{\\leftrightarrow} $ &quot;</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig1(2).png" style="height:124px; width:300px" /></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Line &nbsp;segment &nbsp;:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;line &nbsp;segment &nbsp;has &nbsp;two &nbsp;end &nbsp;points. &nbsp;It &nbsp;is &nbsp;denoted &nbsp;by &nbsp;&quot;$ \\bar{AB} $ &quot;</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig2(2).png" style="height:83px; width:300px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Ray &nbsp;:</strong></p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;ray &nbsp;extends &nbsp;indefinitely in &nbsp;one &nbsp;direction &nbsp;from &nbsp;any &nbsp;given &nbsp;point. &nbsp;It &nbsp;is &nbsp;denoted &nbsp;by &nbsp;&quot;&nbsp;$ \\underset{OA}{\\rightarrow} $ &quot;</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig3(4).png" style="height:86px; width:230px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Plane &nbsp;:</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;It &nbsp;is &nbsp;flat &nbsp;surface &nbsp;having &nbsp;length &nbsp;and &nbsp;breadth , &nbsp;but &nbsp;no &nbsp;thickness. &nbsp;It &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;two &nbsp;dimensional &nbsp;figure.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig4(1).png" style="height:119px; width:200px" /></p>\n\n<h3><strong>Space &nbsp;:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Space &nbsp;exists &nbsp;in &nbsp;three &nbsp;dimensions. &nbsp;Space &nbsp;is &nbsp;made &nbsp;up &nbsp;of &nbsp;all &nbsp;possible &nbsp;planes , &nbsp;lines &nbsp;and &nbsp;points. &nbsp;It &nbsp;extends &nbsp;indefinitely &nbsp;in &nbsp;all &nbsp;directions.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;geometry &nbsp;there &nbsp;are &nbsp;undefined &nbsp;terms &nbsp;like &nbsp;point , &nbsp;plane &nbsp;and &nbsp;line.</p>\n\n<p>Angles , &nbsp;circle &nbsp;and &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;are &nbsp;examples &nbsp;for &nbsp;defined &nbsp;terms</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Some &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;Euclid&#39;s &nbsp;axioms &nbsp;:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Things &nbsp;which &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;things &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;one &nbsp;another.</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;equals &nbsp;are &nbsp;added &nbsp;to &nbsp;equals , &nbsp;the &nbsp;wholes &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal.</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;equals &nbsp;are &nbsp;substracted &nbsp;from &nbsp;equals , &nbsp;the &nbsp;remainders &nbsp;are &nbsp;also &nbsp;equal.</p>\n\n<p>Things &nbsp;which &nbsp;coincide &nbsp;with &nbsp;one &nbsp;another &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;one &nbsp;another.</p>\n\n<p>Things &nbsp;which &nbsp;are &nbsp;double &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;things &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;one &nbsp;another.</p>\n\n<p>Things &nbsp;which &nbsp;are &nbsp;halves &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;things &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;one &nbsp;another.</p>\n\n<h2><strong>Euclid&#39;s &nbsp;postulates :</strong></h2>\n\n<h3><strong>Postulate - 1 :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>There &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;unique &nbsp;line &nbsp;that &nbsp;passes &nbsp;through &nbsp;the &nbsp;given &nbsp;two &nbsp;distinct &nbsp;points.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;Euclid&#39;s &nbsp;terms ,&quot; To &nbsp;draw &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;from &nbsp;any &nbsp;point &nbsp;to &nbsp;any &nbsp;point&quot;.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig5(1).png" style="height:79px; width:280px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Postulate - 2&nbsp;:</strong></p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;line &nbsp;segment &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;extended &nbsp;on &nbsp;either &nbsp;side &nbsp;to &nbsp;form &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;Euclid&#39;s &nbsp;terms ,&quot; To &nbsp;produce &nbsp;a &nbsp;finate &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;continuously &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line&quot;.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig6(1).png" style="height:85px; width:420px" /></p>\n\n<h3><strong>Postulate - 3&nbsp;:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;can &nbsp;describe &nbsp;a &nbsp;circle &nbsp;with &nbsp;any &nbsp;centre&nbsp; and &nbsp;radius.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Radii &nbsp;of &nbsp;four &nbsp;circles &nbsp;are &nbsp;given &nbsp;as &nbsp;3 cm , &nbsp;4 cm , &nbsp;4.5 cm &nbsp;and &nbsp;5 cm. &nbsp;Using &nbsp;a &nbsp;compass , &nbsp;draw &nbsp;circles &nbsp;with &nbsp;these &nbsp;radii &nbsp;taking &nbsp; P , Q , R &nbsp;and &nbsp;S &nbsp;as &nbsp;their &nbsp;centres.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig7(1).png" style="height:135px; width:300px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Postulate - 4&nbsp;:</strong></p>\n\n<p>All &nbsp;right &nbsp;angles &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;one &nbsp;another.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Postulate - 5&nbsp;:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;falling &nbsp;on &nbsp;two &nbsp;straight &nbsp;lines &nbsp;makes &nbsp;the &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;it &nbsp;taken &nbsp;together &nbsp;is &nbsp;less &nbsp;than &nbsp;two &nbsp;right &nbsp;angles , &nbsp;then &nbsp;the &nbsp;two &nbsp;straight &nbsp;lines , &nbsp;if &nbsp;produced &nbsp;infinitely , &nbsp;meet &nbsp;on &nbsp;that &nbsp;side &nbsp;which &nbsp;the &nbsp;sum &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;angles &nbsp;is &nbsp;less &nbsp;than &nbsp;two &nbsp;right &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n', 0, 0);
