(109, 'inline_html', '<h3><strong>Ray :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;ray &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;part &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;line. &nbsp;It &nbsp;begins &nbsp;at &nbsp;a &nbsp;point &nbsp;and &nbsp;goes &nbsp;on &nbsp;endlessly &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;specified &nbsp;direction.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig1(3).png" style="height:136px; width:380px" /><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Line segment :</strong></p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;part &nbsp;of &nbsp;line<strong>&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;with &nbsp;two &nbsp;end &nbsp;points &nbsp;is &nbsp;known &nbsp;as &nbsp;line &nbsp;segment.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig2(3).png" style="height:95px; width:270px" /></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.6em">We &nbsp;usually &nbsp;denote &nbsp;a &nbsp;line &nbsp;segment &nbsp;PQ &nbsp;by &nbsp;$ \\bar{PQ} $ &nbsp;and &nbsp;its &nbsp;length &nbsp;denoted &nbsp;by &nbsp;PQ.</span></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;Normally &nbsp;we &nbsp;use &nbsp;$\\overleftrightarrow{AB}$ , &nbsp;$\\overleftrightarrow{PQ}$ &nbsp;for &nbsp;lines &nbsp;and &nbsp;some &nbsp;times &nbsp;small &nbsp;letters &nbsp;l , m , n &nbsp;etc. &nbsp;will &nbsp;also &nbsp;be &nbsp;used &nbsp;to &nbsp;denote &nbsp;lines.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Line :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp; A &nbsp;line &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;extended &nbsp;endless &nbsp;on &nbsp;both &nbsp;directions.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig3(5).png" style="height:77px; width:300px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Collinear &nbsp;points :</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; If &nbsp;three &nbsp;or &nbsp;more &nbsp;points &nbsp;lie &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;line , &nbsp;they &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;collinear &nbsp;points , &nbsp;otherwise &nbsp;they &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;non - collinear &nbsp;points.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; A &nbsp;circle &nbsp;is &nbsp;divided &nbsp;into &nbsp;360 &nbsp;equal &nbsp;parts. &nbsp;The &nbsp;measure &nbsp;of &nbsp;each &nbsp;part &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;one &nbsp;degree.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Angle :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;The &nbsp;angle &nbsp;is &nbsp;formed &nbsp;by &nbsp;rotating &nbsp;a &nbsp;ray &nbsp;from &nbsp;an &nbsp;initial &nbsp;position &nbsp;to &nbsp;a &nbsp;terminal &nbsp;position.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig4(2).png" style="height:219px; width:310px" /></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.6em">One &nbsp;complete &nbsp;rotation &nbsp;gives &nbsp;$ 360^{0} $.</span></p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;rays &nbsp;making &nbsp;an &nbsp;angle &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;arms &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;angle &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;common &nbsp;point &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;vertex &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;angle.</p>\n\n<h2><strong>Types &nbsp;of &nbsp;Angles :</strong></h2>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;define &nbsp;angles &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;basis &nbsp;of &nbsp;their &nbsp;measure.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>1) Acute &nbsp;Angle :&nbsp;</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp;An &nbsp;angle &nbsp;whose &nbsp;measure &nbsp;less &nbsp;than &nbsp;$ 90^{0} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;acute &nbsp;angle.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig5(2).png" style="height:169px; width:180px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">2) Right &nbsp;Angle :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>An &nbsp;angle &nbsp;whose &nbsp;measure &nbsp;is &nbsp;$ 90^{0} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;a &nbsp;right &nbsp;angle.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig6(2).png" style="height:174px; width:170px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">3) Obtuse &nbsp;Angle :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>An &nbsp;angle &nbsp;whose &nbsp;measure &nbsp;is &nbsp;greater &nbsp;than &nbsp;$ 90^{0} $ &nbsp;and &nbsp;less &nbsp;than &nbsp;$ 180^{0} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;obtuse &nbsp;angle.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig7(2).png" style="height:197px; width:250px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">4) Straight &nbsp;Angle :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>An &nbsp;angle &nbsp;whose &nbsp;measure &nbsp;is<strong> &nbsp;</strong>$ 180^{0} $&nbsp;&nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;angle.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig8(1).png" style="height:80px; width:350px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">5) Reflex &nbsp;Angle :</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;An &nbsp;angle &nbsp;whose &nbsp;measure &nbsp;is &nbsp;greater &nbsp;than &nbsp;$ 180^{0} $ &nbsp;and &nbsp;less &nbsp;than &nbsp;$ 360^{0} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;reflex &nbsp;angle.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig9(1).png" style="height:189px; width:300px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">6) Complete &nbsp;Angle :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;An &nbsp;angle &nbsp;whose &nbsp;measure &nbsp;is<strong> &nbsp;</strong>$ 360^{0} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;complete &nbsp;angle.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig10.png" style="height:91px; width:350px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Concurrent &nbsp;Lines :</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;Three &nbsp;or &nbsp;more &nbsp;lines &nbsp;meet &nbsp;at &nbsp;a &nbsp;point , &nbsp;They &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;concurrent &nbsp;lines &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;point &nbsp;at &nbsp;which &nbsp;they &nbsp;meet &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;point &nbsp;of &nbsp;concurrence.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig11.png" style="height:238px; width:270px" /></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.6em">The &nbsp;complementary &nbsp;angle &nbsp;of &nbsp; $ x^{0} $&nbsp; &nbsp;is &nbsp;(&nbsp;$ 90^{0} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ x^{0} $ ).</span></p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;supplementary &nbsp;angle &nbsp;of &nbsp;&nbsp;$ x^{0} $ &nbsp; is &nbsp;(&nbsp;$ 180^{0} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ x^{0} $ ).</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;pair &nbsp;of &nbsp;angles , &nbsp;whose &nbsp;sum &nbsp;is &nbsp;$ 360^{0} $ &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;conjugate &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\n\n<h2><strong>Adjacent &nbsp;Angles :</strong></h2>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>Pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;angles &nbsp;which &nbsp;have &nbsp;a &nbsp;common &nbsp;vertex , &nbsp;a &nbsp;common &nbsp;arm &nbsp;and &nbsp;non &nbsp;common &nbsp;arms &nbsp;lie &nbsp;on &nbsp;either &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;common &nbsp;arm &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;adjacent &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig12.png" style="height:220px; width:400px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Linear &nbsp;pair &nbsp;of &nbsp;Angles :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>If &nbsp;the &nbsp;sum &nbsp;of &nbsp;two &nbsp;adjacent &nbsp;angles &nbsp;is &nbsp;$ 180^{0} $ , &nbsp;they &nbsp;are &nbsp;said &nbsp;to &nbsp;be &nbsp;a &nbsp;linear &nbsp;pair.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig13.png" style="height:172px; width:380px" /></p>\n\n<h3><strong>Parallel &nbsp;Lines :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>If &nbsp;two &nbsp;lines &nbsp;have &nbsp;no &nbsp;common &nbsp;points , &nbsp;they &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;lines.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig14.png" style="height:83px; width:220px" /></p>\n\n<h3><strong>Intersecting &nbsp;Lines :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;If &nbsp;two &nbsp;lines &nbsp;have &nbsp;a &nbsp;common &nbsp;point &nbsp;then &nbsp;they &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;intersecting &nbsp;lines.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig15.png" style="height:183px; width:240px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Linear &nbsp;pair &nbsp;of &nbsp;angles &nbsp;axiom :</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;If &nbsp;a &nbsp;ray &nbsp;stands &nbsp;on &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line , &nbsp;then &nbsp;the &nbsp;sum &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;two &nbsp;adjacent &nbsp;angles &nbsp;so &nbsp;formed &nbsp;is &nbsp;$ 180^{0} $.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Angle &nbsp;at &nbsp;a &nbsp;point :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;The &nbsp;sum &nbsp;of &nbsp;all &nbsp;the &nbsp;angles &nbsp;around &nbsp;a &nbsp;point &nbsp;is &nbsp;always &nbsp;$ 360^{0} $.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Angles &nbsp;in &nbsp;Intersecting &nbsp;Lines :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;a &nbsp;pair &nbsp;of &nbsp;lines &nbsp;meet &nbsp;at &nbsp;a &nbsp;point , &nbsp;they &nbsp;form &nbsp;four &nbsp;angles. &nbsp;The &nbsp;two &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;angles &nbsp;which &nbsp;have &nbsp;no &nbsp;common &nbsp;arm &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;vertically &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp;the &nbsp;figure $\\angle$a ,&nbsp;$\\angle$c &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$b , &nbsp;$\\angle$d &nbsp;are &nbsp;the &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;vertically &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;two &nbsp;lines &nbsp;intersect &nbsp;each &nbsp;other , &nbsp;then &nbsp;the &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;vertically &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;angles &nbsp;thus &nbsp;formed &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$a &nbsp;=&nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$c &nbsp; and &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$b &nbsp;=&nbsp;&nbsp; $\\angle$d</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Lines &nbsp;and &nbsp;a &nbsp;transversal :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>If &nbsp;a &nbsp;transversal &nbsp;meets &nbsp;two &nbsp;lines &nbsp;we &nbsp;get &nbsp;eight &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$\\angle$1 ,&nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$2 ,&nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$7 ,&nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$8 &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;exterior &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>$\\angle$3&nbsp;,&nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$4&nbsp;,&nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$5&nbsp; and&nbsp;&nbsp; $\\angle$6&nbsp; are &nbsp;called &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; The &nbsp;angles &nbsp;which &nbsp;are &nbsp;non - adjacent &nbsp;and &nbsp;lie &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;transversal &nbsp;of &nbsp;which &nbsp;one &nbsp;is &nbsp;interior &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;other &nbsp;is &nbsp;exterior , &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;From &nbsp;the &nbsp;figure</p>\n\n<p><strong>(a)</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; 1) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$1 &nbsp; and &nbsp;$\\angle$5</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$2&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$6</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;3) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$4&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$8&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;4) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$3&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$7 &nbsp; are &nbsp;4 &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p><strong>(b) &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>1) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$4&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$6</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2) &nbsp; $\\angle$3&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$5 &nbsp; are &nbsp;two &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;alternate &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p><strong>(c)</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;1) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$1 &nbsp; and &nbsp;$\\angle$7</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$2&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$8 &nbsp; are &nbsp;two &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;alternate &nbsp;exterior &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p><strong>(d) &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>1) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$4&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$5</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$3&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$6 &nbsp; are &nbsp;two &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp; same &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;transversal.</p>\n\n<p><strong>(e) &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>1) &nbsp;$\\angle$1 &nbsp; and &nbsp;$\\angle$8</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2) &nbsp;$\\angle$2&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$7 &nbsp;&nbsp;are &nbsp;two &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;&nbsp;same &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;transversal.</p>\n\n<p>Interior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;transversal &nbsp;are &nbsp;also &nbsp;referred &nbsp;to &nbsp;as &nbsp;consecutive &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;or &nbsp;Co&nbsp;- interior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;or &nbsp;allied &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>Exterior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;transversal &nbsp;are &nbsp;also &nbsp;referred &nbsp;to &nbsp;as &nbsp;consecutive &nbsp;exterior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;or &nbsp;Co&nbsp;- exterior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;or &nbsp;allied &nbsp;exterior &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;a &nbsp;pair &nbsp;of &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;lines &nbsp;intersected &nbsp;by &nbsp;a &nbsp;transversal &nbsp;the &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 1) &nbsp;Alternate &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 2) &nbsp;Corresponding &nbsp;angles</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 3) &nbsp;Alternate &nbsp;exterior &nbsp;angles &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;interior / exeterior&nbsp; &nbsp;angles &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;transversal &nbsp;are &nbsp;supplementary.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Lines &nbsp;which &nbsp;are &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;line &nbsp;are &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;each &nbsp;other.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;sum &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;is &nbsp;$ 180^{0} $.</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;a &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;is &nbsp;produced , &nbsp;then &nbsp;the &nbsp;exterior &nbsp;angle &nbsp;so &nbsp;formed &nbsp;is &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;sum &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;two &nbsp;interior &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>An &nbsp;exterior &nbsp;angle &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;is &nbsp;always &nbsp;greater &nbsp;than &nbsp;either &nbsp;of &nbsp;its &nbsp;interior &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Lines  and  Angles', '', '<h3><strong>Ray :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;ray &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;part &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;line. &nbsp;It &nbsp;begins &nbsp;at &nbsp;a &nbsp;point &nbsp;and &nbsp;goes &nbsp;on &nbsp;endlessly &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;specified &nbsp;direction.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig1(3).png" style="height:136px; width:380px" /><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Line segment :</strong></p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;part &nbsp;of &nbsp;line<strong>&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;with &nbsp;two &nbsp;end &nbsp;points &nbsp;is &nbsp;known &nbsp;as &nbsp;line &nbsp;segment.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig2(3).png" style="height:95px; width:270px" /></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.6em">We &nbsp;usually &nbsp;denote &nbsp;a &nbsp;line &nbsp;segment &nbsp;PQ &nbsp;by &nbsp;$ \\bar{PQ} $ &nbsp;and &nbsp;its &nbsp;length &nbsp;denoted &nbsp;by &nbsp;PQ.</span></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;Normally &nbsp;we &nbsp;use &nbsp;$\\overleftrightarrow{AB}$ , &nbsp;$\\overleftrightarrow{PQ}$ &nbsp;for &nbsp;lines &nbsp;and &nbsp;some &nbsp;times &nbsp;small &nbsp;letters &nbsp;l , m , n &nbsp;etc. &nbsp;will &nbsp;also &nbsp;be &nbsp;used &nbsp;to &nbsp;denote &nbsp;lines.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Line :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp; A &nbsp;line &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;extended &nbsp;endless &nbsp;on &nbsp;both &nbsp;directions.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig3(5).png" style="height:77px; width:300px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Collinear &nbsp;points :</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; If &nbsp;three &nbsp;or &nbsp;more &nbsp;points &nbsp;lie &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;line , &nbsp;they &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;collinear &nbsp;points , &nbsp;otherwise &nbsp;they &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;non - collinear &nbsp;points.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; A &nbsp;circle &nbsp;is &nbsp;divided &nbsp;into &nbsp;360 &nbsp;equal &nbsp;parts. &nbsp;The &nbsp;measure &nbsp;of &nbsp;each &nbsp;part &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;one &nbsp;degree.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Angle :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;The &nbsp;angle &nbsp;is &nbsp;formed &nbsp;by &nbsp;rotating &nbsp;a &nbsp;ray &nbsp;from &nbsp;an &nbsp;initial &nbsp;position &nbsp;to &nbsp;a &nbsp;terminal &nbsp;position.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig4(2).png" style="height:219px; width:310px" /></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.6em">One &nbsp;complete &nbsp;rotation &nbsp;gives &nbsp;$ 360^{0} $.</span></p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;rays &nbsp;making &nbsp;an &nbsp;angle &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;arms &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;angle &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;common &nbsp;point &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;vertex &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;angle.</p>\n\n<h2><strong>Types &nbsp;of &nbsp;Angles :</strong></h2>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;define &nbsp;angles &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;basis &nbsp;of &nbsp;their &nbsp;measure.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>1) Acute &nbsp;Angle :&nbsp;</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp;An &nbsp;angle &nbsp;whose &nbsp;measure &nbsp;less &nbsp;than &nbsp;$ 90^{0} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;acute &nbsp;angle.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig5(2).png" style="height:169px; width:180px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">2) Right &nbsp;Angle :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>An &nbsp;angle &nbsp;whose &nbsp;measure &nbsp;is &nbsp;$ 90^{0} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;a &nbsp;right &nbsp;angle.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig6(2).png" style="height:174px; width:170px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">3) Obtuse &nbsp;Angle :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>An &nbsp;angle &nbsp;whose &nbsp;measure &nbsp;is &nbsp;greater &nbsp;than &nbsp;$ 90^{0} $ &nbsp;and &nbsp;less &nbsp;than &nbsp;$ 180^{0} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;obtuse &nbsp;angle.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig7(2).png" style="height:197px; width:250px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">4) Straight &nbsp;Angle :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>An &nbsp;angle &nbsp;whose &nbsp;measure &nbsp;is<strong> &nbsp;</strong>$ 180^{0} $&nbsp;&nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;angle.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig8(1).png" style="height:80px; width:350px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">5) Reflex &nbsp;Angle :</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;An &nbsp;angle &nbsp;whose &nbsp;measure &nbsp;is &nbsp;greater &nbsp;than &nbsp;$ 180^{0} $ &nbsp;and &nbsp;less &nbsp;than &nbsp;$ 360^{0} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;reflex &nbsp;angle.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig9(1).png" style="height:189px; width:300px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">6) Complete &nbsp;Angle :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;An &nbsp;angle &nbsp;whose &nbsp;measure &nbsp;is<strong> &nbsp;</strong>$ 360^{0} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;complete &nbsp;angle.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig10.png" style="height:91px; width:350px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Concurrent &nbsp;Lines :</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;Three &nbsp;or &nbsp;more &nbsp;lines &nbsp;meet &nbsp;at &nbsp;a &nbsp;point , &nbsp;They &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;concurrent &nbsp;lines &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;point &nbsp;at &nbsp;which &nbsp;they &nbsp;meet &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;point &nbsp;of &nbsp;concurrence.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig11.png" style="height:238px; width:270px" /></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.6em">The &nbsp;complementary &nbsp;angle &nbsp;of &nbsp; $ x^{0} $&nbsp; &nbsp;is &nbsp;(&nbsp;$ 90^{0} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ x^{0} $ ).</span></p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;supplementary &nbsp;angle &nbsp;of &nbsp;&nbsp;$ x^{0} $ &nbsp; is &nbsp;(&nbsp;$ 180^{0} $ &nbsp;- &nbsp;$ x^{0} $ ).</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;pair &nbsp;of &nbsp;angles , &nbsp;whose &nbsp;sum &nbsp;is &nbsp;$ 360^{0} $ &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;conjugate &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\n\n<h2><strong>Adjacent &nbsp;Angles :</strong></h2>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>Pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;angles &nbsp;which &nbsp;have &nbsp;a &nbsp;common &nbsp;vertex , &nbsp;a &nbsp;common &nbsp;arm &nbsp;and &nbsp;non &nbsp;common &nbsp;arms &nbsp;lie &nbsp;on &nbsp;either &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;common &nbsp;arm &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;adjacent &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig12.png" style="height:220px; width:400px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Linear &nbsp;pair &nbsp;of &nbsp;Angles :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>If &nbsp;the &nbsp;sum &nbsp;of &nbsp;two &nbsp;adjacent &nbsp;angles &nbsp;is &nbsp;$ 180^{0} $ , &nbsp;they &nbsp;are &nbsp;said &nbsp;to &nbsp;be &nbsp;a &nbsp;linear &nbsp;pair.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig13.png" style="height:172px; width:380px" /></p>\n\n<h3><strong>Parallel &nbsp;Lines :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>If &nbsp;two &nbsp;lines &nbsp;have &nbsp;no &nbsp;common &nbsp;points , &nbsp;they &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;lines.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig14.png" style="height:83px; width:220px" /></p>\n\n<h3><strong>Intersecting &nbsp;Lines :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;If &nbsp;two &nbsp;lines &nbsp;have &nbsp;a &nbsp;common &nbsp;point &nbsp;then &nbsp;they &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;intersecting &nbsp;lines.</p>\n\n<p><img alt="" src="/ckfinder/userfiles/images/fig15.png" style="height:183px; width:240px" /></p>\n\n<p><strong style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.2em">Linear &nbsp;pair &nbsp;of &nbsp;angles &nbsp;axiom :</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;If &nbsp;a &nbsp;ray &nbsp;stands &nbsp;on &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line , &nbsp;then &nbsp;the &nbsp;sum &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;two &nbsp;adjacent &nbsp;angles &nbsp;so &nbsp;formed &nbsp;is &nbsp;$ 180^{0} $.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Angle &nbsp;at &nbsp;a &nbsp;point :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;The &nbsp;sum &nbsp;of &nbsp;all &nbsp;the &nbsp;angles &nbsp;around &nbsp;a &nbsp;point &nbsp;is &nbsp;always &nbsp;$ 360^{0} $.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Angles &nbsp;in &nbsp;Intersecting &nbsp;Lines :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;a &nbsp;pair &nbsp;of &nbsp;lines &nbsp;meet &nbsp;at &nbsp;a &nbsp;point , &nbsp;they &nbsp;form &nbsp;four &nbsp;angles. &nbsp;The &nbsp;two &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;angles &nbsp;which &nbsp;have &nbsp;no &nbsp;common &nbsp;arm &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;vertically &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>From &nbsp;the &nbsp;figure $\\angle$a ,&nbsp;$\\angle$c &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$b , &nbsp;$\\angle$d &nbsp;are &nbsp;the &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;vertically &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;two &nbsp;lines &nbsp;intersect &nbsp;each &nbsp;other , &nbsp;then &nbsp;the &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;vertically &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;angles &nbsp;thus &nbsp;formed &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$a &nbsp;=&nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$c &nbsp; and &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$b &nbsp;=&nbsp;&nbsp; $\\angle$d</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Lines &nbsp;and &nbsp;a &nbsp;transversal :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>If &nbsp;a &nbsp;transversal &nbsp;meets &nbsp;two &nbsp;lines &nbsp;we &nbsp;get &nbsp;eight &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$\\angle$1 ,&nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$2 ,&nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$7 ,&nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$8 &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;exterior &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>$\\angle$3&nbsp;,&nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$4&nbsp;,&nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$5&nbsp; and&nbsp;&nbsp; $\\angle$6&nbsp; are &nbsp;called &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; The &nbsp;angles &nbsp;which &nbsp;are &nbsp;non - adjacent &nbsp;and &nbsp;lie &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;transversal &nbsp;of &nbsp;which &nbsp;one &nbsp;is &nbsp;interior &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;other &nbsp;is &nbsp;exterior , &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;From &nbsp;the &nbsp;figure</p>\n\n<p><strong>(a)</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; 1) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$1 &nbsp; and &nbsp;$\\angle$5</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$2&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$6</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;3) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$4&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$8&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;4) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$3&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$7 &nbsp; are &nbsp;4 &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p><strong>(b) &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>1) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$4&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$6</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2) &nbsp; $\\angle$3&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$5 &nbsp; are &nbsp;two &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;alternate &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p><strong>(c)</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;1) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$1 &nbsp; and &nbsp;$\\angle$7</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$2&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$8 &nbsp; are &nbsp;two &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;alternate &nbsp;exterior &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p><strong>(d) &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>1) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$4&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$5</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2) &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$3&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$6 &nbsp; are &nbsp;two &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp; same &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;transversal.</p>\n\n<p><strong>(e) &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>1) &nbsp;$\\angle$1 &nbsp; and &nbsp;$\\angle$8</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2) &nbsp;$\\angle$2&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;$\\angle$7 &nbsp;&nbsp;are &nbsp;two &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;&nbsp;same &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;transversal.</p>\n\n<p>Interior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;transversal &nbsp;are &nbsp;also &nbsp;referred &nbsp;to &nbsp;as &nbsp;consecutive &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;or &nbsp;Co&nbsp;- interior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;or &nbsp;allied &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>Exterior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;transversal &nbsp;are &nbsp;also &nbsp;referred &nbsp;to &nbsp;as &nbsp;consecutive &nbsp;exterior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;or &nbsp;Co&nbsp;- exterior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;or &nbsp;allied &nbsp;exterior &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>When &nbsp;a &nbsp;pair &nbsp;of &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;lines &nbsp;intersected &nbsp;by &nbsp;a &nbsp;transversal &nbsp;the &nbsp;pairs &nbsp;of</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 1) &nbsp;Alternate &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 2) &nbsp;Corresponding &nbsp;angles</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 3) &nbsp;Alternate &nbsp;exterior &nbsp;angles &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;interior / exeterior&nbsp; &nbsp;angles &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;transversal &nbsp;are &nbsp;supplementary.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Lines &nbsp;which &nbsp;are &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;line &nbsp;are &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;each &nbsp;other.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;sum &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;is &nbsp;$ 180^{0} $.</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;a &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;is &nbsp;produced , &nbsp;then &nbsp;the &nbsp;exterior &nbsp;angle &nbsp;so &nbsp;formed &nbsp;is &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;sum &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;two &nbsp;interior &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>An &nbsp;exterior &nbsp;angle &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;is &nbsp;always &nbsp;greater &nbsp;than &nbsp;either &nbsp;of &nbsp;its &nbsp;interior &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 0, 0),
(110, 'inline_html', '<p>Rene &nbsp;Decartes , &nbsp;a &nbsp;French &nbsp;mathematician &nbsp;has &nbsp;developed &nbsp;the &nbsp;study &nbsp;of &nbsp; co-ordinate &nbsp;Geometry.</p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;need &nbsp;two &nbsp;references &nbsp;to &nbsp;locate &nbsp;the &nbsp;exact &nbsp;position &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;point &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;plane.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Cartesian &nbsp;system :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;A &nbsp;point &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;plane &nbsp;is &nbsp;located &nbsp;with &nbsp;the &nbsp;help &nbsp;of &nbsp;two &nbsp;perpendicular &nbsp;lines.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;horizontal &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;X - axis.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;vertical &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;Y - axis.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;point &nbsp;of &nbsp;intersection &nbsp;of &nbsp;both &nbsp;the &nbsp;axes &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;origin. &nbsp;It &nbsp;is &nbsp;denoted &nbsp;by &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; O ( 0 , 0 ).</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;positive &nbsp;numbers &nbsp;lie &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;directions &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\overrightarrow{OX}&nbsp;$, &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;positive &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;X - axis. &nbsp;similarly &nbsp;$&nbsp;\\overrightarrow{OY}&nbsp;$ &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;positive &nbsp;y - axis &nbsp;respectively. &nbsp;OX&nbsp;&#39; &nbsp;and &nbsp;OY &#39; &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;negative &nbsp;directions &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;X - axis &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;Y - axis &nbsp;respectively.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;axes &nbsp;divide &nbsp;the &nbsp;plane &nbsp;into &nbsp;four &nbsp;parts. &nbsp;These &nbsp;four &nbsp;parts &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;quadrants &nbsp;and &nbsp;are &nbsp;denoted &nbsp;by &nbsp;$ Q_{1} $, &nbsp;$ Q_{2} $, &nbsp;$ Q_{3} $ and &nbsp;$ Q_{4} $ &nbsp;in &nbsp;anti &nbsp;clockwise &nbsp;direction. &nbsp;The &nbsp;plane &nbsp;here &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;cartesian &nbsp;plane &nbsp;or &nbsp;co-ordinate &nbsp;plane &nbsp;or &nbsp;XY - plane. &nbsp;These &nbsp;axes &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;co-ordinate &nbsp;axes.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;distance &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;point &nbsp;from &nbsp;Y - axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;x - coordinate &nbsp;or &nbsp;abscissa.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;distance &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;point &nbsp;from &nbsp;X - axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;Y - &nbsp;coordinate &nbsp;or &nbsp;ordinate.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Origin :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;intersecting &nbsp;point &nbsp;of<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>x - axis &nbsp;and &nbsp;y - axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;origin. &nbsp;We &nbsp;take &nbsp;origin &nbsp;as &nbsp;reference &nbsp;point &nbsp;to &nbsp;locate &nbsp;other &nbsp;points &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;plane.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Signs &nbsp;of &nbsp;co-ordinates &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;point :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;first &nbsp;quadrant (&nbsp;$ Q_{1} $ ) &nbsp;all &nbsp;the &nbsp;points &nbsp;are &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;form &nbsp;of &nbsp; ( + x ,&nbsp;&nbsp;+ y).</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;the &nbsp;second&nbsp; quadrant (&nbsp;$ Q_{2} $ ) &nbsp;all &nbsp;the &nbsp;points &nbsp;are &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;form &nbsp;of &nbsp; ( -&nbsp;x ,&nbsp;&nbsp;+ y).</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;the &nbsp;third&nbsp; quadrant (&nbsp;$ Q_{3} $ ) &nbsp;all &nbsp;the &nbsp;points &nbsp;are &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;form &nbsp;of &nbsp; ( -&nbsp;x , &nbsp;-&nbsp;y).</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;the &nbsp;fourth&nbsp; quadrant (&nbsp;$ Q_{4} $ ) &nbsp;all &nbsp;the &nbsp;points &nbsp;are &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;form &nbsp;of &nbsp; ( +&nbsp;x , &nbsp;-&nbsp;y).</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Equation &nbsp;of &nbsp;X - axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;Y&nbsp; = &nbsp;0.</p>\n\n<p>Equation &nbsp;of &nbsp;Y&nbsp;- axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;X&nbsp; = &nbsp;0.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;x - coordinate &nbsp;of &nbsp;a point &nbsp;on &nbsp;y&nbsp;-&nbsp;axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;zero.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;y&nbsp;- coordinate &nbsp;of &nbsp;a point &nbsp;on &nbsp;x -&nbsp;axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;zero.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;ordered &nbsp;pair &nbsp;( x , y ) &nbsp;is &nbsp;different &nbsp;from &nbsp;the &nbsp;ordered &nbsp;pair &nbsp;( y&nbsp;, x&nbsp;).</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Distance &nbsp;between &nbsp;two &nbsp;points :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Distance &nbsp;between &nbsp;two &nbsp;points &nbsp; A&nbsp;( $ x_{1} $ &nbsp;, $ y_{1} $ &nbsp;) &nbsp;and &nbsp; B &nbsp;(&nbsp;$ x_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;,&nbsp;$ y_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;)&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; =$ \\sqrt{&nbsp;(x_{2} -x_{1})^{2} + (y_{2} -y_{1})^{2}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Mid &nbsp;point :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;A&nbsp;( $ x_{1} $ &nbsp;, $ y_{1} $ &nbsp;) &nbsp;and &nbsp; B &nbsp;(&nbsp;$ x_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;,&nbsp;$ y_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;) &nbsp; are &nbsp;any &nbsp;two &nbsp;points , &nbsp;then &nbsp;the &nbsp;mid &nbsp;point &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;segment &nbsp;joining &nbsp;AB &nbsp;is</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;($ \\frac{x_{1}+x_{2}}{2} $ , &nbsp;$ \\frac{y_{1}+y_{2}}{2} $)</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Collinear &nbsp;points :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp; If &nbsp;a set &nbsp;of &nbsp;points &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;plane &nbsp;lie &nbsp;on &nbsp;a &nbsp;given &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line , &nbsp;then &nbsp;those &nbsp;points &nbsp;are &nbsp;said &nbsp;to &nbsp;be &nbsp;collinear.</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp; AB + BC &nbsp;= &nbsp;AC , &nbsp;then &nbsp;A , B , C &nbsp; are &nbsp;collinear.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Division &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;line &nbsp;segment &nbsp;internally &nbsp;&amp; &nbsp;externally :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;coordinates &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;point &nbsp;R ( x , y ) which &nbsp;divides &nbsp;the &nbsp;line &nbsp;segment &nbsp;joining &nbsp;P&nbsp;( $ x_{1} $ &nbsp;, $ y_{1} $ &nbsp;) &nbsp;and &nbsp; Q&nbsp; (&nbsp;$ x_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;,&nbsp;$ y_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;) &nbsp;internally &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;given &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;m : n &nbsp;( m + n&nbsp;$ \\neq $ &nbsp;0 ) &nbsp;is</p>\n\n<p>R ( x , y ) &nbsp;= &nbsp;($ \\frac{mx_{2}+nx_{1}}{m+n} $ , &nbsp;$ \\frac{my_{2}+ny_{1}}{m+n} $)</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;coordinates &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;point &nbsp;R ( x , y ) which &nbsp;divides &nbsp;the &nbsp;line &nbsp;segment &nbsp;joining &nbsp;P&nbsp;( $ x_{1} $ &nbsp;, $ y_{1} $ &nbsp;) &nbsp;and &nbsp; Q&nbsp; (&nbsp;$ x_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;,&nbsp;$ y_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;) &nbsp;externally &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;given &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;m : n &nbsp;( m -&nbsp;n&nbsp;$ \\neq $ &nbsp;0 ) &nbsp;is</p>\n\n<p>R ( x , y ) &nbsp;= &nbsp;($ \\frac{mx_{2}-nx_{1}}{m-n} $ , &nbsp;$ \\frac{my_{2}-ny_{1}}{m-n} $)</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;points &nbsp;which &nbsp;divide &nbsp;$ \\bar{PQ} $ &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;of &nbsp;1 : 2 &nbsp;or &nbsp; 2 : 1 &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;points &nbsp;of &nbsp;trisection.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Centroid :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp; If &nbsp;the &nbsp;vertices &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;are &nbsp;A&nbsp;( $ x_{1} $ &nbsp;, &nbsp;$ y_{1} $ &nbsp;) ,&nbsp; B&nbsp; (&nbsp;$ x_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;, &nbsp;$ y_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;) &nbsp;and &nbsp; C&nbsp;( $ x_{3} $ &nbsp;, &nbsp;$ y_{3} $ &nbsp;) &nbsp;then &nbsp;the &nbsp;centroid &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;is</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; G ( x , y ) &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;($ \\frac{x_{1}+x_{2}+x_{3}}{3} $ , &nbsp;$ \\frac{y_{1}+y_{2}+y_{3}}{3} $)</p>\n\n<p><strong>Defination :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>The &nbsp;point &nbsp;where &nbsp;the &nbsp;three &nbsp;medians &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;meet &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;centroid &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;triangle.</p>\n\n<p>Centroid ( G ) &nbsp;divides &nbsp;the &nbsp;median &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;2 : 1</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Inclination &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;line :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>The &nbsp;angle &nbsp;made &nbsp;by &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;with &nbsp;positive &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;x - axis &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;anticlockwise &nbsp;direction &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;its &nbsp;inclination.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Slope &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;line (m) :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;The &nbsp;tangent &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;angle &nbsp;&#39;&nbsp;$ \\theta $ &#39; &nbsp;made &nbsp;by &nbsp;the &nbsp;line &nbsp;with &nbsp;the &nbsp;positive &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;x - axis.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;m &nbsp;= Tan$ \\theta $</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;slope &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;vertical &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;undefined.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;slope &nbsp;of &nbsp;horizontal &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;zero.</p>\n\n<p>For &nbsp;every &nbsp;m $\\epsilon$ R , y &nbsp;= &nbsp;mx &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;line &nbsp;with &nbsp;slope &nbsp;m &nbsp;and &nbsp;passing &nbsp;through &nbsp;the &nbsp;origin.</p>\n\n<p>y &nbsp;= &nbsp;mx &nbsp;+ &nbsp;c &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;general &nbsp;form &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;equation &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;line &nbsp;with &nbsp;slope &nbsp;m.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;y &nbsp;= &nbsp;mx &nbsp;+ &nbsp;c &nbsp;cuts &nbsp;y - axis &nbsp;at &nbsp;( 0 , c )</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;terms &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;co-ordinates &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;points &nbsp;A&nbsp;( $ x_{1} $ &nbsp;, &nbsp;$ y_{1} $ &nbsp;) ,&nbsp; B&nbsp; (&nbsp;$ x_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;, &nbsp;$ y_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;) &nbsp; that &nbsp;lie &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line , &nbsp;the &nbsp;slope &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;line</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; m &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-&nbsp;x_{1}} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{difference &nbsp;of &nbsp;y &nbsp;co-ordinates}{difference &nbsp;of &nbsp;x&nbsp; co-ordinates} $</p>\n\n<p>Slope &nbsp;of &nbsp;any &nbsp;line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;x - axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;zero.</p>\n\n<p>Slope &nbsp;of &nbsp;a&nbsp; line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;y&nbsp;- axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;not &nbsp;defined.</p>\n\n<p>Two &nbsp;non-vertical &nbsp;lines &nbsp;are &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;if &nbsp;and &nbsp;only &nbsp;if &nbsp;their &nbsp;slopes &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; If &nbsp;$ L_{1} $ $||$&nbsp;$ L_{2} $ &nbsp;then &nbsp;$ m_{1} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ m_{2} $</p>\n\n<p>Two &nbsp;non-vertical &nbsp;lines &nbsp;are &nbsp;perpendicular &nbsp;to &nbsp;each &nbsp;other &nbsp;if &nbsp;and &nbsp;only &nbsp;if &nbsp;the &nbsp;product &nbsp;of &nbsp;their &nbsp;slopes &nbsp;is &nbsp;(- 1)</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;&nbsp;$ L_{1} $ _|_ &nbsp;$ L_{2} $ &nbsp;then&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;$ m_{1} $$ m_{2} $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;-1</p>\n', 'Co -  ordinate  Geometry', '', '<p>Rene &nbsp;Decartes , &nbsp;a &nbsp;French &nbsp;mathematician &nbsp;has &nbsp;developed &nbsp;the &nbsp;study &nbsp;of &nbsp; co-ordinate &nbsp;Geometry.</p>\n\n<p>We &nbsp;need &nbsp;two &nbsp;references &nbsp;to &nbsp;locate &nbsp;the &nbsp;exact &nbsp;position &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;point &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;plane.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Cartesian &nbsp;system :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;A &nbsp;point &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;plane &nbsp;is &nbsp;located &nbsp;with &nbsp;the &nbsp;help &nbsp;of &nbsp;two &nbsp;perpendicular &nbsp;lines.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;horizontal &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;X - axis.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;vertical &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;Y - axis.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;point &nbsp;of &nbsp;intersection &nbsp;of &nbsp;both &nbsp;the &nbsp;axes &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;origin. &nbsp;It &nbsp;is &nbsp;denoted &nbsp;by &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; O ( 0 , 0 ).</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;positive &nbsp;numbers &nbsp;lie &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;directions &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\overrightarrow{OX}&nbsp;$, &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;positive &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;X - axis. &nbsp;similarly &nbsp;$&nbsp;\\overrightarrow{OY}&nbsp;$ &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;positive &nbsp;y - axis &nbsp;respectively. &nbsp;OX&nbsp;&#39; &nbsp;and &nbsp;OY &#39; &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;negative &nbsp;directions &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;X - axis &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;Y - axis &nbsp;respectively.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;axes &nbsp;divide &nbsp;the &nbsp;plane &nbsp;into &nbsp;four &nbsp;parts. &nbsp;These &nbsp;four &nbsp;parts &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;quadrants &nbsp;and &nbsp;are &nbsp;denoted &nbsp;by &nbsp;$ Q_{1} $, &nbsp;$ Q_{2} $, &nbsp;$ Q_{3} $ and &nbsp;$ Q_{4} $ &nbsp;in &nbsp;anti &nbsp;clockwise &nbsp;direction. &nbsp;The &nbsp;plane &nbsp;here &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;cartesian &nbsp;plane &nbsp;or &nbsp;co-ordinate &nbsp;plane &nbsp;or &nbsp;XY - plane. &nbsp;These &nbsp;axes &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;co-ordinate &nbsp;axes.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;distance &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;point &nbsp;from &nbsp;Y - axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;x - coordinate &nbsp;or &nbsp;abscissa.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;distance &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;point &nbsp;from &nbsp;X - axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;Y - &nbsp;coordinate &nbsp;or &nbsp;ordinate.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Origin :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;intersecting &nbsp;point &nbsp;of<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>x - axis &nbsp;and &nbsp;y - axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;origin. &nbsp;We &nbsp;take &nbsp;origin &nbsp;as &nbsp;reference &nbsp;point &nbsp;to &nbsp;locate &nbsp;other &nbsp;points &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;plane.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Signs &nbsp;of &nbsp;co-ordinates &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;point :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;first &nbsp;quadrant (&nbsp;$ Q_{1} $ ) &nbsp;all &nbsp;the &nbsp;points &nbsp;are &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;form &nbsp;of &nbsp; ( + x ,&nbsp;&nbsp;+ y).</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;the &nbsp;second&nbsp; quadrant (&nbsp;$ Q_{2} $ ) &nbsp;all &nbsp;the &nbsp;points &nbsp;are &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;form &nbsp;of &nbsp; ( -&nbsp;x ,&nbsp;&nbsp;+ y).</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;the &nbsp;third&nbsp; quadrant (&nbsp;$ Q_{3} $ ) &nbsp;all &nbsp;the &nbsp;points &nbsp;are &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;form &nbsp;of &nbsp; ( -&nbsp;x , &nbsp;-&nbsp;y).</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;the &nbsp;fourth&nbsp; quadrant (&nbsp;$ Q_{4} $ ) &nbsp;all &nbsp;the &nbsp;points &nbsp;are &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;form &nbsp;of &nbsp; ( +&nbsp;x , &nbsp;-&nbsp;y).</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Equation &nbsp;of &nbsp;X - axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;Y&nbsp; = &nbsp;0.</p>\n\n<p>Equation &nbsp;of &nbsp;Y&nbsp;- axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;X&nbsp; = &nbsp;0.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;x - coordinate &nbsp;of &nbsp;a point &nbsp;on &nbsp;y&nbsp;-&nbsp;axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;zero.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;y&nbsp;- coordinate &nbsp;of &nbsp;a point &nbsp;on &nbsp;x -&nbsp;axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;zero.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;ordered &nbsp;pair &nbsp;( x , y ) &nbsp;is &nbsp;different &nbsp;from &nbsp;the &nbsp;ordered &nbsp;pair &nbsp;( y&nbsp;, x&nbsp;).</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Distance &nbsp;between &nbsp;two &nbsp;points :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Distance &nbsp;between &nbsp;two &nbsp;points &nbsp; A&nbsp;( $ x_{1} $ &nbsp;, $ y_{1} $ &nbsp;) &nbsp;and &nbsp; B &nbsp;(&nbsp;$ x_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;,&nbsp;$ y_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;)&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; =$ \\sqrt{&nbsp;(x_{2} -x_{1})^{2} + (y_{2} -y_{1})^{2}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Mid &nbsp;point :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;A&nbsp;( $ x_{1} $ &nbsp;, $ y_{1} $ &nbsp;) &nbsp;and &nbsp; B &nbsp;(&nbsp;$ x_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;,&nbsp;$ y_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;) &nbsp; are &nbsp;any &nbsp;two &nbsp;points , &nbsp;then &nbsp;the &nbsp;mid &nbsp;point &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;segment &nbsp;joining &nbsp;AB &nbsp;is</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;($ \\frac{x_{1}+x_{2}}{2} $ , &nbsp;$ \\frac{y_{1}+y_{2}}{2} $)</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Collinear &nbsp;points :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp; If &nbsp;a set &nbsp;of &nbsp;points &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;plane &nbsp;lie &nbsp;on &nbsp;a &nbsp;given &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line , &nbsp;then &nbsp;those &nbsp;points &nbsp;are &nbsp;said &nbsp;to &nbsp;be &nbsp;collinear.</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp; AB + BC &nbsp;= &nbsp;AC , &nbsp;then &nbsp;A , B , C &nbsp; are &nbsp;collinear.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Division &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;line &nbsp;segment &nbsp;internally &nbsp;&amp; &nbsp;externally :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;coordinates &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;point &nbsp;R ( x , y ) which &nbsp;divides &nbsp;the &nbsp;line &nbsp;segment &nbsp;joining &nbsp;P&nbsp;( $ x_{1} $ &nbsp;, $ y_{1} $ &nbsp;) &nbsp;and &nbsp; Q&nbsp; (&nbsp;$ x_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;,&nbsp;$ y_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;) &nbsp;internally &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;given &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;m : n &nbsp;( m + n&nbsp;$ \\neq $ &nbsp;0 ) &nbsp;is</p>\n\n<p>R ( x , y ) &nbsp;= &nbsp;($ \\frac{mx_{2}+nx_{1}}{m+n} $ , &nbsp;$ \\frac{my_{2}+ny_{1}}{m+n} $)</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;coordinates &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;point &nbsp;R ( x , y ) which &nbsp;divides &nbsp;the &nbsp;line &nbsp;segment &nbsp;joining &nbsp;P&nbsp;( $ x_{1} $ &nbsp;, $ y_{1} $ &nbsp;) &nbsp;and &nbsp; Q&nbsp; (&nbsp;$ x_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;,&nbsp;$ y_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;) &nbsp;externally &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;given &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;m : n &nbsp;( m -&nbsp;n&nbsp;$ \\neq $ &nbsp;0 ) &nbsp;is</p>\n\n<p>R ( x , y ) &nbsp;= &nbsp;($ \\frac{mx_{2}-nx_{1}}{m-n} $ , &nbsp;$ \\frac{my_{2}-ny_{1}}{m-n} $)</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;points &nbsp;which &nbsp;divide &nbsp;$ \\bar{PQ} $ &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;of &nbsp;1 : 2 &nbsp;or &nbsp; 2 : 1 &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;points &nbsp;of &nbsp;trisection.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Centroid :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp; If &nbsp;the &nbsp;vertices &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;are &nbsp;A&nbsp;( $ x_{1} $ &nbsp;, &nbsp;$ y_{1} $ &nbsp;) ,&nbsp; B&nbsp; (&nbsp;$ x_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;, &nbsp;$ y_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;) &nbsp;and &nbsp; C&nbsp;( $ x_{3} $ &nbsp;, &nbsp;$ y_{3} $ &nbsp;) &nbsp;then &nbsp;the &nbsp;centroid &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;is</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; G ( x , y ) &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;($ \\frac{x_{1}+x_{2}+x_{3}}{3} $ , &nbsp;$ \\frac{y_{1}+y_{2}+y_{3}}{3} $)</p>\n\n<p><strong>Defination :</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>The &nbsp;point &nbsp;where &nbsp;the &nbsp;three &nbsp;medians &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;meet &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;centroid &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;triangle.</p>\n\n<p>Centroid ( G ) &nbsp;divides &nbsp;the &nbsp;median &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;ratio &nbsp;2 : 1</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Inclination &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;line :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>The &nbsp;angle &nbsp;made &nbsp;by &nbsp;a &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;with &nbsp;positive &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;x - axis &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;anticlockwise &nbsp;direction &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;its &nbsp;inclination.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Slope &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;line (m) :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;The &nbsp;tangent &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;angle &nbsp;&#39;&nbsp;$ \\theta $ &#39; &nbsp;made &nbsp;by &nbsp;the &nbsp;line &nbsp;with &nbsp;the &nbsp;positive &nbsp;direction &nbsp;of &nbsp;x - axis.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;m &nbsp;= Tan$ \\theta $</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;slope &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;vertical &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;undefined.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;slope &nbsp;of &nbsp;horizontal &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;zero.</p>\n\n<p>For &nbsp;every &nbsp;m $\\epsilon$ R , y &nbsp;= &nbsp;mx &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;line &nbsp;with &nbsp;slope &nbsp;m &nbsp;and &nbsp;passing &nbsp;through &nbsp;the &nbsp;origin.</p>\n\n<p>y &nbsp;= &nbsp;mx &nbsp;+ &nbsp;c &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;general &nbsp;form &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;equation &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;line &nbsp;with &nbsp;slope &nbsp;m.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line &nbsp;y &nbsp;= &nbsp;mx &nbsp;+ &nbsp;c &nbsp;cuts &nbsp;y - axis &nbsp;at &nbsp;( 0 , c )</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;terms &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;co-ordinates &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;points &nbsp;A&nbsp;( $ x_{1} $ &nbsp;, &nbsp;$ y_{1} $ &nbsp;) ,&nbsp; B&nbsp; (&nbsp;$ x_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;, &nbsp;$ y_{2} $&nbsp;&nbsp;) &nbsp; that &nbsp;lie &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line , &nbsp;the &nbsp;slope &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;line</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; m &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-&nbsp;x_{1}} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{difference &nbsp;of &nbsp;y &nbsp;co-ordinates}{difference &nbsp;of &nbsp;x&nbsp; co-ordinates} $</p>\n\n<p>Slope &nbsp;of &nbsp;any &nbsp;line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;x - axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;zero.</p>\n\n<p>Slope &nbsp;of &nbsp;a&nbsp; line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;y&nbsp;- axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;not &nbsp;defined.</p>\n\n<p>Two &nbsp;non-vertical &nbsp;lines &nbsp;are &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;if &nbsp;and &nbsp;only &nbsp;if &nbsp;their &nbsp;slopes &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; If &nbsp;$ L_{1} $ $||$&nbsp;$ L_{2} $ &nbsp;then &nbsp;$ m_{1} $ &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ m_{2} $</p>\n\n<p>Two &nbsp;non-vertical &nbsp;lines &nbsp;are &nbsp;perpendicular &nbsp;to &nbsp;each &nbsp;other &nbsp;if &nbsp;and &nbsp;only &nbsp;if &nbsp;the &nbsp;product &nbsp;of &nbsp;their &nbsp;slopes &nbsp;is &nbsp;(- 1)</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;&nbsp;$ L_{1} $ _|_ &nbsp;$ L_{2} $ &nbsp;then&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;$ m_{1} $$ m_{2} $ &nbsp; = &nbsp;-1</p>\n', 0, 0);
