(111, 'inline_html', '<h3><strong>Variable :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;symbol &nbsp;which &nbsp;take &nbsp;various &nbsp;numerical &nbsp;values &nbsp;is &nbsp;known &nbsp;as &nbsp;a &nbsp;variable &nbsp;or &nbsp;literal.</p>\n\n<p>Ex : &nbsp;x , y , z &nbsp;etc.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Constant :&nbsp;</strong></h3>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;symbol &nbsp;having &nbsp;a &nbsp;fixed &nbsp;numerical &nbsp;value &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;a &nbsp;constant.</p>\n\n<p>Ex : &nbsp;2 , 7 , 12 , 100 &nbsp;etc.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Coefficient :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;the &nbsp;product &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;variable &nbsp;and &nbsp;a &nbsp;constant &nbsp;, &nbsp;each &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;coefficient &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;other.</p>\n\n<p>Ex : &nbsp;7x , - 5x &nbsp;etc.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Linear equation :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>An &nbsp;equation &nbsp;involving &nbsp;only &nbsp;linear &nbsp;polynomial &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;a &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation.</p>\n\n<p>Ex : &nbsp;2x - 7 &nbsp;= &nbsp;10</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Linear Equations in two Variables :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp; If &nbsp;a &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation &nbsp;has &nbsp;two &nbsp;variables &nbsp;then &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation &nbsp;in &nbsp;two &nbsp;variables.</p>\n\n<p>Ex : &nbsp;2x &nbsp;+ &nbsp;3y &nbsp;= &nbsp;5</p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp;is &nbsp;usually &nbsp;to &nbsp;denote &nbsp;the &nbsp;variables &nbsp;by &nbsp;&#39; x &#39; &nbsp;and &nbsp;&#39; y &#39;. But &nbsp;other &nbsp;letters &nbsp;may &nbsp;also &nbsp;be &nbsp;used.</p>\n\n<p>Ex : &nbsp;2p + q &nbsp;= &nbsp;3 , 7u - 5v &nbsp;= &nbsp;2 , $ \\frac{s}{3} $ - 5t &nbsp;= &nbsp;7 &nbsp;etc.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;general &nbsp;form &nbsp;of &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation &nbsp;in &nbsp;two &nbsp;variables &nbsp;x , y &nbsp;is &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;ax + by + c &nbsp;=&nbsp; 0&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Where &nbsp;a , b , c &nbsp;are &nbsp;real &nbsp;numbers , and &nbsp;a , b &nbsp;are &nbsp;not &nbsp;simultaneously &nbsp;zero.</p>\n\n<p>Linear &nbsp;equation &nbsp;in &nbsp;one &nbsp;variable &nbsp;has &nbsp;a &nbsp;unique &nbsp;solution.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Solution of a Linear Equations in two Variables :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Any &nbsp;pair &nbsp;of &nbsp;values &nbsp;of &nbsp;x &nbsp;and &nbsp;y &nbsp;which &nbsp;satisfy &nbsp;the &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation &nbsp;in &nbsp;two &nbsp;variables &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;its &nbsp;solution.</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;two &nbsp;variables &nbsp;has &nbsp;many &nbsp;solutions.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Note :</strong>&nbsp; An &nbsp;easy &nbsp;way &nbsp;of &nbsp;getting &nbsp;two &nbsp;solutions &nbsp;is &nbsp;put &nbsp;x &nbsp;= &nbsp;0 &nbsp;and &nbsp;get &nbsp;the &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;value &nbsp;of &nbsp;y. &nbsp;Similarly &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;put &nbsp;y &nbsp;= &nbsp;0 &nbsp;and &nbsp;obtain &nbsp;the &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;value &nbsp;of &nbsp;x.</p>\n\n<p>Every &nbsp;solution &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation &nbsp;represents &nbsp;a &nbsp;point &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;line &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;equation.</p>\n\n<p>Every &nbsp;point &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;solution &nbsp;of &nbsp; the &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation.</p>\n\n<p>Any &nbsp;point &nbsp;that &nbsp;does &nbsp;not &nbsp;lie &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;not &nbsp;a &nbsp;solution &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;equation &nbsp;and &nbsp;vice &nbsp;versa.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;collection &nbsp;of &nbsp;points &nbsp;that &nbsp;give &nbsp;the &nbsp;solution &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;graph &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Steps to draw the graph of a linear equation :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>a)</strong> &nbsp;Write &nbsp;the &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation</p>\n\n<p><strong>b)</strong> &nbsp;Put &nbsp;x &nbsp;= &nbsp;0 &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;given &nbsp;equation &nbsp;and &nbsp;find &nbsp;the &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;value &nbsp;of &nbsp;y.</p>\n\n<p><strong>c)</strong> &nbsp;Put &nbsp;y &nbsp;= &nbsp;0&nbsp;&nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;given &nbsp;equation &nbsp;and &nbsp;find &nbsp;the &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;value &nbsp;of &nbsp;x.</p>\n\n<p><strong>d)</strong> &nbsp;Write &nbsp;the &nbsp;values &nbsp;of &nbsp;x &nbsp;and &nbsp;its &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;value &nbsp;of &nbsp;y &nbsp;as &nbsp;coordinates &nbsp;x &nbsp;and &nbsp;y &nbsp;respectively &nbsp;as &nbsp;( x , y ) &nbsp;form.</p>\n\n<p><strong>e)</strong> &nbsp;Plot &nbsp;the points &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;graph &nbsp;paper.</p>\n\n<p><strong>f)</strong> &nbsp;Join &nbsp;these &nbsp;points.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Equation of lines parallel to x-axis and y-axis :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;graph &nbsp;of &nbsp;x &nbsp;= k &nbsp;is &nbsp;line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;y - axis &nbsp;at &nbsp;a &nbsp;distance &nbsp;of &nbsp;k &nbsp;units &nbsp;and &nbsp;passing &nbsp;through &nbsp;the &nbsp;point &nbsp;( k , 0 ).</p>\n\n<p>​The &nbsp;graph &nbsp;of &nbsp;y&nbsp; = k &nbsp;is &nbsp;line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;x&nbsp;- axis &nbsp;at &nbsp;a &nbsp;distance &nbsp;of &nbsp;k &nbsp;units &nbsp;and &nbsp;passing &nbsp;through &nbsp;the &nbsp;point &nbsp;( 0&nbsp;, k&nbsp;).</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Equation of the x-axis and the y-axis :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Equation &nbsp;of &nbsp;x - axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;y &nbsp;= &nbsp;0</p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>Equation &nbsp;of &nbsp;y&nbsp;- axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;x&nbsp; = &nbsp;0.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Linear  Equations  in  Two  Variables', '', '<h3><strong>Variable :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;symbol &nbsp;which &nbsp;take &nbsp;various &nbsp;numerical &nbsp;values &nbsp;is &nbsp;known &nbsp;as &nbsp;a &nbsp;variable &nbsp;or &nbsp;literal.</p>\n\n<p>Ex : &nbsp;x , y , z &nbsp;etc.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Constant :&nbsp;</strong></h3>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;symbol &nbsp;having &nbsp;a &nbsp;fixed &nbsp;numerical &nbsp;value &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;a &nbsp;constant.</p>\n\n<p>Ex : &nbsp;2 , 7 , 12 , 100 &nbsp;etc.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Coefficient :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;the &nbsp;product &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;variable &nbsp;and &nbsp;a &nbsp;constant &nbsp;, &nbsp;each &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;the &nbsp;coefficient &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;other.</p>\n\n<p>Ex : &nbsp;7x , - 5x &nbsp;etc.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Linear equation :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>An &nbsp;equation &nbsp;involving &nbsp;only &nbsp;linear &nbsp;polynomial &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;a &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation.</p>\n\n<p>Ex : &nbsp;2x - 7 &nbsp;= &nbsp;10</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Linear Equations in two Variables :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp; If &nbsp;a &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation &nbsp;has &nbsp;two &nbsp;variables &nbsp;then &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation &nbsp;in &nbsp;two &nbsp;variables.</p>\n\n<p>Ex : &nbsp;2x &nbsp;+ &nbsp;3y &nbsp;= &nbsp;5</p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp;is &nbsp;usually &nbsp;to &nbsp;denote &nbsp;the &nbsp;variables &nbsp;by &nbsp;&#39; x &#39; &nbsp;and &nbsp;&#39; y &#39;. But &nbsp;other &nbsp;letters &nbsp;may &nbsp;also &nbsp;be &nbsp;used.</p>\n\n<p>Ex : &nbsp;2p + q &nbsp;= &nbsp;3 , 7u - 5v &nbsp;= &nbsp;2 , $ \\frac{s}{3} $ - 5t &nbsp;= &nbsp;7 &nbsp;etc.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;general &nbsp;form &nbsp;of &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation &nbsp;in &nbsp;two &nbsp;variables &nbsp;x , y &nbsp;is &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;ax + by + c &nbsp;=&nbsp; 0&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Where &nbsp;a , b , c &nbsp;are &nbsp;real &nbsp;numbers , and &nbsp;a , b &nbsp;are &nbsp;not &nbsp;simultaneously &nbsp;zero.</p>\n\n<p>Linear &nbsp;equation &nbsp;in &nbsp;one &nbsp;variable &nbsp;has &nbsp;a &nbsp;unique &nbsp;solution.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Solution of a Linear Equations in two Variables :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Any &nbsp;pair &nbsp;of &nbsp;values &nbsp;of &nbsp;x &nbsp;and &nbsp;y &nbsp;which &nbsp;satisfy &nbsp;the &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation &nbsp;in &nbsp;two &nbsp;variables &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;its &nbsp;solution.</p>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;two &nbsp;variables &nbsp;has &nbsp;many &nbsp;solutions.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Note :</strong>&nbsp; An &nbsp;easy &nbsp;way &nbsp;of &nbsp;getting &nbsp;two &nbsp;solutions &nbsp;is &nbsp;put &nbsp;x &nbsp;= &nbsp;0 &nbsp;and &nbsp;get &nbsp;the &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;value &nbsp;of &nbsp;y. &nbsp;Similarly &nbsp;we &nbsp;can &nbsp;put &nbsp;y &nbsp;= &nbsp;0 &nbsp;and &nbsp;obtain &nbsp;the &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;value &nbsp;of &nbsp;x.</p>\n\n<p>Every &nbsp;solution &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation &nbsp;represents &nbsp;a &nbsp;point &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;line &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;equation.</p>\n\n<p>Every &nbsp;point &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;solution &nbsp;of &nbsp; the &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation.</p>\n\n<p>Any &nbsp;point &nbsp;that &nbsp;does &nbsp;not &nbsp;lie &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;line &nbsp;is &nbsp;not &nbsp;a &nbsp;solution &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;equation &nbsp;and &nbsp;vice &nbsp;versa.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;collection &nbsp;of &nbsp;points &nbsp;that &nbsp;give &nbsp;the &nbsp;solution &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;graph &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Steps to draw the graph of a linear equation :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>a)</strong> &nbsp;Write &nbsp;the &nbsp;linear &nbsp;equation</p>\n\n<p><strong>b)</strong> &nbsp;Put &nbsp;x &nbsp;= &nbsp;0 &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;given &nbsp;equation &nbsp;and &nbsp;find &nbsp;the &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;value &nbsp;of &nbsp;y.</p>\n\n<p><strong>c)</strong> &nbsp;Put &nbsp;y &nbsp;= &nbsp;0&nbsp;&nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;given &nbsp;equation &nbsp;and &nbsp;find &nbsp;the &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;value &nbsp;of &nbsp;x.</p>\n\n<p><strong>d)</strong> &nbsp;Write &nbsp;the &nbsp;values &nbsp;of &nbsp;x &nbsp;and &nbsp;its &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;value &nbsp;of &nbsp;y &nbsp;as &nbsp;coordinates &nbsp;x &nbsp;and &nbsp;y &nbsp;respectively &nbsp;as &nbsp;( x , y ) &nbsp;form.</p>\n\n<p><strong>e)</strong> &nbsp;Plot &nbsp;the points &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;graph &nbsp;paper.</p>\n\n<p><strong>f)</strong> &nbsp;Join &nbsp;these &nbsp;points.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Equation of lines parallel to x-axis and y-axis :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;graph &nbsp;of &nbsp;x &nbsp;= k &nbsp;is &nbsp;line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;y - axis &nbsp;at &nbsp;a &nbsp;distance &nbsp;of &nbsp;k &nbsp;units &nbsp;and &nbsp;passing &nbsp;through &nbsp;the &nbsp;point &nbsp;( k , 0 ).</p>\n\n<p>​The &nbsp;graph &nbsp;of &nbsp;y&nbsp; = k &nbsp;is &nbsp;line &nbsp;parallel &nbsp;to &nbsp;x&nbsp;- axis &nbsp;at &nbsp;a &nbsp;distance &nbsp;of &nbsp;k &nbsp;units &nbsp;and &nbsp;passing &nbsp;through &nbsp;the &nbsp;point &nbsp;( 0&nbsp;, k&nbsp;).</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Equation of the x-axis and the y-axis :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Equation &nbsp;of &nbsp;x - axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;y &nbsp;= &nbsp;0</p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>Equation &nbsp;of &nbsp;y&nbsp;- axis &nbsp;is &nbsp;x&nbsp; = &nbsp;0.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 0, 0),
(112, 'inline_html', '<h3><strong>Triangle :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>A , B , C &nbsp;are &nbsp;the &nbsp;three &nbsp;non - collinear &nbsp;points. &nbsp;Join &nbsp;these &nbsp;three &nbsp;points &nbsp;by &nbsp;three &nbsp;line &nbsp;segments &nbsp;AB , BC , CA. &nbsp;We &nbsp;get &nbsp;a &nbsp;closed &nbsp;figure. It &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle.</p>\n\n<h1><strong>Kinds of triangle :</strong></h1>\n\n<p>Triangle &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;classified &nbsp;either &nbsp;according &nbsp;to &nbsp;their &nbsp;sides &nbsp;or &nbsp;according &nbsp;to &nbsp;their &nbsp;angles.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h2><strong>On the basis of Angles :</strong></h2>\n\n<h3><strong>Acute angled triangle :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>A &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;whose &nbsp;angles &nbsp;are &nbsp;all &nbsp;acute ( &lt;&nbsp;$ 90^{0} $ ) is &nbsp;called &nbsp;an &nbsp;acute &nbsp;angled &nbsp;triangle.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Right angled triangle :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;A &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;whose &nbsp;one &nbsp;angle &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;right &nbsp;angle ( =&nbsp;$ 90^{0} $ ) is &nbsp;called &nbsp; a &nbsp;right &nbsp;angled &nbsp;triangle.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Obtuse&nbsp;angled triangle :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;A &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;in &nbsp;which &nbsp;one &nbsp;angle &nbsp;is &nbsp;obtuse &nbsp;( &gt;&nbsp;$ 90^{0} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;obtuse &nbsp;angled &nbsp;triangle.</p>\n\n<h2><strong>On the basis of sides :</strong></h2>\n\n<h3><strong>Scalene triangle :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>A &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;whose &nbsp;three &nbsp;sides &nbsp;have &nbsp;different &nbsp;lengths &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;a &nbsp;scalene &nbsp;triangle.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Equilateral triangle :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>A &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;whose &nbsp;sides &nbsp;are &nbsp;all &nbsp;equal &nbsp;in &nbsp;length &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;an &nbsp;equilateral &nbsp;triangle.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Isosceles triangle :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;A &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;whose &nbsp;two &nbsp;sides &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;in &nbsp;length &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;an &nbsp;isosceles &nbsp;triangle.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Properties of triangle :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>1)</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;Sum &nbsp;of &nbsp;three &nbsp;angles &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;is &nbsp;$ 180^{0} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; In &nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ ABC , &nbsp;$\\angle$A +&nbsp;$\\angle$B +&nbsp;$\\angle$C &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ 180^{0} $</p>\n\n<p>2) &nbsp;The &nbsp;sum &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;lengths &nbsp;of &nbsp;any &nbsp;two &nbsp;sides &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;is &nbsp;greater than &nbsp;the &nbsp;length &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;third &nbsp;side.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;In &nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ ABC , &nbsp;AB + BC &nbsp;&gt; &nbsp;AC</p>\n\n<p>3) &nbsp;The &nbsp;difference &nbsp;between &nbsp;the &nbsp;length &nbsp;of &nbsp;any &nbsp;two &nbsp;sides &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;is &nbsp;smaller &nbsp;than &nbsp;the &nbsp;length &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;third &nbsp;side.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;| AB - AC | &nbsp;&lt; &nbsp;AC</p>\n\n<p>4) &nbsp;The &nbsp;exterior &nbsp;angle &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;is &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;sum &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;interior &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;In &nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ ABC , &nbsp;$\\angle$CBD &nbsp;= &nbsp;$\\angle$A &nbsp;+ &nbsp;$\\angle$C</p>\n\n<p>5) In &nbsp;any &nbsp;triangle , &nbsp;side &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;to &nbsp;greatest &nbsp;angle &nbsp;is &nbsp;largest &nbsp;and &nbsp;side &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;to &nbsp;smallest &nbsp;angles &nbsp;is &nbsp;smallest.</p>\n\n<p>6) &nbsp;Sides &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;to &nbsp;equal &nbsp;angles &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal.</p>\n\n<p>7) &nbsp;Angles &nbsp;opposite &nbsp;to &nbsp;equal &nbsp;sides &nbsp;of &nbsp;an &nbsp;isosceles &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Congruence :</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Figures &nbsp;which &nbsp;are &nbsp;identical.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;i.e. &nbsp;having &nbsp;some &nbsp;shape &nbsp;and &nbsp;size &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;congruent &nbsp;figures.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; The &nbsp;symbol &nbsp;used &nbsp;for &nbsp;congruence &nbsp;is &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\cong $</p>\n\n<p><strong>Note :</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;In &nbsp;general , &nbsp;sides &nbsp;decide &nbsp;sizes &nbsp;and &nbsp;angles &nbsp;decide &nbsp;shapes.</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;the &nbsp;lengths &nbsp;of &nbsp;two &nbsp;line &nbsp;segments &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;then &nbsp;they &nbsp;are &nbsp;congruent.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $\\overline{AB}$ &nbsp;$ \\cong $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\overline{CD}$</p>\n\n<p>Two &nbsp;angles &nbsp;are &nbsp;congruent , &nbsp;if &nbsp;their &nbsp;angle &nbsp;measure &nbsp;is &nbsp;same.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Squares &nbsp;that &nbsp;have &nbsp;sides &nbsp;with &nbsp;same &nbsp;measure &nbsp;are &nbsp;congruent &nbsp;and &nbsp;also &nbsp;with &nbsp;equal &nbsp;diagonals &nbsp;are &nbsp;congruent.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\square $ &nbsp;ABCD &nbsp;$ \\cong $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\square $ &nbsp;EFGH</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;two &nbsp;triangles &nbsp;are &nbsp;congruent &nbsp;then &nbsp;the &nbsp;sides &nbsp;and &nbsp;angles &nbsp;of &nbsp;one &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;sides &nbsp;and &nbsp;angles &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;other &nbsp;triangle.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;we &nbsp;trace &nbsp;these &nbsp;triangles &nbsp;from &nbsp;fig (ii) &nbsp;to &nbsp;(v) &nbsp;and &nbsp;try &nbsp;to &nbsp;cover &nbsp;$ \\bigtriangleup $ ABC. &nbsp;We &nbsp;would &nbsp;observe &nbsp;that &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;in &nbsp;fig (ii) , (iii) &nbsp;and &nbsp;(iv) &nbsp;are &nbsp;congruent &nbsp;to &nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ ABC &nbsp;while &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ TSV &nbsp;in &nbsp;fig (v) &nbsp;is &nbsp;not &nbsp;congruent &nbsp;to &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ &nbsp; ABC.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; If &nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ PQR &nbsp;is &nbsp;congruent &nbsp;to &nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ ABC , &nbsp;we &nbsp;write &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ PQR &nbsp;$ \\cong $ &nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ ABC.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Notice &nbsp;that &nbsp;when &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ PQR &nbsp;$ \\cong $ &nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ ABC , &nbsp;then &nbsp;sides &nbsp;of &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ PQR &nbsp;covers &nbsp;the &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;sides &nbsp;of &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ ABC &nbsp;equally &nbsp;and &nbsp;so &nbsp;do &nbsp;the &nbsp;angles.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; That &nbsp;is , &nbsp;PQ &nbsp;covers &nbsp;AB , QR &nbsp;covers &nbsp;BC &nbsp;and &nbsp;RP &nbsp;covers &nbsp;CA ; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$\\angle$P &nbsp;covers &nbsp;$\\angle$A ,&nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$Q&nbsp; covers &nbsp;$\\angle$B &nbsp;and &nbsp;&nbsp;$\\angle$R&nbsp; covers &nbsp;$\\angle$C. &nbsp;Also , &nbsp;there &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;one- one &nbsp;correspondence &nbsp;between &nbsp;the &nbsp;vertices. &nbsp;That &nbsp;is &nbsp;p &nbsp;corresponds &nbsp;to &nbsp;A , Q &nbsp;to &nbsp;B , R &nbsp;to &nbsp;C.</p>\n\n<p>This &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;written &nbsp;as</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; P $ \\leftrightarrow $ A , Q&nbsp;$ \\leftrightarrow $ B&nbsp;, R&nbsp;$ \\leftrightarrow $ C&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Note &nbsp;that &nbsp;under &nbsp;order &nbsp;of &nbsp;correspondence ,&nbsp;&nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ PQR &nbsp;$ \\cong $ &nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ ABC ; &nbsp;but &nbsp;it &nbsp;will not &nbsp;be &nbsp;correct &nbsp;to &nbsp;write&nbsp;&nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ QRP&nbsp; $ \\cong $ &nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ ABC &nbsp;as &nbsp;we &nbsp;get &nbsp;QR = AB , RP = BC and &nbsp;QP = AC &nbsp;which &nbsp;is &nbsp;incorrect &nbsp;for &nbsp;the &nbsp;given figures.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Similarly , &nbsp;for &nbsp;fig (iii)</p>\n\n<p>FD $ \\leftrightarrow $&nbsp;AB&nbsp;, &nbsp;DE $ \\leftrightarrow $&nbsp;BC &nbsp;and &nbsp;EF&nbsp;$ \\leftrightarrow $ CA</p>\n\n<p>and &nbsp;&nbsp;F&nbsp;$ \\leftrightarrow $&nbsp;A ,&nbsp;&nbsp;D&nbsp;$ \\leftrightarrow $&nbsp;B &nbsp;and &nbsp;E&nbsp;$ \\leftrightarrow $ C</p>\n\n<p>So ,&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>$\\bigtriangleup $ FDE&nbsp; $ \\cong $ &nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ ABC &nbsp;but</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; writing &nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ DEF&nbsp; $ \\cong $ &nbsp;$\\bigtriangleup $ ABC &nbsp;is &nbsp;not &nbsp;correct.</p>\n\n<p>So , &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;necessary &nbsp;to &nbsp;write &nbsp;the &nbsp;correspondence &nbsp;of &nbsp;vertices &nbsp;correctly &nbsp;for writing &nbsp;of &nbsp;congruence &nbsp;of &nbsp;triangles.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Note :&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;Corresponding &nbsp;parts &nbsp;of &nbsp;congruent &nbsp;triangles &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;and &nbsp;we &nbsp;write &nbsp;in &nbsp;short &nbsp;as &nbsp;&#39; CPCT &#39; for corresponding &nbsp;parts &nbsp;of &nbsp;congruent &nbsp;triangles.</p>\n\n<h2><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Congruence of triangle</strong></h2>\n\n<h3><strong>SAS congruence Rule :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>Two &nbsp;triangles &nbsp;are &nbsp;congruent &nbsp;if &nbsp;two &nbsp;sides &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;included &nbsp;angle &nbsp;of &nbsp;one &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;two &nbsp;sides &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;included &nbsp;angle &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;other &nbsp;triangle.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h3><strong>ASA congruence Rule :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>Two &nbsp;triangles &nbsp;are &nbsp;congruent , &nbsp;if &nbsp;two &nbsp;angles &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;inclined &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;one &nbsp;triangle &nbsp;are &nbsp;equal &nbsp;to &nbsp;two &nbsp;angles &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;included &nbsp;side &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;other &nbsp;triangle.</p>\