(114, 'inline_html', '<p>Newton &nbsp;proposed &nbsp;that &nbsp; moon &nbsp;is &nbsp;in &nbsp;a &nbsp;state &nbsp;of &nbsp;continuous &nbsp;free &nbsp;fall &nbsp;towards &nbsp;earth &nbsp;because &nbsp;of &nbsp;earth &nbsp;gravitational &nbsp;pull. Then &nbsp;why &nbsp;does &nbsp;not &nbsp;it &nbsp;fall ? &nbsp;Why &nbsp;does &nbsp;it &nbsp;revolve ?</p>\n\n<p>To &nbsp;understand &nbsp;it &nbsp;better, &nbsp;take &nbsp;a &nbsp;sling &nbsp;consisting &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;stone &nbsp;tied &nbsp;to &nbsp;a &nbsp;string. Revolve &nbsp;it &nbsp;around &nbsp;you &nbsp;with &nbsp;your &nbsp;hands. &nbsp;It &nbsp;describes &nbsp;a &nbsp;circular &nbsp;path. Now &nbsp;release &nbsp;the &nbsp;sling. &nbsp;Does &nbsp;it &nbsp;continue &nbsp;its &nbsp;circular &nbsp;motion ? No.</p>\n\n<p>It &nbsp;moves &nbsp;along &nbsp;a &nbsp;tangent &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;point &nbsp;where &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;released.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>This &nbsp;figure &nbsp;illustrates &nbsp;that &nbsp;wherever &nbsp;the &nbsp;sling &nbsp;is &nbsp;released &nbsp;it &nbsp;moves &nbsp;along &nbsp;the &nbsp;tangent. &nbsp;Before &nbsp;the &nbsp;sling &nbsp;is &nbsp;released, &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;acted &nbsp;upon &nbsp;by &nbsp;a &nbsp;force &nbsp;which &nbsp;keeps &nbsp;it &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;circular &nbsp;motion, &nbsp;which &nbsp;changes &nbsp;its &nbsp;direction &nbsp;continuously.</p>\n\n<p>This &nbsp;force &nbsp;obviously &nbsp; acts &nbsp;towards &nbsp;the &nbsp;center &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;circle &nbsp;along &nbsp;its &nbsp;radius. &nbsp;This &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;&#39;centre &nbsp;seeking&#39; &nbsp;force &nbsp;or &nbsp;centripetal &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;tension &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;sling &nbsp;represents &nbsp;the &nbsp;centre petal &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>Tension &nbsp;in &nbsp;sling &nbsp; &nbsp;$\\longleftrightarrow$ &nbsp;centripetal &nbsp;force&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;moment &nbsp;the &nbsp;sling &nbsp;is &nbsp;released, &nbsp;this &nbsp;force &nbsp;disappears &nbsp;and &nbsp;sling &nbsp;moves &nbsp;in &nbsp;straight &nbsp;line.</p>\n\n<p>This &nbsp;means &nbsp;in &nbsp;every &nbsp;circular &nbsp;motion, &nbsp;some &nbsp;force &nbsp;should &nbsp;act &nbsp;as &nbsp;centripetal &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>In &nbsp;case of &nbsp;moon &nbsp;around &nbsp;earth, &nbsp;gravitation &nbsp;force &nbsp;between &nbsp;the &nbsp;earth &nbsp;and &nbsp;moon &nbsp;serves &nbsp;as &nbsp;the &nbsp;centripetal &nbsp;force.</p>\n\n<p>Now, &nbsp;it &nbsp;should &nbsp;be &nbsp;clear &nbsp;to &nbsp;you &nbsp;that &nbsp;some &nbsp;gravitational &nbsp;force &nbsp;pulls &nbsp;all &nbsp;objects &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;earth &nbsp;towards &nbsp;its &nbsp;center &nbsp;and &nbsp;keeps &nbsp;the &nbsp;moon &nbsp;in &nbsp;its &nbsp;orbit &nbsp;around &nbsp;the &nbsp;earth.</p>\n\n<p>According &nbsp;to &nbsp;action - reaction &nbsp;theory &nbsp;of &nbsp;newton&#39;s &nbsp;3 rd &nbsp;law, &nbsp;moon &nbsp;should &nbsp;also &nbsp;exent &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;earth, &nbsp;every &nbsp;object &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;earth, &nbsp;for &nbsp;example &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball &nbsp;which &nbsp;you &nbsp;throw &nbsp;up, &nbsp;should &nbsp;also &nbsp;exent &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;force &nbsp;on &nbsp;the &nbsp;earth.</p>\n\n<p>Then &nbsp;why &nbsp;only &nbsp;ball falls &nbsp;on &nbsp;earth ? Why &nbsp;the &nbsp;earth &nbsp;doesn&#39;t &nbsp;move &nbsp;towards &nbsp;the &nbsp;ball &nbsp;instead ?</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;answer &nbsp;again &nbsp;is &nbsp;given &nbsp;by &nbsp;newton &nbsp;in &nbsp;is &nbsp;2 nd law &nbsp;of &nbsp;motion.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; F &nbsp;= &nbsp;m a &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;a &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{F}{m} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;a &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\alpha $ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{m} $</p>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;mass &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;earth &nbsp