(115, 'inline_html', '<h3><strong>According &nbsp;to this law :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>1.&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;Every &nbsp;object &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;universe &nbsp;attracts &nbsp;every &nbsp;other &nbsp;object &nbsp;with &nbsp;a &nbsp;force of &nbsp;attraction &nbsp;called &nbsp;gravitational &nbsp;force ( F )</p>\n\n<p><strong>2.&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;Gravitational &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;directly &nbsp;proportional &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;product &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;two &nbsp;masses (&nbsp;$ m_{1} $ &nbsp;and &nbsp;$ m_{2} $ )</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;F &nbsp;$\\propto$ &nbsp;$ m_{1} $&nbsp;$ m_{2} $ &nbsp;----------------------(1)</p>\n\n<p>More &nbsp;than &nbsp;two &nbsp;masses, &nbsp;more &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;gravitational &nbsp;force &nbsp;between &nbsp;them.</p>\n\n<p><strong>3. &nbsp;</strong>Gravitational &nbsp;force &nbsp;between &nbsp;any &nbsp;two &nbsp;objects &nbsp;is &nbsp;inversally &nbsp;proportional &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;square &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;distance( d ) &nbsp;between &nbsp;them.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;F &nbsp;$\\propto$ &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{d^{2}} $ -----------------(2)</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>More &nbsp;the &nbsp;distance, &nbsp;less &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;force &nbsp;and &nbsp;vice versa</p>\n\n<p>Combining &nbsp;equation &nbsp;(1) &nbsp;and &nbsp;(2) , &nbsp;Force &nbsp;of &nbsp;gravitation &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;given &nbsp;by</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;F &nbsp;$\\propto$ &nbsp;$ \\frac{m_{1} &nbsp; m_{2}}{d^{2}} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;F &nbsp;= &nbsp;$G \\frac{m_{1} &nbsp; m_{2}}{d^{2}} $ &nbsp;-------------------(3)</p>\n\n<p>Where &nbsp;G &nbsp;is &nbsp;constant &nbsp;of &nbsp;proportionality &nbsp;called &nbsp;universal &nbsp; gravitational &nbsp; constant. &nbsp;Why &nbsp;it &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;universal ?........... &nbsp;Because &nbsp;its &nbsp;value &nbsp;is &nbsp;same &nbsp;everywhere &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;universe.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Value &nbsp;of &nbsp;G.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Rearranging &nbsp;equation &nbsp;(3)</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; G &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{F&nbsp;d^{2}}{m_{1} &nbsp; m_{2}} $ ------------------ (4)</p>\n\n<p>If &nbsp;you &nbsp;substitute &nbsp;the &nbsp; S.I &nbsp;or &nbsp;C.G.S &nbsp;units &nbsp;of &nbsp;force, &nbsp;distance &nbsp;and mass &nbsp;in &nbsp;equation &nbsp;(4), &nbsp;you &nbsp;get &nbsp;corresponding &nbsp;&nbsp;S.I &nbsp;and&nbsp;&nbsp; C.G.S &nbsp;for &nbsp;G.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;S. I &nbsp;unit &nbsp;of &nbsp;G &nbsp;= &nbsp;$ \\frac{N &nbsp;m^{2}}{kg^{2}} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; = &nbsp;N &nbsp;$&nbsp;m^{2}&nbsp;kg^{-2}$</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; C.G.S &nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{dyne&nbsp; cm^{2}}{g^{2}} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; = &nbsp; dyne &nbsp;$&nbsp;cm^{2}g^{-2}$</p>\n\n<p>Through &nbsp;repeated &nbsp;experiments &nbsp;the &nbsp;value &nbsp;of &nbsp; G &nbsp;was &nbsp;finally &nbsp;found &nbsp;by &nbsp;Henry &nbsp;Caveadish &nbsp;using &nbsp;sensitive &nbsp;balance.</p>\n\n<p>To day &nbsp;the &nbsp;accepted &nbsp;value &nbsp;of &nbsp;G &nbsp;is &nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; G &nbsp;= &nbsp;6 . 673 * $10^{-11}$ N&nbsp;$&nbsp;m^{2}&nbsp;kg^{-2}$</p>\n\n<p>Any &nbsp;law, &nbsp;for &nbsp;force &nbsp;in &nbsp;which &nbsp;the &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;inversely &nbsp;proportional &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;square &nbsp;of &nbsp;distance &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp; Inverse &nbsp;square &nbsp;law.</p>\n\n<p>Universal &nbsp;law &nbsp;of &nbsp;gravitation &nbsp;is &nbsp;also &nbsp;the &nbsp;inverse &nbsp;square &nbsp;law</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;F &nbsp;$\\propto$ &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{d^{2}} $</p>\n\n<p>Let &#39;s &nbsp;say &nbsp;d &nbsp;is &nbsp;trippled ( 3 &nbsp;times ), &nbsp;The &nbsp;F &nbsp;becomes &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{9} $ &nbsp;times &nbsp;smaller &nbsp;and &nbsp;vice &nbsp;versa.</p>\n\n<p>Newton &nbsp;used &nbsp;3 &nbsp;laws &nbsp;of &nbsp;platenory &nbsp;motion &nbsp;given &nbsp;by &nbsp;Johaanes &nbsp;Kepler &nbsp;to &nbsp;arrive &nbsp;at &nbsp;inverse &nbsp;square &nbsp;law &nbsp;for &nbsp;gravitation. &nbsp;Hence &nbsp;it &nbsp;would &nbsp;definetely &nbsp;help &nbsp;to &nbsp;study &nbsp;them.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Universal  Law  of  Gravitation', '', '<h3><strong>According &nbsp;to this law :</strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>1.&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;Every &nbsp;object &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;universe &nbsp;attracts &nbsp;every &nbsp;other &nbsp;object &nbsp;with &nbsp;a &nbsp;force of &nbsp;attraction &nbsp;called &nbsp;gravitational &nbsp;force ( F )</p>\n\n<p><strong>2.&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;Gravitational &nbsp;force &nbsp;is &nbsp;directly &nbsp;proportional &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;product &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;two &nbsp;masses (&nbsp;$ m_{1} $ &nbsp;and &nbsp;$ m_{2} $ )</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;F &nbsp;$\\propto$ &nbsp;$ m_{1} $&nbsp;$ m_{2} $ &nbsp;----------------------(1)</p>\n\n<p>More &nbsp;than &nbsp;two &nbsp;masses, &nbsp;more &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;gravitational &nbsp;force &nbsp;between &nbsp;them.</p>\n\n<p><strong>3. &nbsp;</strong>Gravitational &nbsp;force &nbsp;between &nbsp;any &nbsp;two &nbsp;objects &nbsp;is &nbsp;inversally &nbsp;proportional &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;square &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;distance( d ) &nbsp;between &nbsp;them.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;F &nbsp;$\\propto$ &nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{d^{2}} $ -----------------(2)</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>More &nbsp;the &nbsp;distance, &nbsp;less &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;force &nbsp;and &nbsp;vice versa</p>\n\n<p>Combining &nbsp;equation &nbsp;(1) &nbsp;and &nbsp;(2) , &nbsp;Force &nbsp;of &nbsp;