(116, 'inline_html', '<p>These &nbsp;laws &nbsp;explain &nbsp;how &nbsp;planets &nbsp;revolve &nbsp;around &nbsp;the &nbsp;sun.</p>\n\n<p><strong>1.&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;All &nbsp;planets &nbsp;revolve &nbsp;in &nbsp;elliptical &nbsp;orbits &nbsp;and &nbsp;not &nbsp;in &nbsp;circular &nbsp;orbits &nbsp;as &nbsp;was &nbsp;assumed &nbsp;before.</p>\n\n<p>An &nbsp;ellipse &nbsp;has &nbsp;2 foci. Sun &nbsp;is &nbsp;always &nbsp;at &nbsp;one &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;foci &nbsp;vice versa&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;the &nbsp;planet.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>2.&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;The &nbsp;line &nbsp;joining &nbsp;the &nbsp;planet &nbsp;and &nbsp;the &nbsp;sun &nbsp;sweeps &nbsp;equal &nbsp;areas &nbsp;in &nbsp;equal &nbsp;intervals &nbsp;of &nbsp;time. This &nbsp;means &nbsp;the &nbsp;planet &nbsp;travel &nbsp;from &nbsp;A &nbsp;to &nbsp;B &nbsp;and &nbsp;C &nbsp;to &nbsp;D &nbsp;in &nbsp;same &nbsp;time.</p>\n\n<p>Area &nbsp;OAB &nbsp;= &nbsp;Area &nbsp;ODC.</p>\n\n<p><strong>3. &nbsp;</strong>The &nbsp;cube &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;mean &nbsp;distance ( r ) &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;planet &nbsp;from &nbsp;the &nbsp;sun &nbsp;is &nbsp;proportional &nbsp;to &nbsp;the &nbsp;square &nbsp;of &nbsp;its &nbsp;orbital &nbsp;time &nbsp;period ( T ). &nbsp;Time &nbsp;period &nbsp;is &nbsp;the &nbsp;time &nbsp;taken &nbsp;to &nbsp;complete &nbsp;one &nbsp;revolution &nbsp;around &nbsp;the &nbsp;sun.&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Kepler''s  laws  of  planetary  motion', '', '<p>These &nbsp;laws &nbsp;explain &nbsp;how &nbsp;planets &nbsp;revolve &nbsp;around &nbsp;the &nbsp;sun.</p>\n\n<p><strong>1.&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;All &nbsp;planets &nbsp;revolve &nbsp;in &nbsp;elliptical &nbsp;orbits &nbsp;and &nbsp;not &nbsp;in &nbsp;circular &nbsp;orbits &nbsp;as &nbsp;was &nbsp;assumed &nbsp;before.</p>\n\n<p>An &nbsp;ellipse &nbsp;has &nbsp;2 foci. Sun &nbsp;is &nbsp;always &nbsp;at &nbsp;one &nbsp;of &nbsp;the &nbsp;foci &nbsp;vice versa&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;the &nbsp;planet.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>