(129, 'inline_html', '<h3><strong>Fraction</strong></h3>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;fraction &nbsp;is considered &nbsp;as &nbsp;a &nbsp;part &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;whole, or &nbsp;generally any &nbsp;number of equal parts.</p>\n\n<p>A fraction can be&nbsp;expressed &nbsp;in &nbsp;the &nbsp;form &nbsp;of &nbsp;$ \\frac{p}{q} $ where p,q &isin; Z and q&nbsp;# 0.</p>\n\n<p>A fraction can also be expressed as decimals.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Example:&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{4} $&nbsp;= 0.25.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Decimal Fraction</strong>&nbsp;:</h3>\n\n<p>A fraction &nbsp;whose &nbsp;denominator &nbsp;is &nbsp;10, 100,1000 etc., &nbsp;is &nbsp;called decimal &nbsp; fraction.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Ex :&nbsp;$ \\frac{7}{10} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{7}{100} $ etc..</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Vulgar Fraction:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;fraction &nbsp;whose &nbsp;denominator &nbsp;is &nbsp;a &nbsp;natural &nbsp;number, other &nbsp;than 10, 100, 1000 etc., is called &nbsp;Vulgar &nbsp;fraction.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Proper Fraction:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>A fraction &nbsp;in &nbsp;which &nbsp;numerator &nbsp;is &nbsp;less &nbsp;than &nbsp;the &nbsp;denominator &nbsp;is &nbsp;called a proper fraction.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;Ex:&nbsp;$ \\frac{3}{7} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{4}{15} $ etc..</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Improper Fraction:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>A &nbsp;fraction &nbsp;in &nbsp;which &nbsp;numerator &nbsp;is &nbsp;greater &nbsp;than &nbsp;the denominator &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;an improper &nbsp;function.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Ex :&nbsp;$ \\frac{7}{3} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{8}{5} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{11}{7} $ etc .</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Mixed Fraction:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>An &nbsp;improper &nbsp;fraction &nbsp;can &nbsp;be &nbsp;written &nbsp;as &nbsp;a &nbsp;combination &nbsp;of &nbsp;a &nbsp;whole &nbsp;and &nbsp;a &nbsp;part&nbsp;such &nbsp;fractions &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;mixed &nbsp;fractions.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Ex : 2$ \\frac{1}{5} $ , 2$ \\frac{1}{3} $ etc..</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Equivalent Fraction:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Fractions &nbsp;that &nbsp;represent &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;part &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;equivalent fraction.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Ex :&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{2} $ and&nbsp;$ \\frac{2}{4} $ ;&nbsp;$ \\frac{2}{7} $ and&nbsp;$ \\frac{6}{21} $ etc.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Like&nbsp; Fractions</strong></h3>\n\n<p>The &nbsp;fractional &nbsp;numbers &nbsp;that &nbsp;have &nbsp;the &nbsp;same &nbsp;denominators &nbsp;are called &nbsp;like fractions.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Ex :&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{9} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{2}{9} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{4}{9} $ etc,.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Unlike Fractions</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Fractions &nbsp;that have &nbsp;different &nbsp;denominators &nbsp;are &nbsp;called &nbsp;unlike &nbsp;fractions .</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Ex :&nbsp;$ \\frac{4}{7} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\frac{3}{4} $ etc .</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Terminating Decimal</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Any &nbsp;fraction&nbsp;$ \\frac{p}{q} $ can &nbsp;be expressed &nbsp;as &nbsp;a &nbsp;decimal. If &nbsp;the &nbsp;decimal expression &nbsp;of &nbsp;$ \\frac{p}{q} $ terminates ., i.e. comes &nbsp;to &nbsp;an &nbsp;end , then &nbsp;the &nbsp;decimal to &nbsp;obtained &nbsp;is &nbsp;called &nbsp;a &nbsp;terminating &nbsp;decimal.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;Ex : 1)&nbsp;$ \\frac{3}{2} $ = 1.5&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2)$ \\frac{3}{4} $ = 0.75</p>\n\n<p><strong>Note&nbsp;</strong>: A &nbsp;fraction&nbsp;$ \\frac{p}{q} $ is &nbsp;a terminating &nbsp;decimal &nbsp;only, when &nbsp;prime &nbsp;factors of &nbsp;q are &nbsp;2 and &nbsp;5 only.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Recurring Decimals</strong></h3>\n\n<p>If in a decimal , a digit or a set of digits in the decimal part of is repeated continuously , then such a number is called a recurring or repeating decimal.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Ex : &nbsp;1)&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{3} $ = 0.33333............ &nbsp; &nbsp;= 0.$ \\bar{3} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2)$ \\frac{3}{11} $ = 0.272727......... &nbsp; &nbsp; =&nbsp;0.$ \\bar{27} $</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Non-Terminating Decimal:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>If a rational number in its lowest terms has prime factors other than 2 and 5 , the division does not end.During the process of division &nbsp;we get a digit or a group of digits repeated in some order.such decimal fractions are called non-terminating but recurring decimals.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Ex : &nbsp;1)$ \\frac{4}{9} $ = 0.444444........... = 0.$ \\bar{4} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2)$ \\frac{7}{15} $ = 0.4666666........ =&nbsp;0.4$ \\bar{6} $</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Types of Non-Terminating Repeating Decimals:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>&nbsp; 1)&nbsp;<strong>Pure Recurring Decimals</strong>&nbsp;:</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; A decimal number in which all the digits after the decimal&nbsp;point are repeated .</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Ex : 1)$ \\frac{3}{11} $ = 0.$ \\bar{27} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2)$ \\frac{1}{11} $ =&nbsp;0.$ \\bar{09} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;2)&nbsp;<strong>Mixed Recurring Decimals</strong>&nbsp;: A decimal number in which at least one digit after the decimal point is not repeated and others are repeated.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Ex :&nbsp;0.4$ \\bar{6} $ ,&nbsp;0.6$ \\bar{45} $ ,&nbsp;0.1$ \\bar{6} $</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Period:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>A digit or more than one digit being repeated in the same order , the recurring part is called the period.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Ex : 1)$ \\frac{1}{3} $ =&nbsp;0.$ \\bar{3} $ ,&nbsp;period = 3</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2)$ \\frac{7}{15} $ =&nbsp;0.4$ \\bar{6} $ &nbsp;, period = 6</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Periodicity:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>The number of digits in the recurring part is called the periodicity of the decimal.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Ex : &nbsp;1)$ \\frac{7}{15} $ = 0.4$ \\bar{6} $ , periodicity &nbsp;= 1</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2)$ \\frac{3}{11} $ = 0.$ \\bar{27} $ , periodicity &nbsp;= 2</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nb