(133, 'inline_html', '<h3><strong>Real Numbers:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>The collection of all rational and irrational numbers is called Real numbers.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Real numbers are denoted by R</p>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; R = Q&nbsp;$ \\bigcup $&nbsp;$ Q^{|} $ or Q&nbsp;$ \\bigcup $ S</div>\n', 'Real Numbers', '', '<h3><strong>Real Numbers:</strong></h3>\n\n<p>The collection of all rational and irrational numbers is called Real numbers.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Real numbers are denoted by R</p>\n\n<div class="content-formula">&nbsp; R = Q&nbsp;$ \\bigcup $&nbsp;$ Q^{|} $ or Q&nbsp;$ \\bigcup $ S</div>\n', 0, 0),
(134, 'inline_html', '<h3><strong>Rationalising Factor (R.F):</strong></h3>\n\n<p>If the product of two surds is a rational number then each of the two is the rationalising factor(R.F)of the other.</p>\n\n<pre>\n<em>Note: R.F. of a given surd is not unique.</em></pre>\n\n<p>R.F of&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ +$ \\sqrt{b} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ -&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $</p>\n\n<p>R.F of&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ -&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $</p>\n\n<p>R.F of &nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{a} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{b} $ &nbsp;is&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{&nbsp;a^{2} &nbsp;} $ -&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{ab} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{ b^{2}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $</p>\n\n<p>R.F of &nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{a} $ -&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{b} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{&nbsp;a^{2}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{ab} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{ b^{2}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $</p>\n', 'Rationalising Factor (R.F)', '', '<h3><strong>Rationalising Factor (R.F):</strong></h3>\n\n<p>If the product of two surds is a rational number then each of the two is the rationalising factor(R.F)of the other.</p>\n\n<pre>\n<em>Note: R.F. of a given surd is not unique.</em></pre>\n\n<p>R.F of&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ +$ \\sqrt{b} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ -&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $</p>\n\n<p>R.F of&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ -&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;$ \\sqrt{a} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $</p>\n\n<p>R.F of &nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{a} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{b} $ &nbsp;is&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{&nbsp;a^{2} &nbsp;} $ -&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{ab} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{ b^{2}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $</p>\n\n<p>R.F of &nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{a} $ -&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{b} $ &nbsp;is &nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{&nbsp;a^{2}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{ab} $ +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{ b^{2}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $</p>\n', 0, 0),
(135, 'inline_html', '<p><strong>Exponent:</strong></p>\n\n<p>A number is multiplied by itself again and again (repeatedly) , it can be written in a short form in exponential or power notation.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$ a^{n} $ = a x a x a x a x.............a(n-times); &nbsp; a- integer</p>\n\n<p>Here</p>\n\n<p><em>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; a&nbsp;</em>&nbsp;is called base and&nbsp;<em>n</em>&nbsp;is called power or exponent or index</p>\n\n<p><strong>Laws of exponents for Real Numbers&nbsp;</strong>:</p>\n\n<p>1) Product of Powers:</p>\n\n<p>$ a^{m} $.$ a^{n} $ =&nbsp;$ a^{m+n} $</p>\n\n<p>2) Power of Power:</p>\n\n<p>$ (&nbsp;a^{m} )^{n} $ =&nbsp;$ a^{mn} $</p>\n\n<p>3)Quotient of Power :</p>\n\n<p>$ \\frac{&nbsp;a^{m} }{&nbsp;a^{n} } $ =&nbsp;$ a^{m-n} $ &nbsp; if m &gt; n</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; =1 &nbsp;if m = n</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; =&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{&nbsp;a^{n-m} } $ if m &lt; n</p>\n\n<p>4)&nbsp;$ a^{m} $$ b^{m} $ &nbsp;=&nbsp;$ (ab)^{m} $</p>\n\n<p>5)&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{&nbsp;a^{n}&nbsp;} $ =&nbsp;$ a^{-n} $</p>\n\n<p>6)&nbsp;$ a^{0} $ = 1 , a$ \\neq $0</p>\n\n<p>7) If &nbsp;$ a^{n} $ =&nbsp;$ b^{n} $ , then a = b</p>\n\n<p>8)&nbsp;If &nbsp;$ a^{m} $ =&nbsp;$ a^{n} $ , then m = n &nbsp; &nbsp;if a$ \\neq $0</p>\n\n<p><strong>Note</strong>&nbsp;:&nbsp;$ \\frac{0}{0} $ ,&nbsp;&nbsp; $ 0^{0} $ are indeterminate&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Exponents Of Real Numbers', '', '<p><strong>Exponent:</strong></p>\n\n<p>A number is multiplied by itself again and again (repeatedly) , it can be written in a short form in exponential or power notation.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$ a^{n} $ = a x a x a x a x.............a(n-times); &nbsp; a- integer</p>\n\n<p>Here</p>\n\n<p><em>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; a&nbsp;</em>&nbsp;is called base and&nbsp;<em>n</em>&nbsp;is called power or exponent or index</p>\n\n<p><strong>Laws of exponents for Real Numbers&nbsp;</strong>:</p>\n\n<p>1) Product of Powers:</p>\n\n<p>$ a^{m} $.$ a^{n} $ =&nbsp;$ a^{m+n} $</p>\n\n<p>2) Power of Power:</p>\n\n<p>$ (&nbsp;a^{m} )^{n} $ =&nbsp;$ a^{mn} $</p>\n\n<p>3)Quotient of Power :</p>\n\n<p>$ \\frac{&nbsp;a^{m} }{&nbsp;a^{n} } $ =&nbsp;$ a^{m-n} $ &nbsp; if m &gt; n</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; =1 &nbsp;if m = n</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; =&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{&nbsp;a^{n-m} } $ if m &lt; n</p>\n\n<p>4)&nbsp;$ a^{m} $$ b^{m} $ &nbsp;=&nbsp;$ (ab)^{m} $</p>\n\n<p>5)&nbsp;$ \\frac{1}{&nbsp;a^{n}&nbsp;} $ =&nbsp;$ a^{-n} $</p>\n\n<p>6)&nbsp;$ a^{0} $ = 1 , a$ \\neq $0</p>\n\n<p>7) If &nbsp;$ a^{n} $ =&nbsp;$ b^{n} $ , then a = b</p>\n\n<p>8)&nbsp;If &nbsp;$ a^{m} $ =&nbsp;$ a^{n} $ , then m = n &nbsp; &nbsp;if a$ \\neq $0</p>\n\n<p><strong>Note</strong>&nbsp;:&nbsp;$ \\frac{0}{0} $ ,&nbsp;&nbsp; $ 0^{0} $ are indeterminate&nbsp;</p>\n', 0, 0),
(136, 'inline_html', '<p><strong>Surd:</strong></p>\n\n<p>If n is a positive integer and a rational number &nbsp;a(&gt;0) is not the $ n^{th} $ &nbsp;power of any other rational number , then&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ or&nbsp;$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n} &nbsp;} $ is called a &#39;surd&#39; or &#39;radical&#39; of order n.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Here &#39;a&#39; is called radicand&nbsp;.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{} $ is called radical sign</p>\n\n<p>n is called the degree of radical .</p>\n\n<p>$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $ is called an exponential form</p>\n\n<p>$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ is called radical form of surd.</p>\n\n<p>Ex :&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{2} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{3} $ ,&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{9} $ ,..... etc.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\sqrt{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\pi &nbsp; } $ is not a surd , since&nbsp;$ \\pi $ &nbsp;is an irrational number.</p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.6em">&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{&nbsp;a^{n} &nbsp;} $ = a</span></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;If two surds a +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $ = c&nbsp;+&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{d} $ then&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; a = c and b = d</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ X&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{b} $ =&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a*b} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\sqrt[n]{a} }{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\sqrt[n]{b} } $ =&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{&nbsp;\\frac{a}{b} &nbsp;} $ where b$ \\neq $0</p>\n\n<p><strong>N th root of Real &nbsp;Number:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Let a&gt;0 be a real number and &#39;n&#39; be a positive integer. If&nbsp;$ b^{n} $ = a, for some positive real number &#39;b&#39; ,then bis called n th root of &#39;a&#39; and we write&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ = b</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; i.e.&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ = b &nbsp;; b =&nbsp;$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n} &nbsp;} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 'Surds', '', '<p><strong>Surd:</strong></p>\n\n<p>If n is a positive integer and a rational number &nbsp;a(&gt;0) is not the $ n^{th} $ &nbsp;power of any other rational number , then&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ or&nbsp;$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n} &nbsp;} $ is called a &#39;surd&#39; or &#39;radical&#39; of order n.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Here &#39;a&#39; is called radicand&nbsp;.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{} $ is called radical sign</p>\n\n<p>n is called the degree of radical .</p>\n\n<p>$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n}&nbsp;&nbsp;} $ is called an exponential form</p>\n\n<p>$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ is called radical form of surd.</p>\n\n<p>Ex :&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{2} $ ,&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{3} $ ,&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[3]{9} $ ,..... etc.</p>\n\n<p>$ \\sqrt{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\pi &nbsp; } $ is not a surd , since&nbsp;$ \\pi $ &nbsp;is an irrational number.</p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.6em">&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{&nbsp;a^{n} &nbsp;} $ = a</span></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;If two surds a +&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{b} $ = c&nbsp;+&nbsp;$ \\sqrt{d} $ then&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; a = c and b = d</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ X&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{b} $ =&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a*b} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;$ \\frac{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\sqrt[n]{a} }{&nbsp;&nbsp;\\sqrt[n]{b} } $ =&nbsp;&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{&nbsp;\\frac{a}{b} &nbsp;} $ where b$ \\neq $0</p>\n\n<p><strong>N th root of Real &nbsp;Number:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Let a&gt;0 be a real number and &#39;n&#39; be a positive integer. If&nbsp;$ b^{n} $ = a, for some positive real number &#39;b&#39; ,then bis called n th root of &#39;a&#39; and we write&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ = b</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; i.e.&nbsp;$ \\sqrt[n]{a} $ = b &nbsp;; b =&nbsp;$ a^{&nbsp;\\frac{1}{n} &nbsp;} $</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 0, 0),
